<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Cooperatives     05-25 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Cooperatives,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy List of Amendments Slows Cooperative Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Parliament on Wednesday put off voting
on a progressive tax on people who work for private cooperatives, a
key element of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   Such a move by the Supreme Soviet, which normally approves laws
that have been put forward by the ruling Communist Party, is very
unusual. It may reflect concern about the contents of the law as
well as a greater willingness to speak out under Gorbachev's policy
of greater openness.
   The two chambers of the Supreme Soviet, the nominal parliament,
met in separate sessions Wednesday to debate the law, scheduled to
go into effect on July 1.
   The law also guarantees that cooperatives' property will not be
seized by the government.
   Officials have said the aim of the progressive tax system on
income earned by individuals who work in cooperatives is to get the
cooperatives to invest in expanding their businesses rather than
paying high salaries to workers.
   Gorbachev has pushed cooperatives as a method of augmenting the
state-run economy, which cannot provide enough consumer goods and
services.
   Soviet Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov said in a speech to the opening
session of the Supreme Soviet on Tuesday that the law was of
``immense social and political significance.''
   He said the cooperative system ``in a short time can solve the
most severe problems of perestroika (restructuring), the demand of
the population for goods and services.''
   The cooperative law was to have been brought before a joint
meeting of the Supreme Soviet on Wednesday, but officials at the
meeting said 22 parliamentarians spoke about the law in meetings of
the separate chambers Wednesday morning and that it was delayed
while a commission looked at a series of proposed amendments.
   Officials at the Supreme Soviet meeting gave no details of the
issues under debate, but the Tass news agency said in a report that
``judging by the deputies' remarks, the new edition of the law has
caused no objections of principle, while the amendments suggested
are dictated by the desire to protect cooperatives from unfounded
interference by local authorities.''
   ``Groundless limitations are introduced in many places, often
under the pretext of attempts to keep workers from leaving state
enterprises,'' Tass said. ``Another reason behind the limitations
is the bigoted idea that a cooperative is something to be looked
down at.''
   It said other problems facing cooperatives are the difficulty of
obtaining supplies and the system of taxation.
   Ryzhkov said Tuesday that 6,000 cooperatives had been formed in
the previous three months while the new law was being debated,
while a total of 14,000 had been formed in 18 months.
   Restaurants are one of the most popular forms of cooperatives
that have opened, and others have formed to make clothing, pump
gas, do apartment repairs and provide other services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
