<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CaliforniaSenate     05-25 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California Senate,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pete Wilson Eyes `Jinx'; McCarthy Hoping for Upset</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy is
trailing in the polls and in fund raising, but he has one thing in
his favor as he seeks to unseat Republican Sen. Pete Wilson this
year _ ``The Jinx.''
   For more than 30 years, no one has been re-elected to the Senate
seat Wilson holds. Incumbents have died, stepped down or been
defeated and descended into political oblivion. By contrast,
Democrat Alan Cranston is flourishing in his fourth term holding
down the state's other seat.
   ``Everybody talks about `The Jinx,''' said Craig Schmidt, a
Wilson aide. ``But this is the year `The Jinx' will be broken.''
Wilson, not surprisingly, agrees: ``I think it's nonsense, a myth.
We're going to prove it's not true.'
   The question of whether unlucky tradition will prevail may be
the most exciting thing about the race, which is generally viewed
as a showdown between two competent, conventional and largely
colorless politicians.
   Both men are youthful-looking, clean-cut candidates, with
reputations for personal honesty, and are perceived as moderates in
their respective parties.
   McCarthy, 57, a former San Francisco County supervisor who spent
14 years in the Legislature, including six years as Assembly
speaker, is expected to have no trouble defeating two little-known
challengers in the June 7 Democratic primary: Robert J. Banuelos, a
communications consultant from Orange, and Charles Greene of Los
Angeles.
   Wilson, 54-year-old former mayor of San Diego, is unopposed for
the GOP nomination.
   Since January 1987, Wilson has raised $4.7 million and spent
about $4 million, while McCarthy has raised $2.4 million and spent
$1.7 million. Both candidates say about 80 percent of their funds
will be used to buy television advertising, a critical resource in
this vast state which comprises 10 percent of the nation's
population.
   ``We've spent the recesses and the weekends campaigning,''
Wilson said in an interview earlier this month, perched on the rear
seat of a minivan zipping along Interstate 5. ``We've been out
virtually every weekend ... but it's literally impossible for me to
meet everybody.'' In one recent campaign swing, Wilson hit 13
cities in three days, targeting growers and business groups, while
McCarthy has been on the road with a no-frills whistle-stop-style
campaign from a motorhome.
   McCarthy said he has used the lieutenant governor's position to
push legislation for health care for the elderly, nursing home
improvements and child care programs. ``I think the elderly see me
as their No. 1 champion. This is a very significant area of
strength for me. This is something everyone concedes.
   ``But I don't exaggerate the power inherent in the lieutenant
governor's office,'' McCarthy added. ``I received far more media
attention when I was Assembly speaker.''
   The most recent statewide survey of California voters, a May 11
poll by the Gallup Organization, showed Wilson with a 21-point lead
over McCarthy, 51 percent to 30 percent, with 19 percent undecided.
   McCarthy, however, dismisses the polls, contending they largely
reflect Wilson's television advertising campaign.
   Since those polls, McCarthy received more bad news when a
phalanx of Hollywood film moguls, eight powerful studio chiefs,
endorsed Wilson. The studio bosses included several prominent
Democrats.
   McCarthy belittled the significance of the May 2 endorsements,
saying that such stars Morgan Fairchild, Jack Lemmon, Bruce Willis
and Warren Beatty remained loyal to him.
   At issue is a U.S. Senate seat that has traded hands
continuously since the 1950s.
   Moderate Democrat Clair Engle, who won the seat in 1958, died in
office, and John F. Kennedy's former press secretary, Pierre
Salinger, was appointed to complete his term.
   Salinger lost his 1964 election bid to Hollywood song-and-dance
man George Murphy, a conservative Republican who in turn was
defeated in 1970 by John Tunney, a Democrat and the son of boxer
Gene Tunney.
   In 1976, Tunney was defeated by former San Francisco State
University President S.I. Hayakawa, an acid-tongued, articulate
semanticist known for his hard-line approach to student protesters.
   In 1982, faced with week standings in the polls, Hayakawa
retired and was succeeded by Wilson.
</TEXT>
