<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     05-25 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Hulk' Wins Ratings Battle with `Baby M'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC racked up another win in the Nielsens thanks
to two ratings ``hulks'' _ one Lou Ferrigno and the other Bob Hope.
   ``The Incredible Hulk Returns,'' a reunion movie starring Bill
Bixby and Ferrigno as, respectively, a professor and his violent
alter ego, ranked fourth in the weekly Nielsens with a rating of
20.2 and a 33 share. Hope's special celebration of 50 years of
association with NBC finished in sixth with an 19.0 and 31.
   And NBC may have solved its Wednesday night ratings with an
``Unsolved Mysteries'' special that was also in the top 10 in the
A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings, at ninth, and is due to become a regular
weekly fixture in the fall.
   ABC's ``Baby M'' was no match for ``Hulk'' in a three-way
made-for-TV movie battle on Sunday. Part one of the two-parter
starring JoBeth Williams as Mary Beth Whitehead Gould had a 15.0
rating and 24 share and ranked 17th for the week.
   CBS came in third with ``My Father, My Son,'' starring Karl
Malden and Keith Carradine as Adm. Elmo Zumwalt and his son. It had
a 13.5 rating and 22 share and ranked 21st.
   NBC won the week that ended Sunday with an average, prime-time
rating of 15.3. ABC was second with 11.6.
   CBS' 10.7 was its lowest weekly rating this season. Last week
was part of the important May sweeps, one of the four months a year
when television ratings companies measure viewership in local
markets. But with only a few days to go, CBS was second to NBC in
sweeps competition.
   NBC's average since the beginning of the season stands at 15.8.
ABC has 13.5 and CBS 13.2.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's estimated 88.6
million households with televisions. The share is a percentage of
sets in use.
   The top 10-rated shows of the week were: ``The Cosby Show'' NBC,
``A Different World'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC, ``The Incredible Hulk
Returns'' NBC, ``Night Court'' NBC, ``Bob Hope's Birthday'' NBC,
``Golden Girls'' NBC, ``60 Minutes'' CBS, ``Unsolved Mysteries''
NBC,'' and ``The American Comedy Awards'' ABC.
   The lowest-rated, prime-time shows were: ``Eisenhower & Lutz''
tied with ``Full House,'' ``Perfect Strangers,'' ``Garfield's 10th
Anniversary,'' ``Beryl Markham, Part 2,'' ``Tour of Duty,'' ``Meet
the Munceys,'' ``High Mountain Rangers,'' ``M&W Magazine,''
``Probe'' and ``Our House.''
   NBC remained third in the news race but closed the gap somewhat.
For the week that ended Friday, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was
first for the fourth week in a row, finishing with an average
rating of 9.5 and a 20 share. The ``CBS Evening News'' had a 9.2
and a 19 share. ``NBC Nightly News'' had an 8.8 and 19 share.
</TEXT>
