<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AncientRoad     05-25 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ancient Road,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ancient Route to China Is Busy Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TASHKARGAN, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ancient road traveled by the likes
of Genghis Khan, Marco Polo and Babur has become an active artery
of commerce today between China and Pakistan.
   More than 2,000 years ago, silk and spices made their way out of
China on the route, while gold, silver and wool made their way in.
   The commerce today is considerably more diverse, if not as
exotic.
   As many as 80 Pakistani merchants travel the road into China
each day in battered buses to buy silk, porcelain and pearls, and
Chinese businessmen head in the opposite direction toward the
Khunjerab Pass on the border as part of a barter arrangement
between the two countries.
   The barter enables the Chinese to trade hydroelectric equipment,
farm tools, textiles, quilts and porcelain for Pakistani
cigarettes, medical herbs, dried fruits, shoes and razor blades.
   The volume of official barter has increased to the equivalent of
$3 million in the past year, compared to $300,000 in 1986,
according to Sadeq Malek, sales officer of Pakistan's Northern
Areas Traders Cooperatives.
   The road also is being traveled more and more by tourists.
   From Pakistan's border post of Sost the road follows the Hunza
River, then runs along the icy Khunjerab River into China, crossing
numerous glaciers. As it climbs to the Khunjerab Pass, it goes
through a series of narrow chasms and steep declines.
   At Tashkargan, the first Chinese town across the border, workmen
are building hotels and inns to accommodate the growing number of
travelers passing through.
   Kamel Tahsin, manager of the government-run Pamir Hotel in
Tashkargan, said the new hotels will be more modern and better
equipped.
   ``Business is getting better,'' he said. ``So we have to add a
couple of wings to our hotel.''
   Tahsin is one of about 12,000 people in Tashkargan who are
Shiite Moslem Tajiks, the tribe dominant in the area. They are
distinguishable by their sharp features and their women by their
colorful costume.
   Across the border in Sost, Pakistanis also are building to meet
the growing flow of tourists.
   Assif Khan, a Pakistani government tourist official, said big
tour groups now travel to China four times a month compared to
twice a month a year ago.
   But it's a tough road to travel, says Amanollah Mogul, the bus
driver who makes the journey about once a day back and forth to
China.
   The Khunjerab Pass, he said, makes him dizzy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Gardening     05-25 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Gardening,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Peak Week For Britain's Passionate Gardeners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY C. WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horticulturists from China, garden club members
from Biggleswade and window-box farmers from the inner city
clutched their coveted tickets Tuesday for the Chelsea Flower Show,
which has sprouted along the River Thames this week like a promise
of summer.
   On the sun-dappled lawns beside the red-brick Royal Hospital are
displayed the very best roses, dahlias, pansies and delphiniums
that this nation of gardeners can produce.
   So great are the crowds at Britain's most prestigious annual
garden extravaganza that the Royal Horticultural Society limited
ticket sales for the four-day trade show to 45,000 per day _ at $26
each _ and may have to move to a larger site next year.
   Last year, 243,000 people crowded onto the 19-acre site, most of
them milling under the 3{-acre marquee that covers the choicest
displays.
   Members of the 84-year-old society, which has sponsored the
Chelsea show since 1913, have their own viewing days, as does Queen
Elizabeth II.
   Membership in the society is 110,000 and growing, said assistant
secretary Stephen Bennett. Most are Britons, but there are many
American members and a Japanese branch has just begun.
   More leisure time and income have boosted the growth of
gardening, Bennett said.
   ``But the most important thing is there are no social
barriers,'' he said. ``At the show, you'll see dowagers and dustmen
(garbage collectors) talking about the same thing.''
   Gardening in Britain is the closest thing to a universal
interest, not counting curiosity about the royal family.
   Five weekly TV and radio programs are devoted to gardening, and
the British Broadcasting Corp.'s 13-part series, ``The Victorian
Kitchen Garden,'' was such a hit last year that it's already being
repeated.
   It is difficult to imagine another country where a half hour of
prime time television would be devoted to the growing of tomatoes
or methods of repelling slugs; where a person alarmed by clematis
wilt can telephone an expert on TV and get immediate help; or where
three wry horticulturists could become national celebrities through
their radio question-and-answer show.
   Some city-dwellers nurturing pots of herbs on the windowsill or
geraniums on the roof terrace dream of the gardening opportunities
in the countryside. But even in London, most people have access to
a bit of grass and soil and just about all of them plant something
in it.
   Because most of central London's dwellings are rowhouses, there
are thousands of narrow back gardens, neatly fenced and stretching
to meet an identical row of gardens from the houses on the next
street.
   The English rose, honeysuckle, ivy, jasmine and purple wisteria
climb the fences and camouflage the garden sheds. Lilacs, plum
trees, lavender and foxgloves fill the borders _ often leaving just
enough grass to warrant a push mower.
   Even in the teeming center of the city, there often is a garden
in the back and a cat lying in the sun. No upstanding neighborhood
pub is without its windowbox of ivy and geraniums.
   The 18 garden club members on a Chevron North Sea oil platform
never have to worry about slugs and aphids, although space is
limited in their 10 foot by 8 foot greenhouse bolted to the deck,
100 miles off the Shetland Islands, northeast of Scotland.
   ``You get a great feeling of satisfaction when you sit down to a
fresh tomato sprinkled with chopped basil, knowing you've grown
them both,'' rig electrician Malcolm Dobinson told The Daily Mail.
   Thousands of Londoners work allotments, patches of public land
rented for a few pounds a year to families who want to grow their
own food.
   ``We got 60 pounds of strawberries off the allotment last
year,'' said Ena Mundy, who's been attending the Chelsea show for
30 years.
   She and her husband travel 18 miles twice a week to their
allotment because the soil is ``lovely rich and loamy. Now we're
retired, it's our main interest,'' she said.
   Outer London's Barnet borough has 250 acres in allotments, each
10 yards by 30 yards.
   Most of these amateur gardeners would probably agree with writer
Alan Titchmarsh who told an interviewer: ``There's really nowhere
else in the world I'd rather be than in my garden. When my time
comes I'd be happy to peg out there. An epitaph? Gone to Make
Manure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
