<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristmasCard     05-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christmas Card,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Card Mailed 17 Years Ago Returned To Sender</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 17 years after Wilda Richardson
mailed a Christmas card to an acquaintance, the post office
returned it, unopened.
   But Mrs. Richardson wasn't upset.
   ``I'm sure that whatever happened was an accident,'' she said.
``I'm sure the post office tries their best not to let this kind of
thing happen.''
   The card, mailed Dec. 22, 1970, showed up mysteriously last week
marked ``return to sender.'' It was intended for Mildred Mealor, a
fellow member of the Pilot Club International, who has since died.
   In 1970, Mrs. Richardson was executive director of the service
club for business and professional women. Each year, she mailed
hundreds of homemade Christmas cards to friends and club chapters
across the country.
   The card came back with a May 18 postmark from Gainesville and a
May 19 postmark from Macon. It was not delivered postage due, even
though it bore a 6-cent stamp.
   Mrs. Richardson, 84, said she has mailed so many Christmas cards
that she had no idea this one never reached its destination.
   No one knows where the card spent the last 17{ years.
Gainesville Postmaster Larry Latimer was baffled.
   ``If it was found in my post office, I'm sure I would have heard
about it. Given the size of our office, it's hard to imagine it
lying around for 18 years,'' Latimer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
