<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-25 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTHBORO, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call him persistent, call him tenacious,
or call him what co-workers at a computer company dubbed him after
a three-year struggle to rid the plant grounds of geese: ``Mr.
Goosebuster.''
   Norm Heifetz, 52, facilities manager of the Bytex Corp., has
become a minor celebrity. Employees presented him with a ``Mr.
Goosebuster'' plaque and goosebuster emblems can be spotted
throughout the company, Heifetz said. Heifetz' picture even
appeared on the front page of a local newspaper.
   His fame came after he waged war with the pesky geese, which
filled the man-made pond at the plant and, even worse, ``strolled
all over the grounds.''
   ``They come and proliferate and have babies and they make a holy
mess of the property,'' he said. ``They like young, fresh grass so
they go grazing all day long. It wouldn't have been so bad if they
stayed out back but they came strolling on the sidewalk near the
front entrance.''
   At first, he banged pots and pans to frighten the geese away.
Then, while researching the problem, he learned that geese are
``deathly afraid of swans'' and bought ``a bunch of fake ones.''
   Nothing worked.
   Last year, when the geese returned in late spring, Heifetz began
a new plan of attack. He wired up huge speakers and blared distress
calls over the pond. Still, the geese remained.
   Then Heifetz tried a small, remote-controlled boat. Success at
last.
   ``It made a terrible noise and chased them out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man's toothless technique earned him a
clam-eating contest victory and possible world record as he downed
397 of the mollusks in eight minutes.
   Dave Barnes of Sequim, a roofer who has been eating the bivalves
in competition for 16 years, already holds the record listed in the
``Guinness Book of World Records'' of 424 clams in eight minutes.
   That record, set in 1975 at Port Townsend, included a one-minute
break in the contest. Tuesday's eating of steamed clams, sponsored
by Ivar's Acres of Clams restaurant on Seattle's waterfront, was
non-stop. Contest spokesman Barry Bartlett said Barnes' performance
also will be submitted to the record book.
   Barnes said he had an advantage over competitors: He took out
his false teeth and let the clams slide down unobstructed.
   In second place was Glen Jones of Kent, who ate 306 clams.
   The 12 contestants downed a total of 2,615 steamed clams.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
