<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Homework     05-25 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Homework,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Government Limits Homework, Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government took pity on primary and middle
school students who complain of too much homework and testing by
setting strict limits on both, an official report said today.
   The English-language China Daily said the State Education
Commission banned homework for first-grade pupils and set graduated
limits for older students.
   The limits range from 30 minutes a day for second- and
third-grade students to an hour daily for sixth-grade pupils, the
report said. It did not say what the average length of assignments
had been.
   The panel also said pupils ``should not be given the kind of
homework that requires heavy monotonous routine work, such as large
amounts of copying drills.'' Rote drilling has been the basic
method of education in China for centuries.
   High schools will be allowed to hold major exams only in key
subjects and only at the middle and end of terms, the commission
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
