<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0716 05-25 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Criticizes Trade Bill Veto; Bush Aides Reassure House GOP
Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Idaho results</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis said Tuesday it was ``a
very serious mistake'' for President Reagan to veto trade
legislation that requires advance notice of plant closing. George
Bush's aides sought to reassure House Republicans about the vice
president's poor standing in recent polls.
   ``We have bad polls,'' Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois said after
attending a closed-door session with Bush's top advisers. ``If this
were October we'd be suicidal. But it's May.''
   Jesse Jackson, Dukakis' sole remaining Democratic rival,
campaigned in California in advance of the state's June 7 primary.
He said he would seek government assistance for a farm town where a
dozen children have been diagnosed with cancer in recent years.
   Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis spent most of the day in Boston,
where he issued a statement blasting Reagan and Bush on the trade
bill and linking the veto to negotiations with Panama's Manuel
Noriega, who faces indictment on drug charges.
   ``Any administration that is willing to give Gen. Noriega 120
days notice and a plea bargain ought to be willing to give the
American worker 60 days notice before they are thrown out on the
street,'' he said in a statement.
   Bush declared his independence from Reagan on the Noriega talks
last week, saying he opposed negotiations designed to force the
Panamanian leader to give up his power in exchange for having the
drug indictments dropped.
   The vice president had no official appearances during the day,
although he added Idaho to his list of primary state victories.
With a quarter of the precincts reporting, Bush had 81 percent to
10 percent for Pat Robertson, who suspended his Republican
candidacy earlier this month.
   Bush was winning 15 delegates in Idaho, to two for Robertson,
and one uncommitted. The vice president wrapped up a majority of
Republican National Convention delegates a month ago.
   The Democratic primary in Idaho was a non-binding preference
poll and no delegates were at stake. Dukakis won easily, with 77
percent to Jackson's 14 percent, with 24 percent of the precincts
reporting.
   The next _ and last _ Democratic primary elections will be June
7, with contests in California, New Jersey, New Mexico and Montana.
   Although neither Bush nor Dukakis was out campaigning during the
day, each took steps to rally the troops around their certain
candidacies.
   The vice president's campaign officials announced that Sen.
Charles Grassley and Gov. Terry Branstad would play important roles
in the fall campaign in Iowa. Grassley was a staunch supporter of
Sen. Bob Dole in the state's heated caucus campaign _ which Bush
lost in a third place finish _ while Branstad was neutral.
   On the Democratic side, Dukakis arranged a visit to Washington
on Wednesday en route to campaigning in California. His aides said
he would meet with several groups of House members and senators,
and expected to pick up endorsements from roughly a dozen lawmakers
as he closes in on a nominating majority of Democratic National
Convention delegates.
   Three top Bush advisers met with House Republicans, and one of
them, pollster Robert Teeter, said polls indicate the vice
president is running behind but the race is in a ``very artificial
period.'' He said he told the lawmakers that, ``What you got to do
is get past this California primary before people begin to focus on
it (the presidential race).''
   Several lawmakers said Bush's decision to disagree with Reagan's
policy of negotiations with Noriega drew praise.
   ``It's a very symbolic circumstance, where Bush has moved from
being vice president to being his own candidate,'' said Rep. Jim
Leach of Iowa.
   Ms. Martin added, ``Almost to a person, they were pleased about
the separation on Noriega.;''
   But she also said there was concern about recent polls
indicating Dukakis leads the vice president. ``There wasn't anybody
up screaming, `My God, we've got the Titanic,''' she said.
   Dukakis' linkage of the trade bill veto with the Noriega
negotiations marked an attempt to hit Bush on two issues that
Democratic strategists believe damage the vice president.
   ``To veto this bill because it will give working people and
their families 60 days notice before they're laid off, seems to me
to be unconscionable,'' he said.
   He said Reagan and Bush ``don't understand that for working
families who struggle to pay the mortgage, save for their
children's education and care for their elders, there is nothing
more painful than losing a job.''
   ``I think the president is making a very serious mistake. This
is a good trade bill. It's a responsible bill,'' he said.
</TEXT>
