<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0815,0232</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds Vartan. No separates moved for the AMs cycle.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>William Bougher</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William George Bougher, a retired
electronics engineer who helped develop radar in the United States
before the nation entered World War II, died Friday of cancer. He
was 69.
   Bougher adapted the British system of providing early warning
against approaching enemy aircraft to America's defense network
when he started working for the Bendix Corp. in Baltimore in 1940.
   After the war he joined Philco Corp. in Philadelphia as a
technical representative at military installations and last worked
for the company at the Mare Island Naval Shipyard in Vallejo in
1948.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Vartanig Vartan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vartanig G. Vartan, a financial writer for The
New York Times and the author of two novels, died Tuesday of cancer
at age 64.
   Vartan worked for United Press from 1952 to 1955 in New York and
was a financial writer with The New York Herald Tribune from 1955
to 1962. He also worked as a Wall Street columnist for The
Christian Science Monitor from 1957 to 1962.
   Vartan joined the Times in 1963 as a financial writer. He was
the main writer of the ``Market Place'' column in the newspaper
since 1983.
   Vartan wrote two novels, ``50 Wall Street'' and ``The Dinosaur
Fund.''
</TEXT>
