<HEAD>Arms And Drugs Smugglers Arrested In Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian security forces smashed several
gangs smuggling arms and narcotics, Iran said.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said on Tuesday that
30 ``armed highway bandits'' were arrested in Tehran, Tabriz and
Khorramabad for smuggling drugs and selling weapons to
``counterrevolutionaries.''
   The report, monitored in Nicosia, said 12 members of an
underground group were arrested in Tehran, Tabriz and other cities
for selling arms to dissident groups and procuring forged passports
and visas for Iranians, including draft dodgers, seeking to flee
the country.
   Thirty members of a group of ``well-educated professionals''
were rounded up in Tehran, Tabriz and other towns for coating
metals with a thin layer of gold and selling them as pure gold, the
agency said.
   In East Azarbaijan Province, customs men seized 146 precious
silk carpets that were to be smuggled abroad, the agency added. The
security operations were carried out over the last few days, IRNA
reported.
