<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Queen     05-25 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Queen,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Queen Elizabeth Attends 250th Anniversary Celebration Of Methodism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II joined 2,500 people in a
service at St. Paul's Cathedral celebrating the 250th anniversary
of the religious movement that grew into the Methodist Church.
   The interdenominational service on Tuesday, which was attended
by represenatives of 50 nations, commemorated John Wesley's
conversion at a Christian meeting in London on May 24, 1738.
   The fiery preacher traveled by horseback through the English
countryside spreading the gospel with his hymn-writing brother,
Charles.
   Their followers separated from the state Church of England and
established Methodism after John Wesley's death in 1791.
   Queen Elizabeth is the titular head of the Church of England,
and her presence at the service was seen as a gesture acknowledging
the contribution of the Methodist Church to British life.
   She was accompanied by her husband, Prince Philip.
</TEXT>
