<DOCNO> AP880525-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DukakisPay     05-25 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis Pay,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Lets Traveling Governor Keep All His Salary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis has survived a Republican
attempt to scale back his pay to reflect the days he spends in his
Statehouse office and not on the presidential campaign trail.
   Late Tuesday, after nearly 10 hours of debate over next year's
state budget, Republican Rep. Kevin Poirier offered an amendment to
the $1,888,828 intended to pay the governor and his staff.
   Under the language offered by Poirier, Dukakis would get paid
only for days he is in the state.
   Since the start of this year, Poirier noted, the governor has
spent 68 days out of state, 18 days in state and 51 days in which
he spent part of the day here and part elsewhere.
   ``So therefore, for the 68 days he was out of the state, based
on his salary of $85,000, he owes us $15,835,'' the assistant
minority leader said.
   ``With this amendment, what I'm trying to do is bring some
fiscal sanity back into the commonwealth. We do have a fiscal
crisis. Let's try to address it in his office,'' he said.
   No Democrat rose to defend the governor, but the amendment was
defeated on a voice vote.
</TEXT>
