<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     05-25 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Lawyers Fight Efforts to Use Congressional Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense lawyers are accusing independent
counsel Lawrence E. Walsh of trying to punish former White House
aide Oliver L. North and two co-defendants for trying to tell
Congress the ``whole truth'' about the Iran-Contra affair.
   The defense contends that Walsh was ``completely wrong on the
law'' by claiming that hundreds of statements that North, former
national security adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealer Albert
Hakim made to Congress could be used against them as evidence of
criminal wrongdoing.
   By claiming the defendants waived their limited immunity grants
from Congress, Walsh ``seeks to punish defendants for responding
fully and in good faith to congressional inquiries, when compelled
to do so over vehement objection, and for relaying to Congress and
the nation what occurred and why,'' the defense said in a brief
filed Tuesday.
   Although North, Poindexter and Hakim testified under immunity
grants that prohibit use of their statements as evidence against
them, Walsh contends that the defendants waived the privilege
against self-incrimination by volunteering answers that were not
responsive to questions posed by the Iran-Contra committees.
   Walsh has said that he would not use any of this congressional
testimony during the trial if the court denies a defense request to
conduct an extensive hearing to determine if his investigation was
tainted by impermissible use of the defendants' immunized
statements.
   The defense called Walsh's offer an attempt ``to threaten the
court with a lengthy inquiry into immunized testimony, and then to
use that threat as leverage to strike a favorable bargain with the
court.''
   ``This tactic is unseemly,'' the defense lawyers said in a joint
pleading.
   North, the fired National Security Council aide, Poindexter and
Hakim are accused of conspiring with retired Air Force Maj. Gen.
Richard V. Secord to defraud the government by diverting Iran
arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels. Secord, also an arms
dealer, testified without an immunity grant from Congress.
   North, Poindexter and Hakim contend that their Fifth Amendment
right against self-incrimination would be violated if they were
forced to stand trial on criminal charges following their compelled
congressional testimony. They claim that Walsh's prosecution was
tainted by illegal use of their sworn statements to Congress.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell is scheduled to hear
arguments on the issue on Thursday.
   In its latest filing, the defense said ``there is no claim that
defendants uttered a single word, during the course of their
congressional testimony, that was outside the subject matter of the
congressional inquiry.''
   North, Poindexter and Hakim were not waiving any rights when
they ``explained their answers; or sought to provide useful,
related information to be sure their answers were complete and
accurate _ in short, the `whole truth' they had sworn to provide.''
   The defense said Walsh's position would force Gesell to examine
each and every one of the hundreds of statements to verify Walsh's
claim they were exempt from immunity.
   Walsh contended that the unprotected statements include
Poindexter's admission that he approved the diversion of arms-sale
profits to the Contras but did not tell President Reagan to ensure
that the president could deny involvement if the operation were
exposed.
   The unprotected statements also include Poindexter's remarks
that during Attorney General Edwin Meese III's November 1986
investigation, Poindexter destroyed a presidential intelligence
finding authorizing CIA involvement in one 1985 arms shipment,
Walsh contended.
   Walsh also claimed that North's statements that he destroyed
documents in October and November 1986 could be used as evidence to
prove charges that the fired National Security Council aide
obstructed Meese's inquiry.
   In a separate filing on Tuesday, Walsh's office said that ``it
is clear beyond doubt'' that North, Poindexter and Hakim waged a
``public relations battle'' during their congressional testimony.
   ``In utter defiance of the questions put to them, they sought to
win with speeches and arguments,'' the prosecution brief said.
</TEXT>
