<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TruckExplodes 1stLd-Writethru a0847 05-25 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Truck Explodes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0847,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Propane Tanker Burns on Long Island</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 1st graf that tanker burst into flames sted
exploded, UPDATES throughout with more homes evacuated, driver
arrested, amount of propane, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A propane tanker truck overturned, burst
into flames and burned intensely through the day Tuesday, forcing
police to close two highways, shut a section of the Long Island
Rail Road and evacuate 2,000 homes.
   There were no serious injuries, officials said. The driver and a
trainee who was riding with him escaped before the explosion. The
driver was treated at the scene for a shoulder cut.
   The fire was so intense and potentially explosive that
firefighters had to move back from the fire early in the afternoon,
leaving automatic pumpers to throw water on the blaze.
   Nearly 1,000 homes within half a mile of the burning truck were
evacuated, with residents taken to a church, Nassau County police
spokeswoman Officer Donna Fairweather said. Hank McCann, a
department public information officer, said more homes were
evacuated at 10:30 p.m. bringing the total to about 2,000.
``(Police) cars went through the area with loudspeakers urging
people to evacuate,'' he said.
   Two unmanned automatic fire trucks were pumping water onto the
fire late Tuesday night, hours after the 9:30 a.m. accident.
Authorities said the tanker, carrying about 2,500 gallons of
propane, could burn for as long as 30 hours.
   Sections of the Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway, where the
accident occurred, and the Sunrise Highway, near the expressway,
were closed, Fairweather said.
   The Long Island Rail Road twice suspended service on its busiest
branch, between Wantagh and Amityville, said railroad spokesman
Brian Dolan. He estimated that 70,000 train commuters were affected.
   County police Lt. Willard Krausch said the truck overturned on
the southbound lane of the expressway when the driver experienced a
problem with the truck's rear wheels.
   The driver, identified by police as Roger Vai, 35, of Westbury,
was arrested at the scene on an outstanding traffic warrant and was
also charged with driving with a suspended license and failure to
produce a license. He was taken later released on $100 bail.
   Krausch said the truck was owned by Conservative Gas of Hyde
Park.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Trade Bjt   05-25 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Trade, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Democrats Instantly Make Campaign Issue Of Veto</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after George Bush campaign aides tried
to explain to House Republicans when things would start going right
for the vice president, President Reagan vetoed a trade bill the
Democrats were itching to make an issue in the fall presidential
campaign.
   Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee-to-be,
fired off this response Tuesday when the president's veto message
reached Congress:
   ``Any administration that is willing to give General (Manuel)
Noriega 120 days notice and a plea bargain ought to be willing to
give the American worker 60 days notice before they are thrown out
on the street.''
   The Massachusetts governor was referring to the provision that
would require companies to give workers and communities notice
before closing plants.
   Reagan said he thought giving such notice was ``the humane thing
to do'' but he objected to making it mandatory.
   ``I don't really see it as a campaign issue,'' said Rep. Guy
Molinari. ``I could be wrong.''
   The chairman of the Bush campaign in New York, Molinari was one
of 60 Republicans who deserted the president and voted to override
the veto.
   The House voted 308-113 to override the veto, but Senate
Democratic leaders have predicted the president will prevail in
that chamber.
   The Democrats certainly are betting it will be an issue in the
fall campaign.
   ``I happen to think it's a better issue for the Democrats than
for the Republicans,'' said House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., asked, ``Why hand it to us on a silver platter?''
   Like the president, Bush appeared to be walking a narrow line on
the trade bill.
   During a recent campaign appearance, he even had kind words for
the Massachusetts plant closing law that Dukakis often cites.
   ``In Massachusetts, they have a plant closing law, it's
voluntary. It's not like the federal government imposing it,'' said
the vice president.
   Massachusetts law offers financial and management assistance to
companies and those that accept are then required to give 90 days
notice of plant closings.
   The trade bill veto came on the same day that Bush campaign
aides were getting encouragement from House Republicans for his
recent moves away from Reagan, specifically on the Noriega
negotiations.
   Disagreeing with the idea of dropping drug charges against the
military leader and de facto ruler of Panama is not a politically
high-risk move.
   Likewise, one must expect that if Attorney General Edwin Meese
III continues to cling to his job, Bush will begin to hint that he
thinks it's time for Meese to step aside.
   Bush doesn't need high-priced pollsters to tell him Noriega and
Meese aren't bringing him a lot of votes.
   But a far more critical question is how many general election
votes Ronald Reagan brings his vice president.
   Bush supporters in the House were sympathetic about the vice
president's plight.
   ``I think Bush has to say, as he has for seven years, as long as
we're asking what he would do as vice president, he will support
the president of the United States,'' said Rep. Newt Gingrich of
Georgia. ``He can talk about how he would take the offensive in '89
in other ways, but I think it would be very, very foolish to allow
himself to be drawn into day by day picky fights.''
   But others weren't so concerned about ``picky fights.''
   ``What I'd like to see would be Bush coming out on more of the
issues and articulating the positions that he has,'' said Molinari.
``I think he's beginning to do that now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
