<DOCNO> AP880525-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HairAndFigLeaves Bjt   05-25 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hair And Fig Leaves, Bjt,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Naked Truth Or Nakedness At U.N. `Hair' Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 20th anniversary production of
``Hair,'' the rock musical that shocked the world with frontal
nudity, will be shown in a demure version at a United Nations
benefit for children suffering from AIDS.
   Some say a show that celebrates carefree love and drug use is
not the best choice to raise money to fight AIDS, a fatal disease
transmitted by sexual contact and sharing of intravenous needles.
   The one-night presentation Thursday at the General Assembly Hall
has been watered down to avoid eliciting blushes from diplomats.
Four-letter words are edited out, free spirits will have to cover
themselves with fig leaves and there will be no burning of U.S.
draft cards.
   ``This is a modified version for the United Nations,'' one of
the creators, James Rado, said. ``The street language had to go in
a United Nations format. I guess they couldn't take the four-letter
words. There aren't that many of them.''
   ``But the U.N. just said `No,''' added co-author Gerome Ragni.
   At the end of the first act, the cast will not stand singing in
the nude before the audience. That was in 1968. This is a swishy,
black-tie affair for the Establishment where the best seats cost
$5,000.
   ``The first lady would say no to drug songs,'' production
manager David Bosboom said in an interview, referring to Nancy
Reagan's anti-drug campaign whose slogan is, ``Just say no to
drugs.''
   Mrs. Reagan, an honorary chairman of the benefit, will not be
present to hear the 1988 rendition of the songs ``Starshine'' and
the ``Age of Aquarius,'' although she consults astrologers.
President Reagan and his wife leave for the Moscow summit this
morning.
   Publicist Rebecca Robbins said that when ``Hair'' opened 20
years ago at New York's Public Theater the stars were in almost the
same positions as they will be Thursday.
   Wanda Moore, the original ``Hair'' astrologer who now calls
herself Vanessa Talma-Lord, has worked out the astrological chart
for the show.
   ``The moon again is in the seventh house and Jupiter is aligned
with Mars,'' said the astrologer.
   Bosboom quipped that ``There will be no naked truths here at the
U.N.,'' but that the soul of the show has remained intact.
   ``Yes, we had to change the content to suit the United
Nations,'' he said. ``The themes are there but some lyrics have
changed.''
   He said the numerous changes were made both out of
self-censorship by the creators and at the request of nervous U.N.
bureaucrats.
   One U.N. official muttered privately that the show was
``ill-considered, inappropriate and an embarrassment.
   ``How do you have a show celebrating free love and sex at the
United Nations, of all places, when you are trying to warn against
AIDS?'' said the official who demanded anonymity.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, also is
transmitted through contaminated blood or blood products and from
infected mothers to their unborn babies. The AIDS virus attacks the
body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and
cancers.
   Ragni and Rado have written 14 new songs and the first half of
the new prodution is an update ``for the next generation.'' The
second half is a nostalgic selection of oldies.
   ``Sodomy,'' a song from the original, won't be sung at
Thursday's production. It is now an instrumental by Chuck Mangione.
   ``Some of the songs we had to delete, because out of context
from the original show, they don't work,'' Ragni said in a recent
interview.
   Of ``Sodomy,'' he said: ``It's quite beautiful and effective and
I never had heard it as an instrumental.''
   The changes have been made to address current issues, such as
the depletion of the Ozone layer and banning nuclear bombs.
   Deletions do away with the Vietnam War hippie protest song about
LBJ taking the IRT to find people on LSD.
   But there still is crooning over ``Donna'' and the search for
the ``16-year-old virgin.''
   ``I'm surprised they left that one in,'' said Bosboom.
   The production involves more than 100 people and includes some
members of the original cast. A few of the original players decided
not to take part when they learned that conservative William F.
Buckley was a member of the sponsoring Creo Society. It is a
non-profit organization working with the United Nations Children's
Fund to help young AIDS victims.
   The Creo Society Fund For Children With AIDS is trying to raise
more than $2 million from the benefit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
