<DOCNO> AP880525-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO     05-25 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci To Discuss With NATO Ministers Sharing Cost Of Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci
and his European colleagues in NATO will discuss financial
contributions to the military alliance at a two-day meeting
scheduled to begin Thursday.
   The alliance's European defense ministers will gather today for
a routine meeting at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
   U.S. congressional critics of NATO claim the European NATO
nations don't pay enough for the common Western defense and have
threatened to withdraw some of the 320,000 American troops in
Europe.
   Such criticism has risen as constraints in the United States
budget get tighter.
   The European allies counter that most of the air, land and sea
forces of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization are European.
   ``It's a question of convincing (the U.S. Congress) that what
the Europeans do reflects a fair assumption ... of the common
defense burden,'' said a senior NATO official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said NATO ministers will set up a panel to review the
financial issue and hope to present a report by year's end.
   Carlucci will attend the meeting on his way to join President
Reagan at the Moscow summit.
   The NATO defense chiefs also will approve goals for each of the
16 members for 1989-1994, NATO officials said. The ministers were
expected to adopt 26 long-term force goals, 23 of these dealing
with planning for arms systems to be operational by the late 1990s.
   The ministers also will consider a multinational force to offset
Canada's decision to end the commitment of its Air-Sea
Transportable brigade to reinforce northern Norway in times of
crisis, the officials said.
   Canada announced a year ago that it would end its commitment in
order to consolidate its forces in West Germany.
   The NATO ministers were expected to ask Italy to take in 72 U.S.
F-16 jetfighters that are to be removed from the U.S. air base at
Torrejon near Madrid. Spain's government, under domestic political
pressure, asked for their removal.
   In Washington, Deputy Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV told
the House Armed Services Committee he expects Italy will agree to
be host for the 401st Tactical Fighter Wing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
