<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     05-25 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa To Begin Evicting Black Settlers Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said it will
begin evicting 1,800 blacks next month from a settlement designated
for people of mixed race. Civil rights workers called the plan a
revival of forced removals.
   In another development, state radio reported that a black had
spoken for the first time in an official proceeding at South
Africa's Parliament building.
   Blacks make up 75 percent of South Africa's 35 million people
but have no representation in Parliament and no vote in national
affairs.
   In announcing the planned evictions at Lawaiicamp, white
officials said on Tuesday that the 40-year-old black community is
an illegal, unsanitary squatter camp. They deny the actions will
constitute forced removal.
   But residents of Lawaiicamp say they are determined to stay
where they are.
   In 1984, President P.W. Botha said there would be no more forced
removals of the sort that resettled an estimated 3.5 million people
from 1950 to 1983.
   But critics say the policy continues under different names, such
as ``slum clearance'' and ``squatter control.''
   Lawaiicamp adjoins the township of George, which Botha
represented in Parliament before becoming president in 1984, and is
five miles from a scenic stretch of Indian Ocean coastline east of
Cape Town.
   The government wants to move Lawaiicamp residents to Sandkraal,
about a mile further from George, which was established four years
ago to be the area's official black township.
   George's mayor, John Rogers, told a news conference on Tuesday
that Lawaiicamp residents have until May 31 to move voluntarily.
The town council plans to apply for eviction orders in court on
June 1 and to demolish the 180 remaining Lawaiicamp homes once they
are vacated.
   Rogers said evicted families will be paid compensation and
provided with new homes. About 800 families have already moved from
Lawaiicamp to Sandkraal, and the government claims they enjoy
better services and amenities.
   The mayor said violence would not be used against residents
resisting eviction, but did not explain how this could be assured.
   The current Parliament member for George, Hennie Smit, said
Lawaiicamp is illegal because it is on land designated for use by
people of mixed race. A new mixed-race township is to be developed
on the site.
   In early 1986, the government tried to evict Lawaiicamp
residents but backed off because of legal challenges and stiff
resistance. This time, the government says it will not yield.
   The precedent-setting speech by a black at South Africa's
Parliament building came on Tuesday during committee debate in Cape
Town on the proposed budget for Cape Province.
   Temba Nyati, a black appointed last year to the provincial
executive committee, spoke about the importance of municipal
government.
   He later told the state-run South African Broadcasting Corp.
blacks should view participation in local government as a first
step toward sharing power at higher levels.
   A new constitution in 1984 created the Asian and mixed-race
chambers of Parliament but still excluded the black majority from
national affairs.
   The white chamber is able to get its say on all major
legislative issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MarketReport     05-25 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Market Report,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxmire Chides White House on Stock Market Report, Promises Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Proxmire says he will try to push
stock market reform legislation to the Senate floor next month,
even though Reagan administration officials say that the need for
such a measure is dubious.
   Proxmire, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, chided four
federal officials who appeared before the panel on Tuesday for
producing a report on last fall's stock market crash that suggested
there is scant need for legislation.
   ``I can tell you, we're going to go ahead'' with a bill, said
Proxmire, D-Wis.
   Proxmire told the authors of the study that they had made
``pitiful'' progress in formulating suggestions for calming the
nation's jittery financial exchanges and nervous investors. The
four officials were Treasury Undersecretary George D. Gould,
Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman David S. Ruder,
Commodity Futures Trading Commission Chairwoman Wendy Gramm and
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   ``You have let down the American people at a critical time,''
Proxmire told the officials.
   Gould, who headed the White House team that wrote the report,
sidestepped several questions about when the group would suggest
needed legislation, saying, ``We're not legislatively driven, we're
decision driven.''
   The working group's report, released May 16, suggested several
mild steps for dealing with the markets' ills.
   They included a call for an hourlong trading halt in the
nation's stock, futures and options markets if the Dow Jones
Industrial Average plunges by 250 points in a single day. Such a
decline has occurred only once: last Oct. 19's 508-point drop,
which has triggered on ongoing look at the markets' volatility by
the government and Congress.
   Proxmire introduced legislation on March 31 that would establish
a committee consisting of the chairmen of the Federal Reserve
Board, the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission. The committee would oversee issues that
affect all of the nation's markets, such as coordinating margins _
or downpayments _ exchanged in transactions, and setting up
``circuit breakers'' to halt trading during emergencies.
   ``My aim ... is to make sure that there is an accountable entity
with both the responsibility and the expertise to make the
decisions on intermarket issues,'' Proxmire said.
   Currently, the CFTC oversees the futures markets, while the SEC
and the Fed share responsibility for the stock and options
exchanges.
   After the hearing, Proxmire told reporters he expected his
committee to send the legislation to the full Senate in June.
   With Congress' schedule abbreviated this year because of the
elections _ and with some lawmakers joining the administration in
opposing strong legislative action on the problem _ it seems
unlikely that any bill will become law in 1988.
   ``It makes it much harder to have the administration opposed,''
Proxmire conceded. ``The president has the veto, and the
administration has influence with many members of Congress.''
   Sentiment on the banking committee on the need for legislation
seems split, and not along party lines.
   While Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said, ``We'd be darned fools
to say that all is well'' with the financial markets, Sen. John
Shelby, D-Ala., said, ``A lot of us here ... don't believe you can
legislate investors' confidence.''
   Ruder has dissented from his colleagues on several points,
arguing that futures margins should be raised and that the SEC
should oversee futures trading. The SEC meets Thursday to fashion
legislative proposals that will be submitted to Congress by next
week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary     05-25 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Hungarian Party Chief Concedes Economic Failures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karoly Grosz, Hungary's new Communist
Party leader, said he will speed up economic reforms planned for
late in the year, but cautioned Hungarians not to expect a swift
economic turnaround.
   He also conceded that since he became prime minister in June
1987, his government has failed to revitalize Hungary's sluggish
economy.
   ``Thirty years of accumulated tension cannot be dissolved
overnight,'' he told the government newspaper Magyar Hirlap on
Tuesday in his first lengthy interview since being named party
general secretary two days earlier.
   ``The danger of the reform is the accompanying illusions. Many
think that we shall pass 10 reforms and the country's situation
will change. This is not so,'' he said.
   The 57-year-old Grosz will continue as premier at least until
Parliament announces a new head of government.
   He replaced longtime party chief Janos Kadar, a hardliner.
   Grosz said financial moves alone could not solve this nation's
economic crisis and acknowledged that some political change must
accompany the new measures. He said appointing new Cabinet
ministers and choosing a new head of government probably would take
place this fall.
   He praised Kadar and said that the idea of naming Kadar party
president, a new post that is expected to be largely ceremonial,
was ``the result of the past few weeks.''
   This indicated prolonged haggling over whether Kadar, who turns
76 on Thursday, would give up the party leadership he held nearly
32 years.
   Grosz said Kadar's new post would let him use his vast
experience in international affairs _ an indication that Grosz
expects Kadar to keep out of day-to-day internal politics.
   Kadar was dropped from the Politburo along with seven other
party veterans in Sunday's reshuffle.
   Grosz said it is important that the new 11-member Politburo
include such people as Reszo Nyers, the father of Hungary's
economic reforms in the 1960s, and Imre Pozsgay, another outspoken
advocate of political reform.
   As premier, Grosz pushed stringent measures to curb Hungary's 18
percent inflation rate and $18 billion foreign debt. But he
admitted the austerity measures so far failed to halt stagnation.
   A new party policy statement approved on Sunday advocates more
foreign investment, joint ventures and loosening restrictions on
the ownership of foreign capital.
   It calls for changes allowing Hungarians a greater voice in
economic and political affairs, including a major expansion of
private initiatives.
   Hungary's economic crisis with the attendant loss of confidence
in the Communist Party prompted the birth of many independent
interest groups, demanding a voice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Anti-Terrorism     05-25 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anti-Terrorism,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House-Passed Bill Would Block Military Exports To Terrorist
Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is moving forward with legislation
that could prevent another Iran-Contra affair by establishing
precise rules governing when a president must tell Congress of
dealings with terrorist countries.
   In the latest attempt to turn the lessons learned from the
affair into law, the House on Tuesday approved by voice vote a bill
designed chiefly to prevent exports of military equipment to
terrorist nations, like Iran.
   But the legislation, sent to the Senate, permits the president
to deal with such countries if he believes the national interest is
at stake _ and if he adheres to strict notification requirements to
Congress.
   Since the bill permits the president some flexibility, the
Reagan administration does not oppose the legislation, according to
administration foreign policy supporter Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
   The House bill is the second major attempt by Congress to avoid
another Iran-Contra affair.
   The Senate earlier this year passed a bill, which is still
pending in the House, that would require the president to notify
Congress of any covert intelligence operation within 48 hours after
its authorization. Current law merely provides for timely
notification.
   The Reagan administration considers that requirement too rigid
and opposes the legislation.
   The new House bill requires notification to Congress in a much
broader array of circumstances than just covert actions. The
coverage would include transfer of weapons and foreign aid money,
which may or may not be secret.
   In the Iran-Contra affair, President Reagan did not tell
Congress he had authorized the sales to Iran until after the secret
operation was revealed in a Middle East publication.
   Iran is one of six nations designated by the State Department as
a terrorist country. The other countries are Cuba, Iran, Libya,
North Korea, North Yemen and Syria.
   Current law is supposed to prevent such weapons sales, but
failed to do so.
   Hyde, a member of the former House Iran-Contra committee, called
the bill ``one of the thoughtful responses to the Iran-Contra
hearings.
   ``One of the big problems (in the Iran-Contra affair) was the
transfer of weapons to the Iranians and nobody knew about it,'' he
said. ``In this bill, the president still has his constitutional
power to execute his foreign policy functions.''
   The latest bill would prohibit any American from exporting arms
to a terrorist state, whether the individual is a government
employee, a private citizen or someone acting on behalf of the
government.
   The secret network that controlled weapons sales to Iran and use
of some profits to aid the Nicaraguan Contras was directed by
former National Security Council staffer Oliver L. North. He, in
turn, enlisted two businessmen to run the logistics of the
operations: Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim.
   Under the legislation, the State Department would form its list
of terrorist nations by determining whether a country repeatedly
supported acts of international terrorism or granted sanctuary to
international terrorists.
   The president could delete a nation from the list. But he must
report to Congress that a fundamental change in leadership and
character has taken place, that the country has not supported
international terrorism for the preceding six months, and that
government provided assurances it would not support future acts of
terrorism. The deletion could not take place until 30 days after
the report was submitted.
   The legislation would require a validated license before goods
or technology could be exported to terrorist states, if such
exports would significantly contribute to the military potential of
the country or enhance its ability to support terrorism.
   The State Department must notify Congress 30 days before issuing
a validated license.
   The president would be able to waive export restrictions for
national security reasons, and could provide foreign assistance to
a terrorist nation for humanitarian purposes.
   But first, the president must give Congress a 15-day advance
notification, and a report containing all the details of the
proposed transaction.
   The legislation would retain current penalties for violating
restrictions on exports or aid to terrorist countries: a maximum of
$1 million in fines and 10 years in prison for criminal violations,
and up to $500,000 for civil penalties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
