<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Missiles-Summit     05-25 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missiles-Summit,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says US Will Make New Missile Proposals At Moscow Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arms Treaty Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will make new proposals at
the Moscow summit to keep track of elusive mobile missiles in a
move to complete a treaty sharply reducing strategic nuclear
arsenals, Secretary of State George P. Shultz said.
   So far, U.S. and Soviet negotiators have been unable to find
ways to count the missiles that would be left on both sides if
stockpiles are slashed. This, in turn, keeps the superpowers from
deciding whether to include mobile missiles in an arms reduction
treaty.
   While verification is extremely difficult, the Reagan
administration is not ready to insist on banning the elusive
weapons and give up hope of retaining some of these potent
long-range missiles in the U.S. arsenal, Shultz said Tuesday.
   ``They are harder to find, so they are more survivable and
therefore don't invite a first strike,'' Shultz told news agency
reporters in a pre-summit interview. ``So that adds something to
stability.''
   But he acknowledged their elusiveness poses an extreme problem
for arms control. ``So you have to find a balance, a compromise,''
Shultz said.
   Negotiations on a new treaty are stymied over the U.S.
anti-missile program, known popularly as Star Wars, and over
verifying reductions in mobile missiles and cruise missiles carried
on fighter planes and warships.
   The treaty is supposed to reduce U.S. and Soviet strategic
weapons by 30 percent to 50 percent. At the same time, the two
sides want to devise foolproof ways of verifying weapons are not
retained illegally.
   Shultz said U.S. negotiators in Geneva had already proposed some
ideas on how to keep track of mobile missiles. At the Moscow
summit, he said, ``We will propose additional ones that refine
things and give them more detail.''
   He said the Reagan administration also would pursue at the
summit a system for sending observers to suspect sites with little
advance warning.
   While the treaty cannot be completed in time for the summit,
Shultz said there was still a chance of finishing it before
President Reagan leaves office next January.
   ``It's possible,'' he said. ``I don't know whether it will
actually happen or not. There are very knowledgeable people on both
sides working to bring it about. But the problems are very
difficult.''
   And yet, he said the Soviets evidently want to keep at it,
instead of waiting for the next administration to take over.
   ``They are in a negotiating process with people who are
knowledgeable, competent, and are engaged,'' Shultz said. ``So
they, as we, want to make as much progress as is possible.''
</TEXT>
