<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FAA-Inspections     05-25 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FAA-Inspections,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Cracks Found in Some Older Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is
preparing a formal regulation that could require the metal skin of
older Boeing 737s to be strengthened and reinforced, the agency's
administrator, Allen McArtor, says.
   The proposed regulation is expected to be formally announced
within a week.
   McArtor's comments on Tuesday came in the wake of last month's
in-flight breakup of an Aloha Airlines Boeing 737. A flight
attendant was swept to her death when a 20-foot section of the
plane tore away. The pilots managed to bring the aircraft to a safe
landing, but 61 people were injured.
   The Aloha plane was 19 years old and had made nearly 89,000
landings.
   FAA officials also reported on Tuesday that a special inspection
of 96 older Boeing 737s, begun after that accident, found small
cracks in one of every nine aircraft but none of a magnitude that
they are cause for alarm.
   Anthony Broderick, the FAA's associate administrator for
aviation standards, said that of the 96 planes inspected under the
order, 10 were found to have some cracks, the largest of which was
one-fourth of an inch. He said none of the cracks should be
considered ``alarming.''
   Investigators believe that a 20-foot section of the forward
cabin wall and roof tore away from the Aloha Boeing 737 during
April 28 flight because of a structural failure stemming from
cracking and corrosion.
   A week after the incident, the FAA directed that all Boeing 737s
with 30,000 or more landings undergo a special visual inspection
and those with more than 50,000 landings be subject to additional
inspections using high-frequency electronic equipment.
   According to the Boeing Co., there are 373 of the 737s worldwide
with 30,000 or more landings, 212 of which operate in the United
States and are subject to the FAA-required inspections.
</TEXT>
