<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   05-25 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Demand Report On Noriega-U.S. Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has been
summoned before the legislature to report on negotiations with U.S.
officials over the nation's lengthy political crisis.
   The move on Tuesday by the pro-Noriega Legislative Assembly
would allow Panama's military leader to present his position
without appearing to take the initiative in divulging details of
the talks.
   By a 39-7 vote with five abstentions, the 67-member body
summoned Noriega to appear before it within 48 hours. The chief of
Panama's 15,000-strong Defense Forces and the nation's de facto
leader, did not immediately respond.
   A similar move failed in the assembly on Monday when 27 of 47
legislators present voted for it. Passage required a two-thirds
majority of those present.
   The United States has imposed a wide array of economic sanctions
on Panama in an effort to force the ouster of Noriega, who was
indicted in February on federal drug smuggling charges in Florida.
   Reagan administration officials want Noriega to resign his post
and leave the country at least temporarily.
   If Noriega appears before the legislature, he will be asked what
American negotiators have proposed, what Panamanian negotiators are
trying to achieve, and why the United States is taking part in the
talks if it does not recognize the Noriega-controlled government of
President Manuel Solis Palma.
   The White House's chief negotiator, Michael G. Kozak, has been
meeting with Noriega representatives for nearly a month to try to
resolve the crisis. He returned to Panama on Monday after a brief
trip to Washington.
   While a deal has been reported near on several occasions by
Reagan administration sources, Noriega has said in several recent
appearances that he will not leave unless American economic
sanctions are lifted and U.S. ``aggression'' ends.
   About 2,000 American troops have been sent to Panama in recent
weeks to back up the 10,000 soldiers already here assigned to
protect the Panama Canal.
   Noriega also has said the United States must ``respect'' the
presidency of Solis Palma, who took over the presidency Feb. 26
after President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire Noriega and was
deposed by the general's supporters.
   Delvalle, recognized by the United States as the legitimate
president of Panama, is in hiding in Panama. There is a warrant out
for his arrest.
   Romulo Escobar Betancourt, president of the pro-military
Revolutionary Democratic Party, told local television stations on
Tuesday that the crisis would be resolved if the United States
lifts the sanctions.
   ``In five minutes,'' he said, ``the problem would be settled.''
   Betancourt, who has represented Noriega in the talks with the
United States, also said: ``We have totally rejected the fact that
Noriega has to leave the country.''
   Noriega has denied the U.S. drug smuggling charges, which he
contends are a political ploy to replace him with a less
nationalistic leader who might tolerate a prolonged American
military presence.
   President Reagan reportedly is considering dropping the
indictments if it would lead to Noriega's departure from power, a
position that has sharply divided his administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
