<DOCNO> AP880525-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-USTrade     05-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-US Trade,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Government Relieved By Reagan's Trade Bill Veto</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Trade, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today expressed relief after
President Reagan vetoed an omnibus trade bill that provides for
sanctions against a Japanese company and countries who violate
international trade agreements.
   Japan's relief was qualified, however, by a vote overriding the
veto in the U.S. House of Representatives and the reasons behind
Reagan's veto.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, speaking to reporters at his
official residence, welcomed the veto. ``Concern now is primarily
on domestic issues in the United States,'' Takeshita said. ``When
the negotiations (between Reagan and Congress) begin, the issues
most affecting Japan will be brought out.''
   Japan's minister of international trade and industry, Hajime
Tamura, told a news conference: ``Our ministry has in the past
requested efforts from the United States government to see that the
trade bill would not be enacted, and we welcome President Reagan's
veto.''
   Opposition to the bill in Japan stems mainly from provisions
requiring retaliation against violations of international trade
pacts and other ``unjustifiable'' practices.
   If enacted, the bill would transfer from the president to the
U.S. trade representative the authority to decide what unfair trade
practices another country is engaged in and what, if any,
retaliatory measures to impose.
   A provision imposing sanctions against Toshiba Corp. and one of
its subsidiaries, Toshiba Machine Co., for the subsidiary's sales
of sensitive equipment to the Soviet Union also concerns Japan.
   Reagan's veto message made no mention of the Toshiba sanctions.
The message focused on curbs on exports of Alaskan oil and a
mandatory requirement forcing businesses to give employees advance
warning of closures or layoffs.
   Toshiba Machine Corp. sold the Soviets milling machines that
could be used to make submarine propellers quieter and more
difficult to detect. The sales violated international rules
regulating trade between the West and communist countries.
   Tamura said he hopes Congress will support Reagan and that the
bill will not pass. ``But for us foreigners it is very hard to say
what will happen in the United States,'' he added.
   The House overrode the veto with a margin well above the
two-thirds majority required, but it was thought unlikely that the
Senate would go along when it considers the override after next
week's Memorial Day recess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
