<DOCNO> AP880525-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardUnion     05-25 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Union,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Challenges Union Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University has filed objections
with the National Labor Relations Board about a union vote by
white-collar workers, charging that organizers used illegal tactics
to gain a slim victory.
   The university action Tuesday was ordered by Harvard President
Derek Bok. Harvard officials claimed workers were ``intimidated or
coerced'' as they voted May 17 in favor of unionizing.
   A union officer said Harvard was ``stretching it'' with the
charges and had no evidence to prove the claim.
   Harvard's 3,300 clerical and technical staff members voted by a
44-vote majority to make the Harvard Union of Clerical and
Technical Workers their negotiating body. The Ivy League school
fought the union drive with flyers, in-house meetings with
supervisors and public statements.
   The union drive was closely watched by national labor leaders as
a benchmark for organizing white-collar workers. Harvard's prestige
and the bitterness of the fight between the university and the
union drew national media attention.
   ``Harvard worked very hard to ensure that staff members would be
permitted to vote on May 17 in a fair and lawful process, without
being intimidated or coerced,'' said Anne Taylor, who coordinated
Harvard's response to the union drive. ``There is some evidence
that the union did not share this principle.''
   Taylor said 41 of those who voted for the union were ineligible
to vote because of their jobs status. As a result, she said, the
actual margin could have been as small as three votes.
   Harvard charged that union representatives maintained lists of
voters, interrogated workers at the polls, campaigned near polling
places, escorted workers to voting places and pressured union
opponents not to vote.
   Harvard's filing of the NLRB claim drew a rebuke from Gerald W.
McEntee, national president of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees, to which the Harvard union belongs.
   He called the charges ``an insult to the thousands of university
employees who participated in this free and open election and an
insult to the entire labor movement. Harvard has flunked its
fairness report card.''
   Chief union organizer Kristine Rondeau questioned the charge
that she and others intimidated workers. ``I don't think that I
could intimidate a fly,'' Rondeau said. ``It's really stretching
it.''
   Rondeau said the university issued a questionnaire to the more
than 3,300 workers Tuesday asking whether they noticed any pressure
by the union on election day. She denied that the union pressured
anyone.
   Robert Garner, assistant regional director for the NLRB, said
the board's policy has been to conduct union elections in
``laboratory conditions,'' as free from pressure as possible.
   The NLRB could take from a month to more than a year to review
Harvard's charges, he said.
   ``From the union's standpoint, the worst that could happen is
that they have to run the election over again,'' Garner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
