<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Suit Filed In Effort To Stop Obscenity Prosecutions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut-based operator of a mail-order
pornography business is suing the Justice Department to stop
prosecuting him on obscenity charges in four states.
   Avram Freedberg, owner of Consumer's Marketing Group Ltd. of
Stamford Conn., filed the suit Tuesday to prevent the Justice
Department's national obscenity enforcement unit from bringing the
charges in federal courts in Mississippi, Indiana, Utah and
Delaware.
   He asked a federal judge to issue an temporary restraining order
to halt the prosecutions.
   The suit charges that the effort to prosecute Freedberg, his
wife, Rhoda, and others in the four jurisdictions is merely a
campaign to harass the firm and drive it out of business by forcing
it to incur large legal fees.
   The suit said government prosecutors ``simply disapprove of the
content of plaintiff's promotional materials, magazines, and
videotapes, and are unconstitutionally intimidating plaintiffs with
multiple (simultaneous or consecutive) obscenity prosecutions.''
