<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advocacy Group Contends EPA Allows Too Much Lead in Grapefruit</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Juice
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advocacy group accuses federal regulators
of permitting lead concentrations in fresh Florida grapefruit juice
20 times that allowed in drinking water.
   The Environmental Protection Agency is closing its eyes to the
extreme use of lead arsenate, a chemical used to accelerate the
ripening of grapefruit, the National Coalition Against the Misuse
of Pesticides, said Tuesday.
   The last federal license to sell lead arsenate was surrendered
earlier this year by the manufacturer, Micro-Flo Co. of Lakeland,
Fla., rather than conduct more tests that EPA said were needed for
its 10-year-old review of arsenic-based pesticides.
   In return for surrendering the license, the company was
permitted to sell remaining inventories. Up to 100,000 pounds per
year have been used recently, enabling growers to earn almost $10
million a year in extra profits by sending fruit to market early,
according to EPA estimates.
   The coalition says there is enough lead arsenate in Florida
distribution channels to serve growers for another two years.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To Restrict Use Of Boat-Hull Paint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has approved legislation to restrict
the use of a popular boat-hull paint that is effective against
marine organisms like barnacles but which poses environmental risks.
   The bill, approved by voice vote in the House on Tuesday, would
ban the use of paints containing organic tin additives on
non-aluminum hull vessels less than 82 feet long. The most widely
used additive is tributyltin, or TBT.
   The measure would permit continued use of such paints on large
vessels and those with aluminum hulls so long as the organic tin
compounds are not released into the water at more than 4 micrograms
per square centimeter a day.
   Paints with organic tin are much more effective against
barnacles and marine algae than copper-based paints, meaning lower
maintenance costs for boat owners. But testimony in the House said
those paints can remain toxic for up to six months when released
into the water.
</TEXT>
