<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-25 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Inactive, Stocks Post Healthy Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed little changed today in trading
against the Japanese yen, while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange posted a healthy gain following the overnight advance on
Wall Street.
   After opening the day at 124.20 yen, the dollar climbed slightly
and ended the day at 124.30 yen, up 0.05 yen from Tuesday's finish.
   ``The dollar stayed stable throughout the day, ranging between
124.15 and 124.33 yen in mixed trading,'' said a dealer with a
major commercial bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   There was some dollar-selling by trading houses that pulled the
currency down a little, but it climbed back again on speculative
buying by financial institutions, he said.
   ``There was also apprehensions over possible market intervention
by the Bank of Japan to support the dollar, which prevented
participants to make major moves,'' the dealer said.
   Japan's central bank, however, did not step into the market, he
said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained a small 62.90 points Tuesday, won
130.99 points, or 0.47 percent, to close the day's trading at
27,443.65.
   ``The overnight rise on Wall Street made investors confident,''
said Hiromi Yoneyama of Wako Securities.
   Share prices were firm almost across the board supported by
strong buying mood by institutional, foreign, as well as individual
investors, he said.
   Investors who have been concerned about rising interest rates
and booming inflation in the United States are now less pessimistic
about the future of the U.S. economy, he added.
   Trading was heavy, led by large-capital issues such as steels
and heavy industries, said traders.
   Volume on the first section trading wa estimated at 1.5 billion
shares, up from 1.1 billion shares Tuesday.
   Other than large-capital issues, shipbuildings, automobiles,
chemicals, machineries and real estates were higher. Certain
electricals and precision machineries lost ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
