<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrawleyCase     05-25 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Case,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State A.G. To Seek Contempt Charges Against Brawley's Mother</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 10th graf, `The 16-year-old ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general said he
will seek contempt-of-court charges against the mother of a black
teen-ager who claims she was abducted and raped by a group of white
men.
   Attorney General Robert Abrams said Tuesday he found it ironic
that dozens of friends, neighbors and acquaintances of Tawana
Brawley will talk to investigators, but that the teen-ager's own
family continues to resist the probe.
   Miss Brawley's mother, Glenda, has defied a subpoena to tell a
grand jury investigating the case about her daughter's allegations
of sexual abuse at the hands of six white men. The Brawleys say the
incident was racially motivated.
   ``The strategy of defiance and non-cooperation on the part of
the family and their representatives continues to impede our
investigation from learning the full story of what happened to
Tawana Brawley,'' Abrams said.
   Abrams called the situation ``unfortunate and regrettable,'' and
said the blame must be shared by the Brawleys' representatives,
attorneys Alton Maddox Jr. and C. Vernon Mason, and the Rev. Al
Sharpton.
   Mason and Sharpton have called Abrams and Gov. Mario Cuomo
racists, and insisted that Abrams step aside as special prosecutor
in the case.
   Mrs. Brawley talked about her daughter's case on a New York City
radio station Tuesday at the same time she had been summoned to
appear before the grand jury here.
   ``I could not get any justice, so I went to the black community
and I got all the power that I need to back me to help me to fight
for my daughter,'' said Mrs. Brawley, who was interviewed on
station WLIB with Tawana's stepfather, Ralph King, and the family's
advisers.
   Mason and Maddox said they are eager to explain the reasons for
defying the subpoena. A hearing on the contempt allegation will be
sometime next week, said Abrams' spokesman Timothy Gilles.
   The 16-year-old Wappingers Falls girl was missing for four days
before she was found Nov. 28 in a dazed state with racial epithets
and excrement smeared on her body. She said that white men, one of
them with a badge, had abducted and raped her.
   Miss Brawley has refused to cooperate with investigators. Her
only statements about what happened have come through her family.
   Authorities have not be able to find evidence to corroborate her
story.
   After allegations by attorneys for Miss Brawley that local
investigators could not be impartial, Cuomo assigned the case to
Abrams.
   If found in contempt, Mrs. Brawley could be jailed for up to 30
days or fined $250, Abrams said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TahoeVote     05-25 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tahoe Vote,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tahoe Voters Reject New City Plan, No New Effort Planned At This
Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATELINE, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite assurances of better services,
voters in several resort communities decided against forming the
city of Lake Tahoe after casinos helped wage a vigorous advertising
campaign against the move.
   The vote Tuesday was 1,001 against and 802 for the plan. The
issue prompted an unusually high turnout of 60 percent, said
Douglas County Clerk Barbara Reed. She said a normal turnout was
35-40 percent.
   The proposed city, with a population of about 6,500, would have
embraced the casino area of Stateline and smaller communities along
about 15 miles of Lake Tahoe's southeastern shore.
   The proposal lost in all the lakeshore communities, although
proponents had argued that the communities, which make up 25
percent of Douglas County's population, do not receive a
proportionate share in services of the 60 percent in tax revenue
they contribute.
   Ron Nino, leader of the opposition, said he was very pleased
with the vote, adding, ``We believed there was going to be a
substantial tax increase. People will pay more for more but we
didn't see where there was going to be more. We saw the same or
less.''
   The opposition received financial support from the Stateline
casinos, whose tax burden Nino said would rise by at least $300,000
yearly under a city government.
   ``The tax scare did it,'' admitted Bill Bigham, a leader of the
movement to create the city. ``I think that did us in, perhaps
along with mixing it with the Highway Patrol.'' Opponents also
argued there would be fewer or no state trooper patrols in the area
if the city was created.
   ``The ads that came out in the paper were rather overwhelming,''
Bigham said. ``While we had some good editorials in the paper, and
some people sponsored their own ads for the city, we just didn't
have the money to spend on it that the opposition did.''
   Commissioners of Douglas County, which would lose about $1.8
million in yearly tax revenue to the city, mostly from the big
Stateline casinos, had advised voters to reject the plan.
   Communities in California, on the western side of the lake, also
had complained about the plan, saying the name Lake Tahoe would
create confusion between the lake and the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
