<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-25 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms in Florida Produce Tornadoes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms boomed over Florida today after unleashing
tornadoes and high winds that threw a porch onto a pickup truck,
cut power to thousands and injured six passengers aboard a
jetliner. In Atlanta, lightning killed a man.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell over southeast Georgia and along
the Carolina coast, and extended from southern New England to
eastern Kentucky and the southern Appalachians.
   Thunderstorms and showers also dampened eastern New Mexico and
northwest Texas. Showers and a few thunderstorms fell over the
northern High Plains.
   Frost and freeze advisories were issued for sections of Michigan
and Wisconsin.
   More than half a dozen tornadoes were reported during Tuesday's
storms in Florida. Near Hilliard, a twister threw the back porch of
a home onto a truck in the front yard.
   High winds and heavy rain buffeted a Braniff Airlines jetliner
approaching Orlando International Airport at 13,000 feet, slightly
injuring four of the 55 passengers and two flight attendants. The
BAC-111, two-engine aircraft landed safely.
   Storms also knocked out power to 5,000 customers in Brevard
County.
   On Florida's Gulf Coast, lighting touched off six brush fires
that charred nearly 200 acres near a residential area and forced
people from their homes.
   In Atlanta, lightning killed a 25-year-old man waiting for a bus
who sought shelter from the storm under a tree, said Sgt. C.A.
Graham, an investigator for the Fulton County medical examiner.
   In North Carolina, thunderstorms unleashed winds recorded at 88
mph in the coastal city of Columbia. Power lines were downed in
Martin County.
   Quarter-size hail was reported in Polk County, Fla., and
marble-size hail fell in Rocky Ford, Colo.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern New England and eastern New York to Florida, and scattered
over western Montana.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 50s and 60s from
New England to the Great Lakes and south through the Ohio Valley,
Virginia and West Virginia; the 60s and 70s along the Pacific
Coast; the 70s from the Carolinas to the Tennessee Valley, from
northern Georgia to northeast Arkansas, in the northern half of the
Mississippi Valley and from the Texas Panhandle to Colorado; near
90 in much of Florida and the southern half of Texas; the 90s to
about 110 in the desert Southwest; and the 80s in the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 26 at
Marquette, Mich., to 86 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 partly cloudy; Boston 63 showery; Buffalo 46
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 67 foggy; Cincinnati 53 windy; Cleveland
45 fair; Detroit 43 fair; Miami 79 fair; New York 64 cloudy;
Philadelphia 64 cloudy; Pittsburgh 48 windy; Portland, Maine, 55
cloudy; Washington 66 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 63 fair; Chicago 44 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
63 fair; Denver 56 fair; Des Moines 58 fair; Indianapolis 50 windy;
Kansas City 64 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 50 fair; Nashville 61
foggy; New Orleans 69 foggy; St. Louis 53 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 63 fair; Anchorage 49 fair; Las Vegas 75
fair; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 86 fair; Salt Lake City 68
partly cloudy; San Francisco 53 cloudy; Seattle 51 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 54 partly cloudy; Toronto 41 showery.
</TEXT>
