<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TruckFire     05-25 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Truck Fire,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Evacuated After Propane Tanker Ignites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of evacuated residents waited to
return home today while many others faced commuting headaches as
propane from an overturned tank truck burned for a second day.
   The fire was so intense, and potentially explosive, that
firefighters were prevented from approaching the burning truck
loaded with about 2,500 gallons of propane. Instead, unmanned
pumpers threw water on the blaze.
   Officials estimated that the fire could burn for as long as 30
hours, or until about 3:30 p.m. today, if no explosion occurred.
   About 2,000 families were evacuated from within half a mile of
the accident and taken to a nearby church, said Hank McCann, a
Nassau County police spokesman.
   County police Lt. Willard Krausch said the truck overturned
Tuesday morning on the Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway after the
driver experienced a problem with the truck's rear wheels.
   A section of the highway and of another nearby road were closed,
and the Long Island Rail Road was forced to suspend all commuter
rail service on a nearby line.
   About 30,000 rush-hour passengers were expected to be directly
affected this morning by service disruptions on the railroad's
busiest branch, the Babylon line, said a railroad spokesman, Brian
Dolan.
   ``There hasn't been as severe a tie-up on our system in quite a
while,'' said Dolan. ``It's certainly the worst this year.''
   Fire communications supervisor Douglas Wood said the fire
marshal's office and hazardous materials experts were at the scene,
and ambulances were standing by in case of an explosion.
   Propane meets a variety of residential and commercial energy
needs, particularly in areas that are not served by natural gas
pipelines.
   The driver, Roger Vai, 35, of Westbury, who was treated at the
scene for a shoulder cut, was arrested on an outstanding traffic
offense and also charged with driving with a suspended license and
failure to produce a license.
   A trainee who was riding with him escaped before the truck
ignited, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
