<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-25 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Edge Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged upward today in slow
European trading which exchange dealers said lacked both direction
and volume. Gold prices also rose.
   ``There is nothing interesting in sight,'' said one dealer at a
West German bank in Frankfurt. ``We will keep a narrow range again,
just like yesterday.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed little changed at 124.30 yen, up 0.05 yen. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 124.40 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.7021 West German marks, up from 1.7000
   _1.4210 Swiss francs, up from 1.4150
   _5.7468 French francs, up from 5.7395
   _1.9055 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9030
   _1,263.75 Italian lire, up from 1,261.80
   _1.2420 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2412
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8652, cheaper for
buyers than $1.8680 late Tuesday.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$458.35 a troy ounce at midmorning, down from the opening bid of
$459.60, but up from late Tuesday's $457.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $458.10, little changed from $458
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 42 cents to close at a bid
$460.27.
   Silver was quoted at a bid price of $6.71 a troy ounce in
London, unchanged from late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
