<1ST_LINE>r p PM-IdahoPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0538 05-25 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Idaho Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0538,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, bgng Dukakis was, to show Gore with 4
percent; picks up 5th graf pvs, The Democratic.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB FICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Idaho's less-than-suspenseful Republican
presidential primary added another win to Vice President George
Bush's column. Michael Dukakis cruised to an easy victory in the
Democratic ``beauty contest.''
   With 99 percent of the precincts reporting, Bush had 82 percent
of the vote to 9 percent for Pat Robertson, who suspended his
campaign earlier this month to rejoin the Christian Broadcasting
Network.
   Bush was winning 15 of the 18 national convention delegates at
stake in the lackluster primary Tuesday, with two going to
Robertson and one in the uncommitted column.
   Dukakis was pulling in 73 percent of the vote to 16 percent for
Jesse Jackson, with only a handful of precincts still unreported.
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 4 percent and Sen. Paul Simon 3 percent;
both have suspended their presidential campaigns.
   The Democratic vote was not binding. Dukakis, the front-runner,
claimed a majority of the delegates at caucuses two months ago.
   With no statewide elected offices at stake this year and the
presidential candidates all but formally crowned, there was little
to draw Idaho voters to the polls beyond a handful of heated
legislative and local races.
   ``For various reasons, the presidential election and others,
neither we nor the county clerks are seeing very much intensity in
this one,'' Deputy Secretary of State Ben Ysursa said.
   In congressional primaries, state Rep. Jeanne Givens rolled up a
large victory over two challengers to take the Democratic
nomination to face four-term Republican Congressman Larry Craig in
the 1st District.
   Former state Sen. Dane Watkins won the Republican nomination to
challenge two-term Democratic Congressman Richard Stallings this
fall in the state's 2nd District.
   Bush made a 19-hour campaign swing through Idaho earlier this
month to bolster his support in a state that has not given its four
electoral votes to a Democrat since Lyndon Johnson in 1964.
   Democrats allotted 18 of their 24 nominating delegates in Super
Tuesday caucuses held on March 8. Dukakis captured eight of them,
Jackson four and six were uncommitted.
   Since then, however, Gov. Cecil Andrus, one of the six
previously uncommitted ``super delegates,'' has endorsed Dukakis
and urged others to do the same so the party is clearly unified for
the November assault on the White House.
   Although there has been no statewide polling conducted, a
Democratic poll this spring in the conservative 2nd Congressional
District of southern Idaho showed Dukakis only 2 percentage points
behind Bush.
   ``But it's a long time to the finish line,'' said state Senate
President Pro Tem James Risch of Boise, Bush's state chairman.
``The people will have a choice between a person who knows the
issues and a governor of a state that really hasn't done very
well.''
</TEXT>
