<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NaziCharge     05-25 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nazi Charge,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Role In Nazi Labor Camps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retiree described by neighbors as a
recluse is accused in federal court documents of having been
second-in-command of a system of Nazi slave-labor camps during
World War II.
   The Justice Department's Office of Special Investigations filed
a civil complaint Tuesday claiming that Juris Kauls of Sun City
West, believed to be 75 years old, was the deputy chief and
inspector of guards in 1941 and 1942 for 14 concentration camps at
Riga, Latvia.
   ``The concentration camp was a place of persecution for its
prisoners,'' says the complaint, filed in U.S. District Court.
``Such persecution included ... the incarceration of civilians
solely because of their race, religion, political beliefs or
national origin.''
   According to the complaint, the camps' prisoners were used
primarily for slave labor, but some were beaten, starved and
executed.
   ``It was a terrible facility but not as well-known as
Auschwitz,'' said Neal Sher, director of the Office of Special
Investigations in Washington.
   The office requested that Kauls, who moved to Arizona from
Indianapolis, be deported because he allegedly concealed his
involvement with the Nazis in order to become a naturalized U.S.
citizen.
   Kauls entered Canada in February 1951, entered the United States
in 1954, applied for permanent-resident status in Detroit and
became a U.S. citizen April 13, 1960, according to the complaint.
   A woman who answered the door at the Kauls' residence and
identified herself as Kauls' wife was asked about the allegations.
   ``That's not possible. We are United States citizens,'' she said.
   She refused to talk further with reporters.
   Neighbors said the couple rarely left their home in the
retirement community except to go shopping.
   Nazi hunters at the Simon Wiesenthal Center for Holocaust
Studies in Los Angeles and the Jewish Anti-Defamation League in New
York said they were not familiar with Kauls.
</TEXT>
