<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZeroTolerance-ACLU 1stLd-Writethru a0542 05-25 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zero Tolerance-ACLU, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0542,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami ACLU Takes On Zero Tolerance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with Coast Guard version of seizure.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weekend fisherman who enlisted the American Civil
Liberties Union to fight the federal government's ``Zero
Tolerance'' policy says he is outraged over the Coast Guard's
seizure of his boat for ``absolutely nothing.''
   ACLU lawyer Barbara S. Levenson said U.S. Customs has two days
to return the boat of Jean Sebastian Gros, 28, before the Miami
ACLU chapter plans to go to federal court seeking an injunction
against the Coast Guard and Customs for return of the boat.
   She said she filed a petition Tuesday with Customs for the
23-foot boat's return.
   The day before, Coast Guard and Customs Service officials
announced they were slightly refining the use of the Reagan
administration's policy under which boats, cars and other vehicles
have been confiscated if even a trace of illegal drugs is found in
them.
   The modifications prohibit the Coast Guard from seizing boats
outside the 12-mile territorial limit if there is no evidence of
intent to smuggle. Apart from those changes, however, Attorney
General Edwin Meese III said Tuesday there is ``no softening
whatsoever'' of the policy.
   Ms. Levenson said the ACLU is lining up challenges because she
is ``afraid we may be approaching a police state.''
   ``We feel that Mr. Gros represents many, many recreational boat
users who enjoy their boats, who ... are not drug dealers, but
merely Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer,'' she said. ``The reason for
`Zero Tolerance' does not justify suspension of the Constitution.''
   Gros, a Plantation resident, said Tuesday he is outraged over
the May 15 confiscation of his new $40,000 boat by the Coast Guard.
He uses it for his recreational fishing excursions to the Bahamas.
   ``They went through everything _ I mean my entire boat,'' said
Gros, a service station owner who insists he neither uses illegal
drugs nor condones their use.
   ``We had absolutely nothing on board. They never showed me what
they found,'' Gros said. ``They say they scraped up six grains,
approximately a gram, and it tested positive for THC (the active
ingredient in marijuana). It's simply not true.''
   Gros said his boat was searched by two armed Coast Guardsmen,
confiscated 7 miles off the Bahamanian island of Bimini, which is
beyond the 12-mile limit, and impounded at the Coast Guard Station
in Miami Beach about 45 miles away.
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. James Simpson said the Robalo at first
stopped for the Coast Guard, then ``took off running'' and was
chased for about five minutes before being boarded.
   ``The boarding team found about half a gram of substance on the
deck in the open behind the seat, tested that and it came up
positive,'' Simpson said. ``Based on one, the vessel fleeing
boarding by a Coast Guard vessel and two, finding a quantity of
controlled substance,'' a further search was authorized, Simpson
said.
   Small quantities of what tested as marijuana were subsequently
found on the boat's console and in a mop, he said.
</TEXT>
