<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0498 05-25 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consular Delegates Likely Heading to Moscow Next Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with officials confirming reports,
group leaving for Moscow next week. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of up to six Israeli diplomats will
leave for Moscow, possibly by next week, as the first Israelis to
take up consular duties there in 21 years, officials and news
reports said today.
   The Soviets agreed to issue visas to the Israelis at a secret
meeting in Zurich, Switzerland on Monday, said Foreign Ministry
political adviser Nimrod Novick, who negotiated for the visas.
   Novick told Israeli army radio the diplomats' main job in Moscow
will be to administer an embassy building for which Israel has been
paying monthly rent even though it has been empty for 21 years.
   Agreement for the visas came 10 months after Soviet consular
officials began operating from the Finnish Embassy in Tel Aviv.
   Novick said he hoped the consular visit to the Soviet Union
could lead to renewal of full diplomatic ties with Moscow, but
described the current agreement as less than a breakthrough.
   ``What we are talking about is dipping ourselves in the water to
check if it is hot or cold. It remains to be seen when our
delegates reach Moscow, how well they will be received,'' Novick
said.
   He added that the agreement followed two months of secret
contacts with Vladimir Terrasov, the deputy head of the Soviet
Foreign Ministry's Middle East department.
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic relations with Israel during
the 1967 Middle East War, when the Jewish state captured the West
Bank, Gaza Strip and Golan Heights from the Kremlin's Arab allies.
   Kremlin leaders have improved ties with Israel in the last two
years largely as part of an effort to become involved in
peacemaking efforts in the Middle East.
   The Soviets held numerous meetings with Israelis abroad and then
sent an eight-member consular team to Israel in July 1987.
   The Israeli diplomats will number as many as six and work from
the Dutch Embassy in processing visas for Soviet Jewish emigrants,
Israeli news reports and officials said.
   There was no date set for when the visas would be issued. But
one Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the Israeli diplomats could be on their way to Moscow as early
as next week.
   The Yediot Ahronot daily said the visas may come this week or in
advance of the superpower summmit in Moscow.
   Novick indicated that Israel had sought a broader role for its
diplomats, which would include handling visas for Soviet Jewish
emigrants.
   ``It looked like it was broadening things to the Soviets,''
Novick said, adding that now ``there is no argument between us and
the Soviets that our group will have a mandate as outlined, to
check out the Israeli Embassy building'' in Moscow.
   He added that the Soviets had agreed there would be ``no
restrictions'' placed on other contacts between the Israelis and
Jews in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolTakeover     05-25 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Takeover,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Recommends Takeover Of Jersey City Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jersey City's schools are in an ``advanced
stage of decay,'' New Jersey's education commissioner charged in
announcing the state will attempt to seize control of the
32,000-student district.
   It would be the first time a state has taken over such a big
urban district, New Jersey's second-largest, said the National
Governors Association in Washington.
   Education Commissioner Saul Cooperman, citing rampant political
patronage, mismanaged schools and chronic failure to educate the
district's students, began efforts to take over the district on
Tuesday.
   The school system in Jersey City, an ethnic melting pot of more
than 200,000 people, many of them recent immigrants, has come under
fire for poor test scores and a high dropout rate. The city is
across the Hudson River from New York City.
   An independent auditor's report cited by the state also charged
that jobs in the school system are treated as political paybacks,
and courses are so outdated that one on Africa failed to list 17
countries formed since 1958.
   ``As is true of other enterprises that reach such an advanced
stage of decay, the Jersey City school district offers a compelling
case for bolder, more decisive and non-traditional intervention by
higher public authorities,'' Cooperman said at a news conference.
   The commissioner said district administrators are incapable of
properly running the schools or fixing widespread problems.
   ``Political patronage, union pressure and cronyism is a
consistent motivation, at all levels, in the hiring, firing and
promoting of staff,'' he said.
   Under New Jersey legislation enacted five months ago, Cooperman
could abolish the local board of education, fire the superintendent
and top administrators and appoint a state superintendent to
operate the schools for at least five years.
   The law gives New Jersey officials some of the broadest powers
in the nation to take control of deficient school districts.
   The district has 10 days to accept Cooperman's decision or
respond with reasons why it shouldn't be taken over.
   Jersey City Board of Education spokeswoman Leslie Silberman said
the panel would not comment on Cooperman's recommendation until
reviewing the report.
   Meanwhile, the state Division of Criminal Justice is to
determine whether local officials have committed any crimes.
   Auditors found inadequate record keeping, missing contract
documents and questionable payroll, personnel and procurement
practices. The district has wasted more than $1.2 million on an
improper health insurance plan, the report said.
   Richard Kaplan, who ran a separate investigation for the state,
said employees routinely were rewarded or demoted based upon which
mayoral candidate they backed in the Democratic stronghold.
   In addition, curriculum guides in Jersey City are so outdated
that a course guide for a high school class on Africa fails to list
17 countries formed between 1958 and 1980, and lists four countries
that no longer exist.
   Teachers weren't optimistic Tuesday that state control would end
the district's problems.
   Mike Bogart, a grammar school teacher, said over time, rules
have been forgotten and replaced with double standards. ``We can't
come back, but I guess we've got to try,'' Bogart said.
   Schools Superintendent Franklin Williams has said if the
district were properly funded, the state would not need to take it
over.
   He also said that conditions are not as bad as the state
maintains and that many problems stem from the city's high crime
rate, and drug problems and poverty among district students, many
of whom are homeless or do not speak English.
   Cooperman countered that the district has enough money, but it
hasn't been properly spent. ``It's bleak,'' he said. ``I've read
everything and respect the superintendent. The facts are stubborn
things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
