<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MotherSentenced     05-25 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mother Sentenced,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Accused of Abandoning Children Ordered To Remain On Birth
Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a young woman to remain on
birth control for the rest of her child-bearing years for
abandoning her two young sons in a sweltering apartment last summer.
   Debra Ann Forster's attorney and the head of the American Civil
Liberties Union in Arizona objected to the sentence Tuesday as a
violation of the 18-year-old Mesa woman's constitutional rights.
   Superior Court Judge Lindsay Ellis Budzyn sentenced Ms. Forster
to lifetime probation and ordered her to give regular written proof
to her probation officer that she is on birth control.
   ``Your case represents the epitome of what's wrong with our
society: A child having children,'' the judge said.
   Ms. Forster pleaded guilty in April to two counts of attempted
felony child abuse.
   Her estranged husband found the two boys _ ages 18 months and 6
months _ in the apartment where police say they had been left alone
for two days.
   The children were suffering from malnutrition, dehydration and
lesions caused by a rash and were hospitalized in serious condition
for eight days.
   Police said Ms. Forster told them she left the children because
she was unable to cope with the pressure of caring for them. She
said she had used drugs to escape from the pressures and had
attempted suicide, police reported.
   Louis Rhodes, executive director of the ACLU in Arizona, called
the sentence a ``stunning violation of a person's right,'' and
Robert Billar, a deputy public defender, said it violated her right
to privacy.
   But the judge said Ms. Forster's ``lack of nurturing'' and the
``close call the children had with death'' merited such an order.
   The judge also barred Ms. Foster from seeing her sons or the
daughter she bore in prison two months ago. She also was told that
she cannot babysit for others.
   Court records show that Ms. Forster's daughter has been adopted
and that her sons also have been put up for adoption.
   ``I know I did something wrong, and I have to pay for it. I'm
sorry,'' a tearful Ms. Foster she told the judge.
</TEXT>
