<2ND_LINE>PM-Body Found,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Victim Found In Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 63-year-old man who raised his
window shade every morning to let neighbors know he was all right
was found slain after he failed to give the signal.
   Neighbors who entered William J. Carr's house Tuesday afternoon
found his body in his upstairs bedroom with his throat slit, his
hands bound with an electrical cord and a rope tied around his
neck, police said.
   Carr had apparently been dead for 24 to 36 hours, police said.
Police Chief Donald Oliver said police found three knives on the
bureau in Carr's bedroom and were searching for his car, which was
missing.
   Grace Skipp, a next-door neighbor, said she and her landlord did
not react immediately to the drawn shade because Carr's car was not
in his driveway. Skipp said she and the landlord assumed Carr had
gone out and forgot to raise the shade.
   Carr's dog led Skipp and the landlord to the body when they
finally decided to go inside and check.
   Carr, a bachelor who lived alone, arranged with his neighbors to
watch the window shade after he had a heart attack several years
ago, Skipp said.
</TEXT>
