<DOCNO> AP880525-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Army     05-25 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Army,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yazov Criticizes Readiness, Discipline of Soviet Forces in East
Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov says Soviet
soldiers in East Germany lack discipline and battle preparedness,
the ministry daily Krasnaya Zvezda reported today.
   Red Star said Yazov addressed a special meeting of senior army
officers from the East German detachment, estimated by Western
sources to number about 380,000 soldiers, as part of the
preparations for next month's Communist Party conference.
   He pressed for reform of the military units stationed in the
allied country and championed Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policy of ``perestroika,'' or rebuilding, as the appropriate
foundation for building a better fighting force.
   Yazov, who became head of the Kremlin's armed forces a year ago,
appeared to be stumping for the leader's policies among military
officials before the party conference, which is expected to be a
faceoff between reform advocates and conservatives.
   He made the address in East Germany, but the newspaper did not
say when or in what city the gathering took place.
   The defense minister provided no specific examples of poor
performance by the troops serving in East Germany, but he delivered
a largely critical report on their military preparedness, according
to the newspaper.
   Yazov blamed the substandard conditions within the military
units on ``stagnant tendencies, low attentiveness and
oversimplification.''
   ``The Communist Party of the Soviet Union, the Soviet people
demand of us that we liquidate these negative tendencies in the
army which are harming military readiness,'' Yazov told the
officers.
   It was not clear how many were present for his scolding, but the
newspaper said the meeting was attended by several other generals
and staff members of the Soviet Military Council, Marshal Nikolai
V. Ogarkov and the Soviet ambassador to East Germany.
   ``Many of the party organizations of the GSSG (Group of Soviet
Soldiers in Germany) have yet to show themselves to be generators
of perestroika,'' Yazov was quoted as saying.
   The newspaper said he brought up ``problems of improving the
quality of military preparedness and gave constructive
recommendations'' for change. Red Star did not report Yazov's
suggestions.
   Yazov told the meeting that part of the problem was adherence to
the ``administrative-command'' form of management, a phrase that
has come to refer to the leadership style of late dictator Josef V.
Stalin.
   The gap between commanders and leaders and their subordinates
must be narrowed and the needs, concerns and interests of the
soldiers taken into consideration in all decision-making, the
newspaper quoted Yazov as saying.
   Yazov was named to succeed Marshal Sergei L. Sokolov on May 30,
1987, two days after West German teen-age pilot Mathias Rust
slipped past the Soviet Air Defense forces in the Baltic, flew his
single-engine plane undetered over more than 500 miles of Soviet
territory and landed in Red Square.
   Yazov became a candidate, or non-voting member, of the ruling
Politburo a month later. He has called for reform of the military
services in the few articles and speeches he has given.
   Yazov met with his American counterpart, Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci, in Switzerland in March.
</TEXT>
