<HEAD>Iraq Announces Major Offensive Near Basra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with new Iraqi claims, peace
conference opening in Baghdad, Vernon Walters in Middle East. Edits
to trim. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it launched a major ground
offensive east of Basra today to retake Iraqi territory captured by
Iran 16 months ago. Iran said it repulsed the attack.
   Iraq also said its warplanes destroyed a power station in
northern Iran, and Tehran said a separate Iraqi air raid killed 28
civilians in northwestern Iran.
   The latest hostilities coincided with the opening in Baghdad of
a ``Global Popular Conference on Peace'' attended by delegates from
dozens of countries.
   State-run Baghdad radio broke into regular programming to
broadcast a military communique announcing the Iraqi ground
offensive. It said Iraqi forces made ``considerable gains'' in the
operation code-named ``On God We Depend,'' but it gave no casualty
figures.
   ``Our men attacked the enemy forces to get rid of them and crush
their heads, which are empty of human values,'' the communique said.
   A later communique carried by the state-run Iraqi News Agency
said Iraqi forces took the southern end of Fish Lake, a large body
of water created by the Iraqis on the border as an obstacle to
Iranian attack.
   The lake was the scene of fierce fighting when Iran took the
area in January 1987.
   Iraqi troops, including elite Presidential Guards, also took the
Jasim River running through the area, as well as two police posts
that had been occupied by the Iranians, the communique said.
   The attack came after warnings by Iraq that it could launch a
major offensive if Iran continued to reject a settlement of the
nearly 8-year-old Persian Gulf war. It also came the day after Iraq
warned it would retaliate for alleged Iranian shelling of Iraqi
border towns.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said the ground attack was
repulsed. It said fighting was continuing but Iranian forces held
their ground, ``vigilantly defending their positions.''
   Iranian forces in January 1987 advanced on a 25-mile-wide front
to within six miles of the southern town of Basra and have held
much of that territory since.
   The Iranian agency reported an Iraqi thrust in the northern
Iraqi Sulaymaniyah region but said it was crushed with the
attackers sustaining ``heavy losses and casualties.''
   Iraqi air raids on the northwestern Iranian border town of
Sardasht killed 28 civilians, Iran said. Iraq did not comment on
the claim.
   The Iraqi News Agency said warplanes flew more than 600 miles to
bomb a power station near the Caspian Sea 125 miles northeast of
Tehran, ``turning it into ashes.'' Iran said the bombs hit workers'
houses but reported no casualties.
   Iraq's news agency said the peace conference in Baghdad was
attended by a ``large number of political and social figures'' from
various countries.
   Tehran radio said Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi told
reporters that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's ``aim in holding
the so-called peace conference is only to prevent disclosure of
facts in regard with identification of the aggressor.'' Iran has
said it will not agree to a cease-fire unless Iraq first is branded
the aggressor in the war.
   Elsewhere today, Vernon Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations, arrived in the United Arab Emirates for talks on
means for achieving a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war and for
resolving the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Walters is on a Middle East tour that has taken him so far to
Israel, Syria, Jordan, Iraq, Kuwait and Oman. His itinerary also
includes Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and Turkey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
