<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   05-25 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0556,0846</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Arab wounded, indictment
of Israeli in death of Arab, drive to clean up of anti-Israeli
graffiti, PICKS UP graf 14 pvs `The only...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike commemorating a slain
Palestinian military leader virtually shut down the occupied
territories today, and the army clamped a curfew on at least five
refugee camps and Arab villages.
   In the West Bank, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded a
Palestinian youth during a clash with young men throwing stones and
bottles in the Nur Shams refugee camp, officials at Rafidiyeh
Hospital said.
   A military spokesman confirmed that a youth was shot in the camp
today. Hospital officials said the victim, Nasser Sulayman, was in
critical condition with a gunshot wound in the chest.
   Tuesday night, soldiers shot and wounded an 18-year-old
Palestinian during a similar clash with stone-throwers in the West
Bank town of Tulkarem, officials at Tulkarem Hospital said. Army
officials said they had no information on the report.
   During today's general strike, an indefinite curfew was placed
on the Dheishe refugee camp, largest in the West Bank, and four
locations in the Gaza Strip.
   The strike was called to mark the end of mourning 40 days after
the assassination in Tunisia of Khalil Wazir, also known as Abu
Jihad. He was military chief of Fatah, the largest faction in the
Palestine Liberation Organization, and deputy to PLO chief Yasser
Arafat.
   Palestinian, Israeli, and other sources say Israeli commandos
carried out the attack, but the Israeli government has declined
comment.
   Ahmed Wazir, a cousin of the slain PLO leader, said Israeli
soldiers showed up at his Gaza City house today to prevent a
reception marking the assassination.
   ``The army is outside our house,'' Wazir said in a telephone
interview. ``They turned back anyone who came here.''
   In walled, old city of Jerusalem, a firebomb was thrown Tuesday
at the car of Trade and Commerce Minister Ariel Sharon, as his
wife, Lily, was about to drive from their home, the daily Maariv
newspaper reported.
   No casualties were reported. The paper quoted Mrs. Sharon as
saying she was not even aware the firebomb was thrown. ``Maybe they
should try again,'' she was quoted as saying.
   Israel radio reported, meanwhile, that the military government
in the occupied territories threatened to jail Arab property owners
for up to five years if they do not wash anti-Israeli graffiti from
their buildings and remove outlawed Palestinian flags.
   The military had no immediate comment on the report, which said
those who did not comply could also be fined $9,670.
   Israeli authorities are attempting to put down resistance to
their occupation of the territories, which they seized in the 1967
Middle East War. Since Dec. 8, at least 195 Palestinians and two
Israelis have been killed in the unrest.
   An Israeli today was indicted for manslaughter in the fatal
shooting of a Palestinian shepherd on May 5 near the Jewish
settlement of Shiloh in the West Bank, Israel radio reported.
   It quoted the indictment as saying Yisrael Zeev fired at a group
of Arab shepherds just after they shouted to him that they would
stop grazing sheep on disputed land near Shiloh. One of the
shepherds was killed and another wounded.
   Stores were closed in the Gaza Strip and West Bank,
transportation was shut down, and most Palestinian workers did not
go to jobs in Israel.
   Witnesses said the general strike was observed throughout the
occupied land and Israeli-annexed Arab east Jerusalem.
   ``The Intefadah (Arab for uprising) is still going on and will
continue until victory and the creation of our independent state,''
said an underground leaflet signed by the PLO@Unified Command of
the Uprising in the Occupied Territories.
   The only commerce today seemed to be vendors selling newspapers
and doughnut-shaped bread covered with sesame seeds that is an Arab
staple.
   West Bank primary schools, where classes resumed Monday for the
first time in four months, were open despite the strike. Government
spokesman Olivier Rafovicz said about 90 percent of the 200,000
students attended.
   The return to school apparently has the support of Arab
underground leaders who wrote in the latest leaflet, the 17th
issued since December: ``We will continue in the civilized path of
our people by more learning and education.''
   Israeli army officials have said they would open West Bank high
schools if students did not participate in demonstrations.
   The government today charged two editors of the left-wing
newspaper Derech Hanitzotz with membership in a guerrilla
organization and having contacts with a foreign agent, Israel radio
reported. The two, Yaacov Ben Efrat and Assaf Adiv, face up to 40
years in jail if convicted.
   Earlier this week, the government indicted two other newspaper
employees on the same charges.
   The four are accused of belonging to the Democratic Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, a radical PLO faction.
</TEXT>
