<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0569,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Syria Warns Kidnappers Not To Harm Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Belgian doctor missing.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Most of...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria warned kidnappers that any harm
done to Western hostages in Lebanon would be an ``infringement of
Syria's security,'' the independent Beirut newspaper An-Nahar
reported today.
   The prestigious daily cited no source for its 15-word report,
which failed to say how and when the warning was conveyed or what
the Syrian reaction would be if the warning was not heeded.
   Also today, the Norwegian Aid Committee announced that a Belgian
doctor helping Palestinians in south Lebanon disappeared four days
ago after leaving his base at the Rashidiyeh refugee camp, two
miles south of the port of Tyre.
   A statement released by the committee said Dr. Jan Cools, 32,
disappeared at 2 p.m. Saturday. Coots, a general practitioner, has
been on a voluntary mission in Lebanon since February. No group has
claimed kidnapping him.
   Fears for the 18 confirmed hostages, including nine Americans,
have been roused by almost three weeks of fighting between
Iranian-backed fundamentalists and pro-Syrian Shiite Moslem
militiamen in Beirut's southern slums.
   Most of the kidnapped foreigners in Lebanon are believed held in
the embattled slums by extremist factions affiliated with
Hezbollah, or Party of God, Iran's main ally in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah's fighters have seized control of 95 percent of the
slums in the fighting with Justice Minister Nabih Berri's
Syrian-armed Amal militia.
   Police say 296 people have been killed and 1,000 wounded since
the hostilities broke out May 6.
   They said Hezbollah appeared to be marshaling its forces today
for a push into the sprawling Shiyah district to flush out Amal
from its last remaining stronghold in the slums.
   Sporadic shell blasts resounded across Beirut this morning, but
police said no new casualties have been reported from the slums war.
   Syria has 7,500 troops, 100 tanks and 400 armored vehicles
massed in hills and dunes surrounding the slums, a warren of 16
square miles of narrow alleyways and cement-block shanties.
   But a dispute with Iran over ways of ending the fighting has
delayed a Syrian push into the slums.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, apparently alarmed by
Hezbollah's triumph, traveled to Damascus today. Several Beirut
radio stations said he would officially request Syria's military
intervention to halt the slums war.
   ``Hezbollah's expansion heralds the fall of west Beirut,''
warned a front-page headline in the conservative Beirut newspaper
Al-Anwar.
   West Beirut has a predominantly Sunni Moslem population. Sunnis
generally reject Iranian patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
brand of Islamic fundamentalism.
   Syria has another army contingent of 7,500 troops in charge of
west Beirut's security. That force was sent on Feb. 22, 1987 at the
request of Lebanese Moslem government leaders to curb militia
anarchy in the capital's Moslem sector.
   Hoss, a Sunni, went immediately upon his arrival in Damascus
into a closed-door conference with Syrian Vice President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam, that nation's top expert on Lebanese affairs.
   Police said Tuesday that Hezbollah fighters had mopped up the
last pockets of Amal resistance in the southern suburb of Ghobeiri
in house-to-house combat.
   Beirut radio stations said three Syrian soldiers were killed by
a stray shell that slammed into their checkpoint on the airport
highway on Tuesday. Police and the Syrian command refused to
comment on the report.
   No clear word on the fate of the hostages has emerged since the
fight for the Shiite slums began.
   Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, is the hostage held longest. He was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
