<DOCNO> AP880525-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HowardBeach     05-25 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Howard Beach,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Plead in Howard Beach Case; Five Defendants Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five defendants remain in the second Howard
Beach racial attack trial after two young men pleaded guilty to
riot charges _ one of them in a secret hearing made public by an
appeals court.
   Salvatore DeSimone, 20, entered his plea Tuesday before jury
selection resumed for the remaining defendants in the case, in
which a black man was beaten and another was chased to his death in
front of a car by a gang of whites.
   After DeSimone's plea, state Supreme Court Justice Thomas
Demakos unsealed transcripts of a May 19 hearing that revealed
Harry Buonocore, 19, also pleaded guilty to riot.
   Under the plea bargains, Buonocore and DeSimone will receive
five years' probation and 200 hours of community service. The riot
charge is punishable by up to four years in prison.
   Four of the five remaining defendants face riot charges in the
case; the fifth also is charged with attempted murder and assault.
   In the first trial last year, three young men were convicted of
manslaughter. A fourth was acquitted of all charges.
   Under his plea, Buonocore may testify against the remaining
defendants. DeSimone's plea ensures he will not have to, said his
lawyer, Augustus Agate.
   The plea bargains surprised one of the remaining defendants,
John Saggese, who reasserted his innocence.
   ``I'm not guilty of riot,'' Saggese said. ``I don't think Sal is
guilty. I couldn't have done it. I don't think anyone should have
plea-bargained at all.''
   DeSimone also pleaded guilty to criminal facilitation for
driving members of a white gang to the confrontation with three
blacks in 1986. The melee in the city's Howard Beach section left
23-year-old Michael Griffith dead.
   Buonocore's plea was entered at a secret proceeding before
Demakos. On Monday, a four-judge state appellate panel ruled
unanimously in favor of a motion by The New York Times to unseal
the transcript.
   The panel said Demakos is prohibited from excluding the news
media and public from any future plea proceedings in the case.
   Buonocore's attorney, Edward M. Rappaport, was in court Tuesday
and unavailable for comment on whether his client would testify.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
