<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolChauffeurs     05-25 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Chauffeurs,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Board Votes to Discontinue Using Chauffeurs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The School Board has barred its members from
taking chauffeur-driven cars at taxpayer expense, averting a
threatened cutoff of $30 million in state money.
   Clara Rutherford and Rose Mary Osborne, who had refused to join
fellow board members in giving up chauffeur-driven cars to take
them to and from evening meetings, were silent in the voice vote
Tuesday night.
   The decision came two weeks after state Treasurer Robert Bowman
said he would withhold the money from the school district, which
has a deficit of more than $60 million, unless Rutherford and
Osborne relented.
   School officials said earlier the district would fail to meet
its May 31 payroll without the money.
   Bowman said the $30 million should be available by Friday.
   The 11-member board has been criticized for using chauffeurs
despite financial problems. The district cut $16 million from its
budget last year and plans to eliminate 515 jobs in the fall and
close 13 school buildings within two years.
   Osborne had maintained that female board members need chauffeurs
for protection when traveling to and from evening meetings. She
also said she had poor night vision and couldn't drive safely.
   A survey showed the district paid about $500,000 in salaries,
overtime and bonuses to 12 drivers assigned to the board in 1986
and the first five months of 1987.
   Board members receive $30 for each meeting they attend. They are
also reimbursed for expenses.
</TEXT>
