<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-BeautyContest     05-25 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Beauty Contest,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beijing Follows Other Cities, Cancels Beauty Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beijing's first beauty contest has been called
off because such pageantry would be unsuitable when so many people
are living in poverty, organizers said today.
   The cancellation came after other cities across China called off
scheduled beauty pageants.
   ``In Beijing, conditions for such an event are not ripe,'' said
Long Xinmin, head of Beijing Television Studio, one of the
scheduled sponsors. He cited China's low standard of living.
   Shanghai scrapped its ``Shanghai Maiden'' contest two weeks ago,
also saying that ``conditions are not ripe.''
   Long said Beijing's decision was not influenced by the other
cancellations.
   The Beijing contest to select 10 ``Girls of Youth and Elegance''
entered the semifinals last week. The 10 winners were to have been
selected in early June.
   The event, open to Beijing women between the ages of 17 and 27,
drew 842 applicants. The field was narrowed down to 50 contestants
after two stages.
   Foreign reporters were barred from attending preliminary events
and were told they could only cover the finals. They also were
barred from China's first beauty pageant since the 1949 communist
victory, apparently because of fears of negative publicity. That
pageant was in Canton in 1985.
   After Beijing announced its pageant plans in April, at least
half a dozen cities also held local beauty contests.
   Kunming, Yunnan province, was the first to finish, selecting its
``Miss Spring City'' in early May.
   But beauty contest plans in other cities met with disapproval
from many people who said such events were improper when many
people in China are living in poverty.
   Newspaper commentators in Shanghai said the city was facing
economic and other problems that require ``leaders and the 12
million city residents to be of one heart and one mind and to
quietly immerse themselves in hard work. It is premature to spend
450,00 yuan ($126,000) on a beauty pageant.''
   Miss ``Empress Cup'' of the coastal province of Fujian will be
awarded 15,000 yuan, or $4,054, worth of prizes. That's the
equivalent of 10 years' pay for the average Chinese worker.
   Supporters of the pageants argue that the events would educate
people on the correct standards of beauty and help raise awareness
of grooming and manners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
