<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0585,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Looking to Fifth Summit on Strategic Arms, Paper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS thruout to ADD the president urging NATO partners to
share more defense costs, comment on glasnost, attitude toward
Gorbachev, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan still hopes for a
strategic missile treaty with the Soviet Union and says there may
be a fifth summit with Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
according to a newspaper report made available today.
   The conservative newspaper Die Welt also said Reagan is urging
other NATO member nations to pick up more of the Western alliance's
defense costs.
   Die Welt said the interview was conducted shortly before Reagan
departed for the upcoming summit in Moscow. It said the interview
would appear in its Thursday editions but sent it by telex in
advance to other news media.
   ``President Ronald Reagan figures that the START treaty, which
foresees the halving of nuclear intercontinental missiles, still
can be brought to completion before the end of his term,'' the
Bonn-based newspaper said.
   Die Welt did not provide a direct quote from Reagan regarding
his hopes for such a treaty.
   Reagan told Die Welt and four other European newspapers that the
Soviets also are interested in reaching an intercontinental missile
treaty with him, rather than waiting for his successor.
   ``Therefore, the president doesn't exclude the possibility of a
fifth summit conference with Gorbachev this year on neutral
ground,'' the newspaper said, again without providing a direct
quote.
   The Moscow summit starting Sunday with be the fourth meeting
between the two leaders. Reagan met with Gorbachev in Geneva in
November 1985; Reykjavik, Iceland, in October 1986; and Washington
in December 1987.
   In his interview, Reagan also urged other NATO members to pick
up more of the expenses for maintaining military defense forces of
the alliance.
   ``I don't think this is an area that should cause bad blood
between us,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying. ``But it would be
helpful if the allies would carry more of the load, especially
since the American Congress for years has declined to approve
further increases for defense.''
   Reagan's quotes were provided in German and translated by The
Associated Press.
   Reagan also said it was good that Gorbachev's program of
Glasnost, or more openness, is being practiced in other communist
nations, the newspaper reported.
   Referring to his relationship with Gorbachev, Reagan was quoted
by Die Welt as saying: ``We can discuss delicate issues without
lingering personal bad feelings. I believe there is actually a
certain degree of friendship between us.''
</TEXT>
