<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Military     05-25 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Military,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Denies Sharing Military Technology with Argentina, Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today issued a series of denials about its
activities on the world arms market, including reports that it
helped Pakistan launch a missile and that it agreed to share
technology for missile production with Argentina.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing denied reports that
Chinese leaders agreed to supply Argentina with technology for
producing anti-ship and medium-range missiles capable of hitting
the Falkland Islands.
   In 1982, Argentina lost a war to Britain over the islands, which
it calls the Malvinas.
   A report in The Sunday Times in London said China and Argentina
signed a secret agreement during President Raul Alfonsin's visit to
China last week. It said the agreement was for cooperation rather
than sale of missiles and that China in return would receive access
to Argentine research stations.
   Li said no such agreement was discussed.
   He also denied reports that China helped Pakistan test fire a
missile capable of carrying a nuclear warhead.
   ``The allegation about China's assistance in Pakistan's
launching of a medium-range missile is utterly groundless,'' Li
said of a report that appeared in The New York Times on Tuesday.
   It said Pakistan launched a missile April 25 that was produced
with the help of Chinese experts and that is capable of reaching
the Indian cities of Bombay and New Delhi.
   Li also called ``groundless'' news reports that Israel helped
develop Chinese ground-to-ground missiles sold to Saudi Arabia.
   On Tuesday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Shamir also denied
the Washington Post report that said Israeli scientists improved
the guidance systems of the Chinese CSS-2 medium-range missile
deployed in Saudi Arabia.
   Li said he knew nothing about a report in the British
publication, Jane's Defense Weekly, that China had sold mine
sweepers to Thailand and agreed to sell submarines.
   China last spring sold tanks, armored personel carriers and
small arms to Thailand reportedly valued at $10 million.
   Li also denied a report in the U.S. media that China helped the
United States obtain Soviet weapons from Afghanistan for study by
the Defense Department.
   China has become a major arms supplier to Third World countries.
According to some estimates, China is the fifth largest seller of
arms in the world behind the Soviet Union., United States, Britain
and France.
   China has been a major supplier of arms to both Iran and Iraq in
their nearly 8-year-old war.
</TEXT>
