<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0488 05-25 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says ``Liberal Elite'' Undermine Defense Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush address in top 14 grafs, picking up in 10th
graf pvs, During the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today accused
a ``liberal elite'' of seeking to undermine U.S. defense and said
that while he was encouraged by the upcoming superpower summit,
``we cannot wish away the Soviet Union as a competitor.''
   The Republican presidential contender, addressing a graduation
ceremony at the U.S. Military Academy, said the times require
leadership that ``will pursue negotiations with the Soviet
realistically.''
   Standing in a pouring rain during the outdoor ceremony, Bush
told the graduating cadets that summits such as the one in Moscow
beginning this weekend ``are good in and of themselves, for they
contribute to an atmosphere of peace and familiarity.''
   However, Bush said Americans must not become too complacent
about a Soviet threat just because the two sides are talking.
   In what was billed by his aides as a non-political speech, Bush
lashed out at liberals.
   However, he praised the late President John F. Kennedy for
standing firm against the Soviets in Cuba, saying that Kennedy's
acts were in line with a bipartisan consensus on dealing with the
Soviets that had prevailed from the 1940s.
   ``But by the '70s the consensus had fractured, splintered, the
center did not hold,'' Bush said.
   ``The liberal elite do not understand, they never understood,
the common sense behind'' the former approach to the Soviets, Bush
told the graduating cadets.
   ``They are so blinded by ideology that they cannot see what
Americans have understood for 40 years: that peace flows from
strength,'' he said.
   Bush said that such people, whom he did not identify, ``will
make the world more dangerous.''
   The vice president addressed the graduating class of 849 men and
90 women.
   Bush was campaigning later today in New Jersey, then was heading
to his oceanfront vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine. While
Reagan is in Moscow, Bush is to spend the next week meeting with
advisers and Republican leaders with an eye to sharpening his
strategy for the fall campaign.
   Republican advisers in recent days, mindful of recent polls
showing Bush trailing Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis, have
urged the candidate to come up with more specifics on campaign
issues that will help to separate him from the administration's
recent problems.
   His aides are portraying the Maine visit as low-profile and say
they expect the vice president to do more listening than newsmaking
while the public spotlight is on the Moscow summit.
   During the time in Kennebunkport, Bush will ``be meeting with
(Republican) governors, senators, congressmen, people with
expertise in economic and domestic affairs,'' said campaign
spokesman Peter Teeley.
   ``Basically, he'll be discussing issues, and looking at these
issues in relation to the general election.''
   Despite his continued efforts to identify himself with
accomplishments of the Reagan administration, Bush in recent weeks
has staked out his own stands apart from Reagan's on issues ranging
from education to day care and the environment.
   He has also put some distance between himself and the
administration's efforts to strike a deal with Panamanian military
leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, including the possibility of
dropping drug charges in exchange for his relinquishing of power.
   Bush has said that, if elected, he would not negotiate with drug
traffickers. And aides said Bush privately has urged that talks
with Noriega be broken off.
   On Tuesday, House Republicans met for 90 minutes with top Bush
campaign officials. Participants said Bush was applauded at the
meeting for differing with Reagan on Noriega.
   ``It's a very symbolic circumstance, where Bush has moved from
being vice president to being his own candidate,'' said Rep. Jim
Leach of Iowa.
   ``Almost to a person they were pleased about the separation on
Noriega,'' said Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois.
   Bush's poor showing in recent polls, showing he was behind
Dukakis in a hypothetical fall matchup by margins ranging from 7 to
16 percentage points, was also discussed at the session, according
to participants.
   ``We have bad polls. If this were October we'd be suicidal. But
it's May,'' Martin said. But, she added, ``There wasn't anybody up
screaming, `My God, we've got the Titanic.' The seas are rough.''
   The Republican lawmakers met with Lee Atwater, the Bush campaign
manager; Craig Fuller, the vice president's chief of staff, and
pollster Robert Teeter.
   Teeter shrugged off the recent polls and said he told the House
members ``we're in a very artificial period, that period when
Dukakis has been rolling along. What you got to do is get past this
California primary before people begin to focus on it (the
presidential race).''
   California and New Jersey both hold primaries on June 7.
   After speaking in West Point, Bush was to speak to a group of
senior citizens in Lakewood, N.J., and attend a GOP rally in Jersey
City.
   On Thursday, he planned several campaign stops in the Newark
area before heading to Maine.
</TEXT>
