<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Hijack-Shooting 5thLd-Writethru a0614 05-25 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack-Shooting, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0614,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Shoots Himself After Hijacking Private Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with airport official saying man was a
mechanic with no pilot's license; ADDS background on Flight
International, report that jet hit a security van as it took off.
ADDS that plane was a twin-engine. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight mechanic without a pilot's license stole
a private jet in Virginia early today and took it on a 1,600-mile
joyride to Denver, where he shot himself as authorities closed in,
officials said.
   ``The indication was that he just wanted to fly around for a
while,'' said Richard Boulware, spokesman for Stapleton
International Airport.
   Denver police, FBI agents and emergency vehicles were waiting at
the edge of a runway at the airport when the twin-engine Learjet 36
came to a stop in a landing an airport spokesman said appeared to
be that of a proficient pilot.
   ``As the crash crew and law enforcement personnel approached, he
was ordered to lock his brakes,'' said Boulware. ``They heard a
noise and when they looked in the cockpit they found him dead.
Things happened really fast.''
   The man, Mike Christiansen, 24, of Newport News, Va., was alone
in the jet stolen from his employer, Flight International, at
Patrick Henry International Airport in Newport News, where the
plane sideswiped a security van as it took off, said airport
spokesman Pete Daikos.
   ``We're not sure whether he had a gun when he started, but when
he landed he was surrounded and he shot himself, shot and killed
himself,'' said Dick Stafford, a Federal Aviation Administration
spokesman in Washington.
   Daikos said at a news conference in Newport News that
Christiansen had been a flight mechanic at Flight International
since March. He said Christiansen did not have a pilot's license.
   ``This is bizarre,'' Boulware said. ``Rarely do you find someone
stealing a plane like this worth millions of dollars.''
   ``This guy obviously was a proficient pilot,'' he said. ``He
made a good landing right in the middle of the runway with no
damage to the plane or the runway.''
   Daikos said the man is believed to be a former resident of the
Denver area. No one saw him armed, he said.
   Atlanta-based Flight International performs ground services for
corporate aircraft and airlines and operates the world's largest
fleet of Learjets, Daikos said.
   Daikos said Flight International also ``is a major contractor
with the armed forces to test defense mechanisms by challenging
them.'' He said some of the Learjets have classified electronic
gear, but the stolen plane was not believed to be so equipped.
   Gordon James, executive vice president of Flight International,
confirmed that the man was an employee but refused further comment.
   John Hill of the Peninsula Airport Commission security staff,
which oversees the Newport News airport, reported receiving a call
about 2:15 a.m. from a guard who told him an aircraft was being
stolen, Daikos said.
   Hill drove onto the runway in a van and got out, Daikos said.
The airplane apparently hit the van, damaging the driver's side and
leaving what appeared to be part of a wingtip fuel tank on the
runway, Daikos said. No one was injured.
   Air traffic controllers at several airports had tracked the
plane for parts of the flight across the country, Stafford said.
Controllers in Longmont picked up the plane over Colorado Springs,
south of Denver, according to Boulware.
   The jet landed at 5:18 a.m.
   ``We got an experienced Lear 36 pilot up in the Stapleton
control tower and he managed to talk him down into a good
landing,'' Boulware said.
   According to Jane's All The World's Aircraft, the Learjet has a
flight range of about 1,640 miles when carrying four passengers and
a full load of fuel.
   Flight experts here said the Learjet 36 is designed to seat two
crew members and 11 passengers, although Boulware said this plane
could seat six or seven passengers.
   Boulware said the plane was picked up at 39,000 feet. He said
the Learjet cruises at about 500 mph.
</TEXT>
