<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ValleyQuintuplets     05-25 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Valley Quintuplets,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Says She Never Expected Quintuplets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McALLEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria Esther Chavez said doctors told her
she would probably have twins. She delivered quintuplets.
   Mrs. Chavez gave birth to three boys and two girls by Caesarean
section early Tuesday at McAllen Medical Center.
   ``They told me two,'' the surprised mother said Tuesday in
Spanish.
   The babies, whom hospital officials were calling ``Babies A
through E,'' were listed in stable condition this morning. Their
weight ranged from two pounds, three ounces to three pounds, said
hospital spokeswoman Nelda Hernandez.
   ``They're fine, thanks to God,'' said Mrs. Chavez, a 28-year-old
resident of Reynosa, Mexico. Her 41-year-old husband, Baldemar
Chavez, was working in Mexico and could not be reached for comment.
   She was visiting her parents in the Lower Rio Grande Valley city
of Pharr on Monday when she went into labor, said Dr. John Garcia,
the attending physician.
   ``We delivered both and then I said, `Wait everybody, here's
another one,''' Garcia said, adding that neonatologist Ramiro
Caballero ``let out an exclamation point which I will not repeat.''
   ``And then we told him we had four, then we had five and it was
really exciting,'' Garcia said.
   Garcia, who had examined Mrs. Chavez three times before, had
told her she probably would have twins. She had not taken fertility
drugs, which often are associated with multiple births, he said.
   ``A few years back, these babies would have had a poor chance of
survival, but now with the neonatology advances, these babies have
an excellent chance,'' Garcia said.
   Mrs. Chavez said she and her husband have one other child, a
4-year-old girl.
   Asked if she planned to have any more children, she answered
with an emphatic, ``No.''
</TEXT>
