<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0615 05-25 0995</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0615,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Reaps Congressional Endorsements; Bush Heads to West Point</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush at West Point in top 6 grafs, picking up in
3rd graf pvs, On a; subs 11th graf pvs, Dukakis is, to update
delegate count; deletes graf 19-21 pvs, Bush himself ... it's
May.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today accused a ``liberal elite'' of
chipping away at a national consensus that the United States must
deal from strength in approaching the Soviet Union. Democratic
presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis reaped endorsements on
Capitol Hill before flying west for a debate with Jesse Jackson.
   Bush, the all-but-certain Republican nominee, used the
graduation ceremony at West Point to say that the 1980s require
leadership that ``will pursue negotiations with the Soviet
realistically.''
   Speaking as President Reagan was leaving for the Moscow summit,
Bush said such superpower meetings ``are good in and of themselves,
for they contribute to an atmosphere of peace and familiarity.''
However, he added, ``We cannot wish away the Soviet Union as a
competitor.''
   Without naming names, he said, ``The liberal elite do not
understand, they never understood, the common sense behind'' what
he said was a former consensus on dealing with the Soviet Union.
``They are so blinded by ideology that they cannot see what
Americans have understood for 40 years: that peace flows from
strength,'' he told the graduating cadets.
   One day earlier, Bush picked up what could prove to be an
unwelcome piece of baggage on the campaign trail _ Reagan's veto of
a big trade bill.
   Dukakis, who has frequently criticized the expected veto, said
today at the Capitol that it was ``a tragedy'' for Reagan to take
such action because of a provision requiring companies to give 60
days notice to workers before closing a plant.
   On a happier note for Bush, the Republican nominee-to-be cruised
to an easy victory in Idaho's presidential primary on Tuesday. He
was picking up 15 of the 18 national convention delegates, as
Dukakis won a non-binding Democratic ``beauty contest'' with no
delegates at stake.
   With 99 percent of the precincts reporting, Dukakis was taking
73 percent to Jackson's 16 percent in Idaho, while Bush was gaining
82 percent to 9 percent for Pat Robertson, who suspended his
presidential bid earlier this month.
   Robertson was winning one delegate, with two going to the
uncommitted column. Bush already has more delegates than he needs
for the GOP nomination.
   In Washington, Dukakis picked up endorsements from more than a
dozen members of Congress and met privately with former rival
Albert Gore Jr.
   Dukakis' talk with Gore resulted in no endorsement, but ``it was
a good, friendly meeting,'' Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan said of
the session. He said the two men met alone in Dukakis' hotel room.
   Bush left Washington to spend a week at his summer home in
Kennebunkport, Maine. After speaking to the graduating cadets at
West Point, he was expected to keep a low profile to avoid
upstaging Reagan during the Moscow summit.
   Tonight's Jackson-Dukakis debate in San Francisco comes as the
two campaign for California's June 7 primary. Candidates' debates
were almost painfully commonplace earlier in the campaign, as the
the-crowded Democratic field met frequently for talkfests.
   But the last time Jackson and Dukakis met for a debate was in
April, prior to the Pennsylvania primary. Back then, the two were
exchanging mainly pleasantries. But Jackson has been more critical
of Dukakis in recent weeks as the delegate gap between the two
widened.
   Dukakis is now within striking distance of the 2,081 delegates
needed to nominate. He has 1,680 to Jackson's 983, according to the
latest Associated Press count.
   On Tuesday, Dukakis denounced Reagan's veto of the trade
measure, which would require advance notice of plant closings.
   ``Any administration that is willing to give Gen. (Manuel
Antonio) Noriega 120 days notice and a plea bargain ought to be
willing to give the American worker 60 days notice before they are
thrown out on the street,'' the Massachusetts governor said,
referring to talks aimed at easing the Panamanian military leader
from power. Noriega is under indictment on drug charges.
   Dukakis made it clear the plant-closing issue would be used as
ammunition in his expected campaign against the vice president.
Reagan and Bush, he said, ``don't understand that for working
families ... there is nothing more painful than losing a job.''
   Even some Bush backers broke with the administration on the
trade bill. Rep. Guy Molinari, Bush's New York campaign chairman,
was one of 60 House Republicans who joined in the 308-113 vote to
override the veto. Senate Democratic leaders have said they expect
the veto to stand in their chamber.
   Bush has not come out directly in favor of the president's
position, but he hasn't publicly dissented either.
   He has edged slightly away from Reagan by speaking favorably of
the plant-closing law in Massachusetts, Dukakis' home state. But
Bush has said that he approves of the Massachusetts measure because
it is voluntary, whereas the federal one would be mandatory.
   For the vice president, the trade bill was the latest example of
an administration action that has left him on the defensive as he
campaigns. In one such controversy _ the Noriega affair _ Bush let
it be known, if in cautious terms, that he disagreed with the
president.
   On Tuesday, at an anti-apartheid rally in Los Angeles, Jackson
renewed his call for South Africa to be designated a terrorist
state, and said he would push to include that in the party platform.
   Jackson also released a five-year budget plan this week calling
for a freeze in military spending. He underscored that idea on
Tuesday in a speech before a World Affairs Council luncheon in Los
Angeles, and said that he hoped it would also be reflected in the
platform.
   ``After the largest military buildup in our history, we must
change our course or lose our way,'' he told the group.
</TEXT>
