<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Marcos 2ndLd-Writethru a0551 05-25 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0551,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Philippines President Hospitalized In Guarded Condition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 9th graf pvs, `Asked if ...,' to
UPDATE with two senators in Philippines saying Marcos should be
allowed to return home.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
was hospitalized in intensive care because of chest pains,
officials said.
   Marcos, 70, was listed in guarded condition Tuesday night at St.
Francis Medical Center, and was undergoing tests, said Eugene N.
Tiwanak, the hospital's assistant administrator.
   He began suffering chest pains during the day. After an
hour-long interview with Allen Neuharth, chairman of the Gannett
newspaper group, Marcos continued to feel the pains. The family
consulted with Marcos' personal physician and it was decided he
should be taken to the hosital for a checkup, said Arturo Aruiza,
Marcos' chief spokesman.
   Marcos was taken to the hospital by car at about 8 p.m. Tuesday,
said Aruiza.
   There were unconfirmed reports Monday that Marcos' health was
deteriorating, but his spokesman, Gemmo Trinidad, said at the time
Marcos was healthy, although still grieving the death of his mother.
   ``He's admitted that he's feeling ill _ that he is not well,''
Aruiza said at the hospital.
   Also at the hospital was Marcos' wife, Imelda, who was wearing
her customary black dress and sunglasses.
   Mrs. Marcos left the hospital through a side door and appeared
to be escorted by four people. She told them, ``Thank you so much
for coming.''
   Asked if Marcos was going to be all right, she replied, ``Yes, I
think so. I hope so.''
   In the Philippines, Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, a former defense
minister under Marcos, and Sen. Ernesto Maceda, who ran on Mrs.
Aquino's ticket but has since grown critical of her administration,
said Marcos should be allowed to return home.
   ``This is going to create another problem if (Marcos) comes home
in a box,'' Maceda said today. ``Now is the time for the government
to act and allow him to return.''
   Marcos was hospitalized briefly at St. Francis last October
during which a parathyroid gland was removed to ease chronic pain
in his legs, doctors said.
   Marcos, his wife and their three children have lived here since
fleeing the Philippines during the February 1986 civilian-military
revolution toppled him after 20 years in power.
   Marcos, who was first elected president in 1965, ruled the
Philippines with a mixture of dictatorship and democracy, reform
and stagnation.
   He was re-elected in 1969. In 1972, he declared martial law as
troops arrested scores of opponents, saying it was needed to save
the country from communism and to reform society. Marcos ruled with
an iron hand for the next eight years.
   He lifted martial law in January 1981 but gave up little of his
vast powers. A few weeks later, he won another term against a
little known candidate in an election that was boycotted by all his
major opponents.
   The beginning of the end for Marcos' reign came in 1983, when
his most powerful challenger, Benigno Aquino, was assassinated on
his return from exile in the United States. Opposition to Marcos
grew rapidly, and he scheduled an early election in February 1986
to prove his popularity.
   The Commission on Elections said Marcos won, but opponent
Corazon Aquino, Aquino's widow, charged the election was rigged and
also claimed victory.
   Later that month, Defense Minister Juan Ponce Enrile broke with
Marcos. Soldiers, joined by hundreds of thousands of civilians,
rose up against Marcos, sweeping Mrs. Aquino to the presidency.
   Marcos' 95-year-old mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos, died in the
Philippines on May 4. The family appealed to Mrs. Aquino to allow
Marcos to return for funeral but she refused, citing national
security.
   The body has been lying in state at a suburban Manila church,
where scores of Marcos supporters have been conducting a vigil
marked by calls for his return.
</TEXT>
