<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0604 05-25 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0604,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Reaps Endorsements at Capitol, Criticizes Veto</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis comments on trade veto, Western issues,
inserting 3 grafs after 1st graf; subs 10th graf pvs, The
Massachusetts, to update delegate total</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis pocketed endorsements today from more than a dozen members
of Congress and met privately with vanquished rival Albert Gore Jr.
as he methodically made the rounds of the Capitol.
   The Massachusetts governor also renewed his criticism of
President Reagan's veto of trade legislation. He said it was ``a
tragedy'' to veto the measure over a provision requiring companies
to give 60 days notice to workers before closing a plant.
   In addition, during a meeting with Western lawmakers, Dukakis
criticized the administration's environmental policies, saying
offshore oil drilling ``should be a last resort, not a first.''
   Though Republican Vice President George Bush is considered
strong in the West, Dukakis told the lawmakers he would run an
aggressive campaign in their states. He said the issues that are
important to voters nationwide are the same ones that concern
Western voters including jobs, education, economic opportunity, a
clean and safe America and a ``strong America.''
   Dukakis' private talk with Gore resulted in no endorsement, and
aides said in advance none was expected. ``It was a good, friendly
meeting,'' Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan said of the session. He
said the two men met in Dukakis' hotel room without aides.
   The Massachusetts governor also was receiving the formal
endorsement of several members of the House and Senate and the
views of several dozen others in a fast-paced series of meetings.
Dukakis spent his morning in Washington before a scheduled flight
to California and an evening debate with Jesse Jackson in advance
of the state's June 7 primary.
   Dukakis is the Democratic nominee in all but name, and his
morning schedule was designed to depict him as the leader of a
united party. He moved from meeting to meeting with lawmakers who
will share the Democratic ticket with him in the fall.
   The Dukakis campaign said those endorsing the governor included:
Sens. John Breaux of Louisiana, Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, Quentin
Burdick of North Dakota, Wendell Ford of Kentucky, Harry Reid of
Nevada and Dennis DeConcini of Arizona.
   Among House members, Reps. Frank Annunzio of Illinois; John
Bryant of Texas; Norman Dicks of Washington; William Ford of
Michigan, Tony Hall of Ohio, Paul Kanjorski of Pennsylvania, Tom
Lantos, Leon Panetta, Nancy Pelosi, Pete Stark, Tony Beilenson, Vic
Fazio and Esteban Torres of California; Peter Rodino of New Jersey;
James Scheuer of New York; Richard Stallings of Idaho; Ron Wyden of
Oregon.
   Dukakis' campaign made sure that the governor's meetings with
those lawmakers, as well as groups of southern and western
congressmen, were well covered by reporters.
   In contrast, the session with Gore was held in unusual privacy.
The meeting did not appear on Dukakis' printed schedule, and the
senator walked alone into the Washington hotel where Dukakis was
staying and was ushered into his room.
   The Tennessee senator has more than 350 delegates to the
Democratic National Convention in his column, and has urged his
supporters to stay loyal. But Dukakis has slowly been whittling
away at Gore's delegate strength.
   
   
   The Massachusetts governor has 1,680 delegates, out of 2,081
needed to win the nomination. Aides say they have no doubt that
Dukakis will emerge from the final day of the primary season with a
nominating majority in hand.
   These campaign officials say they expect Dukakis will earn
roughly 300 of the 456 delegates at stake June 7 in the year's
final Democratic primaries in California, New Jersey, Montana and
New Mexico.
   That would mean they need to find another 100 to 150 from the
ranks of the uncommitted or from candidate dropouts like Gore to
reach the total needed to clinch the nomination.
   Dukakis spent Tuesday night in Washington after an evening
fund-raiser in Virginia.
   The Massachusetts governor set out on his campaign swing after
spending most of Tuesday in Boston, where he issued a statement
that managed to link President Reagan's veto of the trade bill with
the administration's protracted negotiations with Panamanian leader
Manuel Antonio Noriega, indicted on drug charges.
   ``Any administration that is willing to give General Noriega 120
days' notice and a plea bargain ought to be willing to give the
American worker 60 days notice before they are thrown out on the
street,'' the statement said. Reagan vetoed the trade bill, citing
objections over a provision requiring employers to give workers
advance warning on plant closings.
   In his statement, Dukakis tied his probable Republican opponent
in the fall, Vice President George Bush, to the veto, saying that
neither the president nor the vice president understands ``that for
working families who struggle to pay the mortgage, save for their
children's education and care for their elders, there is nothing
more painful than losing a job.''
   ``I think the president is making a very serious mistake,'' the
governor told reporters. ``This is a good trade bill. It's a
responsible bill. ... To veto this bill because it will give
working people and their families 60 days notice beore they're laid
off, seems to be to be unconscionable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
