<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TV-Letterman     05-25 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Letterman,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letterman Hopes to Return to Air June 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman said today in a statement
released by NBC that his manager and attorney are negotiating with
the Writers Guild of America to get his ``Late Night'' show back on
the air, possibly as early as June 8.
   The Writers Guild has been on strike against television and
motion picture producers since March 7. Negotiations broke off soon
after the strike started, but resumed this week with a federal
negotiator, and a session is scheduled for today. No details of the
negotiations have been released.
   Only ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' and one independent
movie producer have received waivers from the Guild to continue
production during the strike.
   Johnny Carson, whose ``Tonight Show,'' like ``Late Night,'' has
been in reruns since the strike began, went back on the air last
week, writing his own material. Carson is not a member of the
Writers Guild, but Letterman is.
   Mona Mangan, executive director of the Writers Guild of America
East, said if the union membership agreed in its meeting on
Thursday, the Letterman show could receive a waiver.
   ``We assume he is referring in his statement to the independent
contracts, which, if the members agree at the meetings on Thursday,
will be available to David Letterman as well. We do not wish to
comment further on the substance of our conversations between our
lawyers and the David Letterman people,'' she said.
   Letterman's statement, typically tongue-in-cheek, said:
   ``During the last two weeks, my manager Jack Rollins, my
attorney Ron Elberger, and U.S. Attorney General Ed Meese have been
working with the Writers Guild of America and NBC in an attempt to
resume production of `Late Night.' The signs seem most encouraging
that we could return to the air, accompanied by our entire writing
staff, as early as June 8, 1988.
   ``In the meantime, I am keeping busy with my gardening and
phoning my favorite talk-radio programs. Last month, I splurged and
treated myself to much-needed liposuction surgery on my hips and
thighs. I look and feel 10 years younger.
   ``Finally, I would like to thank our audience, the best-looking
television audience in America, for their loyalty and patience.''
</TEXT>
