<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Monsoons     05-25 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Monsoons,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Predict `Good Monsoon' After Year of Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India will have good monsoon rains this
year to help make up for last year's widespread drought, a
government official predicted on Wednesday.
   Vasant Gowariker, secretary of the Department of Science and
Technology, said he expected the first rain to hit the western
state of Kerala by the weekend, the United News of India reported.
   He said that a study by his department and the Indian
Meteorology Department of weather patterns indicated that most
factors this year ``favor a good monsoon'' rain, UNI said.
   The study looked at temperatures around the country in May, wind
patterns and pre-monsoon rainfall, which has been normal is most
parts of the country.
   More than two-thirds of India's 800 million people work in
agriculture, which is heavily dependent on rain.
   Last year the rains failed in 16 of the nation's 25 states,
sharply reducing rice, wheat and fodder production. India is
importing wheat from the United States and corn from Argentina to
make up for the losses.
   The rains fall from June through September and account for more
than two-thirds of India's annual rainfall.
</TEXT>
