<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WhaleStudies     05-25 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whale Studies,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genetic Sampling Can Replace Whale-Hunting for Research,
Scientists Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whales can be studied without being killed if
researchers take skin samples for genetic analysis, two scientists
say.
   ``Management policies and conservation measures may now be
determined without the need to kill whales,'' A. Rus Hoelzel and
William Amos of Cambridge University write in a letter in
Thursday's issue of the British journal Nature.
   Whale-hunting for scientific purposes has become a political
issue. President Reagan imposed fishing sanctions against Japan in
April for approving the killing of 300 minke whales in the
Antarctic for research purposes.
   The International Whaling Commission had passed a resolution
opposing the hunt. Japanese officials say the commission has no
power to ban such whaling.
   Researchers plan to study the health, growth rates and diet of
the whales, Japanese officials said.
   In their letter, Hoelzel and Amos said researchers have gained
valuable information about whales from commercial and scientific
whaling, as well as from stranded animals.
   But given what has already been discovered, ``our new priority
should be to characterize accurately the size of populations and
their genetic status,'' they wrote. ``The technology needed to
determine these fundamental population parameters without killing
animals is at hand.''
   Skin samples can be retrieved by firing a specialized arrow,
equipped to recover a skin sample and tethered to a fly casting
reel, into the animal's skin, they said.
   Genetic analysis can then determine each animal's distinctive
``DNA fingerprint,'' providing an accurate method for population
counts, they said.
   Other genetic studies can trace reproductive behavior and the
status of genes present in whale populations, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeeGenes     05-25 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bee Genes,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genes Influence Roles of Bees in Hive, Studies Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Genes play a major role in whether a honey bee
serves its hive as a groomer, guard or even an undertaker, two
studies suggest.
   Certain genes may make particular bees more responsive to
environmental cues that trigger those behaviors, the authors wrote.
   The findings have ``substantial implications for our
understanding of the evolution of division of labor in colonies of
social insects,'' Michael Breed of the University of Colorado at
Boulder said in an editorial accompanying the papers, which appear
in Thursday's issue of the British journal Nature.
   Bee colonies are collections of subfamilies, each created by the
queen bee and a different drone.
   Researchers used artificial insemination to establish
subfamilies that could later be differentiated. Then they looked
for relationships between a bee's subfamily, and therefore its
genetic inheritance, and its job in the hive.
   Gene Robinson and Robert Page Jr. of Ohio State University
studied worker bees that specialized in standing guard at the hive
entrance or in removing corpses. Only a minority of bees do those
jobs, they wrote.
   They found significant genetic differences between the groups,
and between each specialist group and other worker bees.
   The other study found evidence for genetic influence on the
tendency of worker bees to groom nestmates, wrote Peter Frumhoff
and Jayne Baker, who did the work at the University of California
at Davis.
   In the editorial, Breed said scientists should now see if queen
bees choose a range of mates that would encourage variety in jobs.
Queen bees mate up to 17 times, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-IowaPrimary     05-25 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iowa Primary,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowa Democrats Eye Big Crop of LaRouche Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa Democrats are nervously watching a
crop of candidates loyal to political extremist Lyndon LaRouche,
and worrying about a predicted dismal turnout in for June 7 primary
featuring no statewide contests.
   Some top Democrats even have endorsed Republicans in a couple of
legislative districts.
   ``I'm confident that where there is a race we're going to win,''
said Iowa Democratic Party spokesman Phil Roeder.
   In all, 16 LaRouche backers are running in Iowa Democratic
primaries, five seeking congressional nominations and the rest
running in legislative districts.
   Roeder said Democrats will work to make sure voters know which
candidates back LaRouche and will deny them access to
party-sponsored events. ``We'll be helping out the regular
Democratic candidates,'' Roeder said.
   In 1986, three LaRouche backers ran for office, when Juan Cortez
of Cedar Rapids got nearly 18 percent of the vote in a U.S. Senate
primary.
   The increase has Democrats scratching their heads, because the
state's farm-based economy is improving.
   ``The `send them a message' slogan that everybody was using in
the Midwest was very relevant, we had big problems,'' Roeder said.
``The general resentment toward government just isn't there this
time.''
   Few of the LaRouche candidates are actively campaigning, though
two legislative candidates will get the official party nomination
because they are the only Democrats on the ballot.
   House Speaker Don Avenson, who runs Democratic legislative
elections, has endorsed Republican incumbents in those districts.
   ``I far prefer a mainstream Republican to a LaRouche backer,''
Avenson said.
   ``We're going to urge voters not to vote for them,'' Roeder
said. ``That means they either don't vote in that particular
election, or they vote for the Republican.
   ``While the number may have gone up this time, the level of
activity has gone down,'' Roeder said.
   Part of the reason Democrats are nervous is the experience in
neighboring Illinois, where two LaRouche backers won statewide
primaries in the last election, tossing that state's party into
turmoil and destroying efforts to unseat Republican Gov. James
Thompson.
   ``I think everybody learned a good lesson from Illinois,''
Roeder said.
   Aggravating the worries is a projected low turnout, which state
officials say could be less than 15 per percent of the 1.6 million
registered voters.
   Iowa political activists were wearied by months of intense
presidential campaigning leading up to precinct caucuses Feb. 8,
and there are few races of interest to draw voters.
   It's the first election since 1976 in which neither a Senate
seat nor the governor's office is at stake, and all six incumbent
congressmen are seeking re-election.
   Only freshman Democrat David Nagle in northeast Iowa's 3rd
District has primary opposition, and that comes from LaRouche
backer James Cox, of Grinnell.
   In that district, Republicans Don Redfern and Marvin Simpson
square off in a GOP primary. Redfern wanted to run when the seat
was open in 1986, but forgot to sign his nominating petition and
missed the filing deadline by 15 minutes.
   Freshman Republican Rep. Fred Grandy, who for years played
Gopher on television's ``Love Boat,'' has no primary opposition in
his bid for a second term from western Iowa's 6th District. There
are, however, four Democrats running in a primary.
   With little activity at the top of the ticket, election
officials say they're counting on local elections to spark pockets
of voter interest. There are 30 Democratic legislative primaries
and 17 for Republicans. In addition, sheriffs in all 99 of the
state's counties face election this year, and that office usually
gets heavy local attention.
   As of this month, Iowa had 495,182 registered Republicans,
562,039 registered Democrats and 504,082 registered voters who
expressed no party preference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
