<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>6 Sailors Accused In Recruit's Drwning Get Navy Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Naval investigator at a hearing for six
sailors charged in the March 2 drowning of a recruit denied a
defense request today to close the proceedings to the public.
   The hearings, which began today, are the military equivalent of
a grand jury inquiry.
   Lawyers for two of the sailors argued that extensive press
coverage would prejudice any future panel that may consider the
case if court-martials are ordered in the death of airman recruit
Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   Cmdr. Daniel J. D'Alesio Jr., the investigating officer, said he
may close portions of the hearings to consider whether certain
evidence can be admitted or might prejudice any future
court-martial.
   ``I think the law is clear: If there is any closure it is to be
done with a scalpel, not an ax,'' D'Alesio said.
   Mirecki died during rescue training exercises at a Pensacola
Naval Air Station pool. Investigators said he was dragged into the
pool against his will, and his head held under water.
   On May 10, five instructors were charged with involuntary
manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery, and their commanding
officer was charged with dereliction of duty.
   D'Alesio, of the Naval Legal Service Office in Philadelphia,
will recommend whether the charges should be handled at a
presidential preference of the delegates selected or allocated thus
far to the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta, July 18-21,
1988.
</TEXT>
