<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     05-25 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Reaps Capitol Endorsements, Says He's Conceding No States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis breezed through the Capitol on Wednesday, picking up
endorsements and advice from members of Congress and declaring he
will not ``concede one single state to the Republicans'' in the
fall campaign.
   Dukakis also met privately with defeated rival Albert Gore Jr.
He got no endorsement there but said he and the Tennessee senator
had a ``very cordial meeting.''
   The Massachusetts governor took a fresh shot at President
Reagan's veto of trade legislation. He said it was ``a tragedy'' to
reject the big trade bill over a provision requiring companies to
give their workers 60 days advance notice before shutting down a
plant.
   In a meeting with Western lawmakers, Dukakis also criticized the
administration's environmental policies, saying offshore oil
drilling ``should be a last resort, not a first.''
   He made his fast-paced tour of the Capitol before flying off on
a Western campaign swing, including a Wednesday night debate in San
Francisco with Democratic rival Jesse Jackson.
   Dukakis expects to wrap up a nominating majority of Democratic
National Convention delegates on June 7, the final day of the
primary season when elections are set in California, New Jersey,
Montana and New Mexico.
   Several Southern lawmakers observed pointedly that Dukakis had
fended off pressure during the primary campaign from traditional
Democratic interest groups, and they said he would be a more
popular general election candidate that Walter F. Mondale was in
1984.
   Sen. Terry Sanford of North Carolina said that four years ago
Mondale ``overpromised'' in the early primaries whereas Dukakis did
not. That was a reference to the perception that Mondale catered to
a series of special interest groups during his campaign.
   Sen. John Breaux of Louisiana said Dukakis has been ``able to
resist many demands'' that look good but turn out to pose problems
later on.
   Dukakis said repeatedly he will contest Bush in every state.
``We are not going to concede one single state to the Republicans
in the fall,'' he said.
   The Massachusetts governor held separate sessions with Southern
and Western lawmakers, where the talk centered on regional issues.
   In contrast to the meetings in the Capitol which were
orchestrated for maximum news coverage, the session with Gore took
place as quietly as could be managed.
   It was not on Dukakis' printed schedule, and the two men met
privately in Dukakis' hotel room.
   The Massachusetts governor said they had had a ``very good
conversation.''
   Asked whether Gore had agreed to release more than 350 delegates
pledged to him, Dukakis repeated, ``It was a very cordial
meeting.'' Gore wrote his delegates last week urging them to stay
loyal at least for the time being.
   Even so, Dukakis has been steadily whittling away at Gore's
delegates as he has moved towards winning a nominating majority.
   The lawmakers who endorsed Dukakis during the day included:
   Sens. Sanford, Breaux, Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, Quentin Burdick
of North Dakota, Wendell Ford of Kentucky, Harry Reid of Nevada and
Dennis DeConcini of Arizona.
   Among House members, Reps. Frank Annunzio of Illinois; John
Bryant of Texas; Norman Dicks of Washington; William Ford of
Michigan, Tony Hall of Ohio, Paul Kanjorski of Pennsylvania, Tom
Lantos, Leon Panetta, Nancy Pelosi, Pete Stark, Tony Beilenson, Vic
Fazio and Esteban Torres of California; Peter Rodino of New Jersey;
James Scheuer of New York; Richard Stallings of Idaho and Ron Wyden
of Oregon.
</TEXT>
