<DOCNO> AP880525-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kids'News     05-25 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kids' News,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Says TV Rates Highest for Recreation and Information</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School children say they prefer watching
television to any other leisure activity, while reading is the
least popular pastime, according to a survey released Wednesday.
   Grade schoolers also say they trust what they hear on television
more than what they read in newspapers, the survey released by
Weekly Reader says.
   In the lower grades they love reading books, but that ardor
cools by grades 4 to 6, the survey reported.
   Weekly Reader said its survey of reading and TV habits was
prompted in part because low test scores and high dropout and
illiteracy rates indicate children are reading less than they once
did.
   Survey results were compiled from teacher summaries representing
about 117,000 of more than 340,000 children who answered
questionnaires in class. Weekly Reader said that statistically the
survey was not a random sample whose results could be projected,
but it said the sample was large enough to be taken as
representative.
   Some findings:
   _Watching television was something 80 percent or more of all
children in grades two through six said they liked a lot. Only 3
percent or less said they didn't like TV.
   _Among second-graders, 65 percent said they liked reading a lot
and 8 percent said not at all. By sixth grade, only 39 percent had
a strong yen to read, 10 percent were anti-reading and the rest
were lukewarm.
   _Newspaper reading was popular with 28 percent of
second-graders, but with only 11 percent of fifth- and
sixth-graders. Those who said they did not like reading newspapers
at all ranged from 35 percent of sixth-graders to 43 percent of
fourth-graders.
   _Asked what they typically do at home, 55 percent said watch TV,
14 percent play, 14 percent talk on the telephone, 11 percent
listen to the radio and 6 percent read.
   _Asked where they get their news, 69 percent said television, 23
percent radio, 5 percent magazines and 3 percent newspapers.
   _Fifty-seven percent said they believed the TV news a lot, but
only 47 percent said they had strong faith in newspapers, 45
percent in radio and 15 percent in magazines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TradeDeficit     05-25 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Deficit,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Export Sales Offset Import Climb in First Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit narrowed dramatically
during the first three months of the year as an all-time high in
American export sales offset a relentless climb in imports, the
Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
   The trade deficit from January through March totaled $35.9
billion, a 12.7 percent drop from a deficit of $41.2 billion in the
fourth quarter of 1987.
   It was only the second quarterly improvement in the deficit in
the past two years and it represented the biggest decline since the
deficit fell by 18.9 percent in the fourth quarter of 1982.
   Analysts said the sharp narrowing showed that the United States
has finally turned the corner on trade and should see in 1988 the
first yearly decline in the trade deficit since 1980.
   ``We believe that 1988 will finally be the year of the
turnaround, and these figures support that prediction,'' said
Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data Resources Inc., an economic
consulting firm in Lexington, Mass.
   She predicted the trade deficit would fall this year by about 10
percent from last year's record $160.3 billion deficit, when
measured on a balance-of-payments basis.
   The new figures confirmed an improvement that had already shown
up in the department's monthly merchandise trade reports. The
earlier figures showed a 16.4 percent drop in the deficit to $36
billion in the first quarter, compared with $43.1 billion in the
fourth quarter of 1987.
   Wednesday's figures are smaller because they subtract factors
such as shipping costs and military sales from the monthly numbers.
The balance-of-payments deficit is also adjusted for seasonal
variations; the monthly figures are not.
   ``We are making slow but steady improvement, but we shouldn't
get too confident,'' said Jay Goldinger, chief economist with
Capital Insight, a Los Angeles investment firm. ``We won't see
progress in reducing the deficit continue at this rate.''
   The improvement in the first quarter came from a 9.8 percent
surge in export sales, which rose to a record high of $74.7
billion, as American companies continued to enjoy an export boom
fueled by the weaker dollar.
   Since the spring of 1985, the dollar has fallen in value by 50
percent against the currencies of Japan and many European
countries, making U.S. products more competitive overseas.
   Unfortunately, the weaker dollar has driven up the cost of
imports as well. In the first quarter they rose to a record high of
$110.6 billion, 1.3 percent above the fourth-quarter level.
   Analysts termed the continued rise in imports disappointing, but
Ms. Latta noted that much of the growth in imports apparently came
not from consumer demand but from a pickup in business spending as
U.S. factories boosted investment to expand production facilities
in order to meet the increased export demand.
   She said this business investment should slow in coming
quarters, and this would help lower imports.
   The Reagan administration is counting on strong export sales to
provide close to half of total economic growth in the United States
this year as well as blunt the drive by Congress to enact trade
legislation that the White House considers protectionist.
   President Reagan cited the improving trade figures on Tuesday
when he vetoed the omnibus trade bill.
   The figures are in current dollars before adjusting for price
changes caused by the decline in the value of the dollar since
1985. When inflation is factored out, the trade deficit in volume
terms fell 12.8 percent in the first quarter to $36.7 billion when
expressed in 1982 dollars.
   In current dollars, the trade deficit with Japan fell by $1.9
billion to $12.9 billion in the first quarter. The trade deficit
with Western Europe dropped by an even sharper $3.8 billion to $4.5
billion. The deficit with the newly industrialized countries of
Singapore, Hong Kong, South Korea and Taiwan, fell by $1.1 billion
to $6.9 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
