<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Teen Sentenced,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Sentenced in Beating Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDENTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Wednesday sentenced an
18-year-old man to spend the rest of his life in prison for beating
a classmate to death in a crime prosecutors described as a satanic
sacrifice.
   Camden County Circuit Judge James Franklin sentenced James Hardy
of Joplin to life in prison without possibility of parole, the
circuit clerk said.
   Hardy had pleaded guilty to first-degree murder in exchange for
prosecutors' promise not to seek the death penalty.
   Prosecutors accused Hardy and two other teen-agers of beating
19-year-old Stephen Newberry with baseball bats and dumping his
body in a cistern. Prosecutors say the Dec. 6 beating was fueled by
the teen-agers' involvement with drugs, satanism and violent rock
music.
   One defendant was convicted of first-degree murder earlier this
month. During that trial, a psychiatrist testified that Hardy was
the leader of the teen-agers' self-styled satanic cult, and planned
Newberry's death as a sacrifice.
   The third teen-ager was to stand trial next month.
</TEXT>
