<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PrincetonDrinking     05-25 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Princeton Drinking,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Student Given Jail Time For Drinking Party At Princeton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Princeton University students were
sentenced to 30 days in jail and fined $500 each today for their
part in two parties Feb. 6 that resulted in 46 students seeking
medical attention for drinking too much.
   This is not ``an undergraduate frolic that got out of hand, it
is a violation of the law,'' said Municipal Court Judge Russell
Annich. ``I'm not aware of a similar event that has produced as
many casualties,'' he said.
   Thirty-nine students went to the university infirmary and seven
to the hospital after initiation parties held by the Charter Club
and the Cloister Inn _ two of 13 on-campus eating clubs, which
resemble fraternities.
   Many of the students were underage. The legal drinking age in
New Jersey is 21.
   Kenneth Simpler, 20, of Rehoboth, Del., a junior who is
president of the Charter Club, and Lisa Napolitano, 21, of Geneva,
N.Y., a junior who is the club's former social chairperson, were
convicted May 18 of serving alcohol to minors.
   During a one-day trial, witnesses testified that students
seeking to join the Charter Club were blindfolded and led from room
to room where club members poured alcoholic drinks down their
throats.
   The judge delayed the start of the sentence so that the students
could appeal.
</TEXT>
