<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Tourism     05-25 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Tourism,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Launchs Advertising Campaign to Counter Arab Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel launched a $5 million advertising
campaign Wednesday to counter the crippling effects on its tourist
industry of the nearly 6-month-old Arab uprising in the occupied
territories.
   Officials had hoped to reap a tourist bonanza on Israel's 40th
anniversary, but now they're anticipating a drop of about $300
million. That would make tourism, the nation's biggest source of
foreign capital, the industry hardest hit by the unrest.
   ``It's a disaster. The cancellations are coming in a murderous
rhythm. I'm losing hundreds of thousands of dollars,'' said Shimon
Shtern, a hotel owner and chairman of the Hotel Association in
Netanya, a popular Mediterranean resort.
   Shtern's 150-room Netanya Hanesicha hotel is operating at 10
percent of capacity, and 63 hotel employees have been fired this
month as a result.
   Shtern says each time his office telex switches on, his hopes
rise. ``The telex starts up, we all get excited, and it's another
cancellation. We don't even ask the reason anymore,'' he said.
   By comparison, 1987 was a record year for Israeli tourism, with
1.52 million visitors bringing in $1.6 billion.
   On Wednesday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir got the first
official look at the advertising campaign, slated for Europe and
the United States under the slogan: ``Israel: See for Yourself.''
   The ads feature television endorsements from American tourists
saying how safe Israel's popular vacation spots are.
   ``The idea we're selling is Israel isn't just the West Bank.
It's Masada, Eilat, Jaffa oranges, all these wonderful things,''
said Al Lieberman, president of New York-based Grey Advertising,
one of the companies involved in the campaign.
   ``When there's a crisis on, we can't compete with the front
page. But after people read the headlines, these ads say: `Forget
what's going on in Gaza, it's beautiful here in Israel,'''
Lieberman said.
   Israel's Tourism Ministry is also treating European and American
travel agents to all-expenses paid tours of Israel to promote the
country. To help Israeli hoteliers, the ministry contributes two
dollars for every dollar an owner spends to advertise his hotel
abroad.
   But some hotel owners have already complained that the $5
million budget for the campaign is not enough to effectively fight
Israel's tarnished image, brought about not only by the unrest but
by the army's handling of it.
   More than 190 Palestinians have been killed, mostly by Israeli
army gunfire, since December. Two Israelis have died.
   ``Five million dollars when we are going to lose hundreds of
millions is nothing. It's a drop in the bucket. If you spend that
little, you might as well do nothing at all,'' said Yehuda
Greenbaum, chairman of the Jerusalem Hotel Association.
   ``What we have today is as much an image problem as a security
problem,'' said Yaacov Katz, marketing manager of the Israel Hotel
Association, which represents the country's 320 hotels.
   ``People are not just worrying about rocks or terrorist acts.
The problem is that in the United States, Israel's image has been
sullied. It's a political problem, something we've never tackled
before,'' he said in an interview.
   Katz believes the lost revenue will amount to $500 million
instead of the $300 million estimated by the Tourism Ministry.
   Twenty percent fewer Americans came to Israel in April compared
with the same month last year, and the biggest decline was among
American Jews, according to Tourism Ministry Spokeswoman Dvora
Ganani-Elad.
   Tourism in March and April slid 23 percent compared to the first
two months of the year, and advance bookings have plummeted. In
Europe alone, about 60,000 people have called off plans to travel
to Israel.
   Tourism buses standing idle in their lots have prompted Israel's
largest bus company, Egged, to announce it will lay off 500
employees. The Hilton Hotel in Tel Aviv has already fired 180
workers and reduced the remainder of its 650-member staff from a
six- to a five-day work week.
</TEXT>
