<1ST_LINE>u a PM-EmergencyLanding 2ndLd-Writethru a0651 05-25 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emergency Landing, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0651,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hail Apparently Knocked Out Plane's Engines</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU-1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD weather report at the time of the
crash. PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `The plane ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hail apparently knocked out both engines of a
new Boeing 737, forcing the jet to glide to a landing on a narrow
strip of grass 20 miles short of New Orleans' airport, a federal
investigator said today.
   Passengers broke into applause for the pilot who safely brought
down the TACA International Airlines jet Tuesday without injury to
the 40 or so people aboard the flight from El Salvador to New
Orleans.
   ``Apparently the pilot ran into a hail storm and that knocked
the engines out,'' said J.O. Johnson, an investigator with the
National Transportation Safety Board office in Fort Worth, Texas.
   ``The damage that was caused by the denting of the (jet turbine)
blades was probably the major factor in the loss of power,'' he
said.
   The 3-week-old Boeing 737-300 jet remained on the grassy strip
where it glided to a stop between an irrigation canal and a ship
channel. Johnson said the NTSB, Federal Aviation Administration and
TACA officials are investigating.
   ``I suspect they'll probably grade (the strip) down and fly it
out later,'' Johnson said. ``Except for the engines, the plane
apparently suffered no damage.''
   At the time of the flight, the entire Gulf region was under
National Weather Service warnings for severe thunderstorms,
including hail and high winds, for several hours. Storm clouds were
reported as high as 50,000 feet.
   ``The plane was going up and down, sideways, and twisting,''
said the Rev. Leo Humphrey, 52, a Baptist missionary. ``Lightning
was everywhere. The lights went out on the plane and the engine
died. Everyone thought it was over.
   ``As the pilot said, `By the grace of God, I got this sucker on
the ground,''' Humphrey said after the smooth landing.
   TACA, based in San Salvador, El Salvador, has business offices
in New Orleans. The flight had made a stop in the Central American
country of Belize.
   The TACA plane was at 11,000 feet when it was diverted 15 miles
to the Naval Air Station at suburban Belle Chasse, said a source
with the Federal Aviation Administration.
   The pilot then managed to restart both engines, the source said,
and asked for clearance to New Orleans International before power
went out again.
   Flying at about 5,000 feet, the pilot then was diverted 6 miles
away to the less congested Lakefront Airport, said the source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The pilot responded with two ``Mayday'' messages and began
looking for somewhere else to land, the source said.
   The plane came to a stop on the grounds of a National
Aeronautics and Space Administration complex in eastern New
Orleans, five miles short of Lakefront Airport. The wings barely
fit between the drainage canal and the levee.
   Officials have put the total number of passengers and crew
aboard the craft between 45 and 36.
   Two witnesses said they heard no engine sounds as the plane
landed.
   Saidy Duran, 35, of Costa Rica said she and other passengers
showed their appreciation with a round of applause _ ``a big one.''
   The pilot, Carlos Dardano, about 35, is from San Salvador and
has been with TACA about five years, said Peter Messina, the
airline's U.S. regional manager.
   ``He's a pretty cool captain. He doesn't get flustered very
easily,'' Messina said.
   Crew members refused to talk with reporters.
   ``We went through rain and severe turbulence and I thought I
heard them say lightning hit the plane,'' said passenger July Mora,
25, of New Orleans.
   Officials could not confirm the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
