<HEAD>Twenty Boeing Employees Suspended After Internal Drug
Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty employees of Kansas' largest
employer, Boeing Military Airplanes, were suspended without pay for
allegedly using or dealing drugs on company property.
   An investigation into selling, buying and using cocaine and
marijuana on Boeing property started several weeks ago, said Allen
Hobbs, a company spokesman.
   A Drug Enforcement Administration spokesman said one of the 20
people was arrested. Possible charges are being reviewed by the
Sedgwick County district attorney's office.
   Hobbs said the investigation is continuing. He would not say
what jobs the suspended workers held, but said they weren't
sensitive. Two are supervisors, he said.
   The company's drug policy is posted throughout the plant, Hobbs
said.
   ``We just want to be seen as tough on drugs,'' he said. ``We
don't want it on our property.''
   Boeing Military Airplanes employs more than 20,000.
</TEXT>
