<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DaroncoFuneral     05-25 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Daronco Funeral,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slain Judge Eulogized for `Justice and Holiness'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PELHAM, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 200 federal, state and local judges
joined the family and friends of slain federal Judge Richard
Daronco today to mourn a man praised for living a life ``of justice
and holiness.''
   Daronco, 56, was shot to death Saturday by a retired New York
City policeman distraught over the judge's dismissal of a sex
discrimination lawsuit brought against a bank by the officer's
daughter, authorities.
   Charles Koster, 67, of Bath, Pa., committed suicide immediately
after killing Daronco, who was appointed last year to the U.S.
District Court for the Southern District of New York.
   About 400 people crowded into St. Catharine's Roman Catholic
Church in this affluent New York City suburb, while 300 others
gathered in the cafeteria of a neighboring school to watch the
funeral on closed-circuit television.
   ``Richard Daronco was a great success in this world,'' Monsignor
Philip Murphy said at the Mass.
   The judge, said Murphy, was a ``wonderful, loving and devoted
husband and father ... son and brother, friend and relative. He was
an excellent judge. ... He lived a life of justice and holiness.''
   Among those attending the funeral were U.S. Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R.-N.Y., who recommended Daronco for nomination to the
federal bench, and Rudolph Giuliani, U.S. attorney for the Southern
District.
   Koster, who had used up his life savings on his daughter's
7-year-old suit, shot Daronco as he tended his garden. After
chasing Daronco into his home, Koster turned the gun on himself.
   The slaying was only the second of a federal judge this century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
