<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShooting     05-25 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Receives Liquid From Woman In School Shooting Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatrist who was treating Laurie Dann
received a drink container this week from the woman who went on a
shooting rampage at a Winnetka, Ill., school, and the liquid will
be tested for poison, the FBI said.
   Ms. Dann is believed to have delivered arsenic-laced snacks to
two fraternities and several families for whom she had worked as a
babysitter before the rampage Friday.
   An 8-year-old boy was killed in the shooting spree at Hubbard
Woods Elementary School, and five other children were wounded. Ms.
Dann, 30, then wounded a young man in a home nearby and killed
herself.
   University of Wisconsin-Madison psychiatrist John Greist, who
was treating Dann, received the container Monday at his office, FBI
agent Kent Miller said.
   Greist, a specialist in phobias and depressions, did not drink
the liquid, said police Capt. Jeffrey Frye. The container was given
to the FBI.
   Greist, contacted at his office Tuesday, said only that Ms. Dann
was being treated as an outpatient at the Psychiatric Research
Institute, which is affiliated with the university.
   An FBI search of Dann's apartment Friday uncovered a lab coat,
powders and capsules, and library catalog cards describing books on
poison, Miller said.
   Also found were papers from which the FBI compiled a list of
people to whom Dann may have sent poisoned food, Miller said.
</TEXT>
