<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Taiwan-China     05-25 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Taiwan-China,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Businessman Sentenced in Failed Trade in Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Wednesday convicted a Chinese
businessman of sedition and sentenced him to nine years in prison
for trying to buy goods for China in Taiwan.
   High Court officials said Liu Kuo-wei, 41, an executive of the
Ta Lien Co. in the Portuguese territory of Macao, came to Taiwan to
make the purchase in December 1986. They said he used a false Thai
passport and tried to buy 3,000 tons of tin plates for a Beijing
metal company.
   The deal fell through because of a disagreement over price,
officials said.
   They said Liu, a Chinese citizen, was arrested when he visited
Taiwan again in November.
   The Nationalist Chinese government, which fled to Taiwan in 1949
when it lost a civil war to the Communists, bans direct trade
between Taiwan and China. But it allows indirect trade through a
third country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
