<DOCNO> AP880525-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSStudy     05-25 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Study,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hopkins Researchers To Test Blood Of 10,000 Inmates For AIDS Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The blood of 10,000 new inmates from across the
United States will be tested this summer as part of an effort to
measure the spread of the disease among prisoners.
   ``This study is not intended to identify people or identify risk
groups,'' said Joanne Ullrich, coordinator of the project at Johns
Hopkins School of Public Health. ``The purpose of the study is to
find out the prevalence rates of human immunodeficiency virus
infection of people coming into the prison system so the systems
can plan for what they are coming up against.''
   The study is being funded under a $332,000 grant from the
federal Centers for Disease Control.
   The blood samples will be coded to ensure neither inmates nor
prison officials learn who is infected, Ms. Ullrich said.
Information about sexual orientation or drug use will not be
collected.
   The prisoner's age, gender, entrance date, length of sentence
and offense will be known. That will give prison officials a broad
profile of HIV-infected patients, researchers said.
   Results should help prison officials project the number of
inmates who may eventually develop acquired immune deficiency
syndrome and, in turn, plan services and prevention programs, Ms.
Ullrich said. Doctors are unsure exactly what percentage of
HIV-infected people will develop AIDS, but many experts believe the
figure is at least half.
   AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to a variety of infections.
   Dr. T. Forham Brewer, medical director of the Maryland Division
of Correction, said the study is the first survey of HIV-infection
among inmates in a geographically diverse slice of the nation's
prisons.
   In a survey by the National Institute of Justice, AIDS cases in
prisons rose 59 percent in the year ending Oct. 1, 1987 (from 1,232
to 1,964 cases), compared with a 61 percent increase in the general
population (26,002 to 41,770). The survey was based on reports from
70 federal, state and local correctional systems.
   The survey, however, did not measure the prevalence of HIV
infection in the prison population, the only reliable predictor of
how many inmates may develop AIDS.
   The Johns Hopkins study will screen the blood of 1,000 inmates
entering each of 10 prisons. The study will be repeated next year.
Hopkins investigators have said they not identify the prisons until
the study is complete.
   Participating prisons will siphon off a small amount of the
blood that is already routinely drawn to test for syphilis,
gonorrhea, anemia and other diseases. The samples will be shipped
to Johns Hopkins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EPAAir     05-25 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPA Air,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Pollution-Fighters Find Bad Air in Their Own Offices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the nation's pollution-fighters at the
headquarters of the Environmental Protection Agency have been
gasping and wheezing from an air pollution problem apparently
caused by new carpeting.
   Sixty-five employees have sought medical attention and seven
can't enter the building at all because of their reactions when
they do, William Hirzy, president-elect of Local 2050 of the
National Federation of Federal Employees, said Wednesday.
   Hirzy said he was ``90 percent certain'' the reactions came from
exposure to phenylcyclohexene, a gas given off by the backing of
new rugs the agency has been installing in the building used by
5,100 employees.
   ``From talk in the halls, I would guess that the number affected
is at least 100,'' but not all have reported to the agency's health
office, Hirzy said.
   The agency has stopped putting in new carpets, but Charles
Grizzle, assistant administrator for administration, said
phenylcyclohexene had not been fixed definitely as the cause of the
problem and ``I don't see any reason to rip up the carpets until we
are sure.''
   So far, tests have shown ``nothing above background levels of
any toxic chemicals,'' Grizzle said, but the results of tests for
phenylcyclohexene are not yet known. Hirzy said tests of the air of
a warehouse containing about 175 remaining rolls of carpet showed a
concentration of 60 parts per billion to 70 parts per billion. The
odor of the gas can be detected at concentrations of as little as 1
ppb to 3 ppb.
   About 100 rolls of carpet already have been installed.
   Little is known about the effects of phenylcyclohexene and there
are no standards for workplace exposure, but there is ``some
indication'' that it damages lung tissue and intestinal mucous
membranes in laboratory animals, said Hirzy, a chemist.
   The agency has not yet decided what to do about the seven
employees who can't enter the building. Some are on sick leave,
some are using vacation time and some are being permitted to work
at home, Hirzy said.
   Grizzle, however, said, ``We are giving our employees the
maximum relief we can and help with workmens' compensation cases at
the Labor Department'' while the agency tries to decide on a policy.
   EPA has asked the government's housekeeping agency, the General
Services Administration, for space elsewhere if it is forced to
relocate employees, he said.
   Hirzy said the union had been pressing for removal of the new
carpets, but was rebuffed in a ``very stormy'' meeting of the
union-management facilities advisory committee on April 28.
   EPA officials proposed to steam-clean the new carpets, air them
out and re-lay them, Hirzy said. ``Not only will it not work, it
doesn't make sense from a public policy standpoint. It's not the
job of government employees to be used as test animals.''
   Industrial hygienists say the ``sick building'' problem like
EPA's is often caused by poor ventilation. Grizzle said, ``I have
asked our folks to make sure we are doing everything we can to
improve ventilation. I am told the dampers are open as far as they
can go. I am just a layman, but it does seem to me we lack fresh
air in here.''
   The EPA building, which was constructed in 1971 near the
waterfront in the city's southwestern section, is almost totally
sealed. Many of EPA's employees work in cramped quarters in offices
without windows, and those who rank high enough to rate a window
find they cannot open it.
   Grizzle said the agency has 125 square feet per employee, below
the 135 square feet GSA specifies for new offices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
