<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MechamTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0455 05-25 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0455,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juror Questioning Continues In Mecham Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with questioning nearing
completion. PICKS UP 12th graf pvs, `Mecham faces ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Questioning of prospective jurors for
former Gov. Evan Mecham's criminal trial neared completion today,
with one woman making the first cut after saying she was
embarrassed by some of his remarks in office.
   ``He didn't seem to have tact in talking to people,'' said the
prospective juror, who added that she voted for Mecham in 1986. She
mentioned his description last year of the United States as a
``Christian'' nation and added, ``I did feel some embarrassment.''
   However, the woman said she wondered whether Mecham was ``set
up'' in his impeachment trial, which concluded with the state
Senate removing him April 4. She said she believed she could be
fair, and was accepted as a possible juror.
   Mecham and his brother and 1986 campaign treasurer, Willard, are
charged with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Sixteen prospective jurors were chosen Tuesday, and the
questioning could be completed today. Maricopa County Superior
Court Judge Michael Ryan said he probably would stop when 24
acceptable panelists are found.
   Peremptory eliminations by the prosecution and defense then
would be the last step in choosing the eight-member jury plus four
alternates.
   Another possible panelist was accepted today after saying she
bought a car from Mecham's Pontiac dealership that ``burned up''
after being serviced there. One man was excused after saying he had
signed a Mecham recall petition.
   Evan and Willard Mecham watched intently today as the judge,
prosecution and defense questioned the individual potential jurors.
   On Tuesday, the former governor told reporters he was ``just a
stoic observer.''
   One prospective juror who was accepted Tuesday said she felt
``sympathy'' for Mecham, while others said they did not believe he
should have faced recall from the governorship so soon after he
took office in January 1987.
   Another prospective panelist said Mecham ``has had a very big
mouth through this whole thing ... (and) got himself into a lot of
trouble because of the way he was so hard-headed.'' Prosecutors
unsuccessfully sought to exclude her.
   One man said Mecham seemed to make ``goofs, mistakes, errors,
bad judgment, that has nothing to do with his integrity.''
   All the prospective jurors, however, said they believed they
could be fair in the trial.
   Mecham faces six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment
and filing false documents, and faces up to 22 years in prison if
convicted on all counts. His brother faces three similar counts and
up to 9{ years if convicted of all three.
   The former Republican governor and his brother have denied all
wrongdoing in failing to report the loan from a Tempe developer.
   Opening statements are scheduled for June 2, the day after the
Arizona Supreme Court is to hear arguments on the defense's request
that the charges be returned to the state grand jury for a new
determination of probable cause.
   The original pool of 99 possible jurors was narrowed to 51 on
Monday after lawyers and Ryan examined questionnaires filled out
last week.
   Mecham was removed from office April 4 when the state Senate
convicted him on two impeachment counts of misusing a protocol fund
and of obstructing justice. He was impeached in connection with the
$350,000 loan, but the Senate decided not to hear the charge for
fear of prejudicing the criminal trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
