<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1532EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Terrorist     05-25 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorist,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plan Floated To Abduct Suspected Terrorist In France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intelligence operatives floated a plan in 1985
to send agents to France to seize a man believed to be behind the
kidnapping of Americans in the Middle East, but the State
Department torpedoed the proposal, a U.S. official and a broadcast
report said Wednesday.
   American intelligence received word in the autumn of 1985 that
Imad Mugniyeh, a Lebanese Shiite linked to terrorist attacks, was
visiting France and proposed that he be abducted to the United
States for trial, said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The State Department, fearing the action would cause a major
blowup in U.S.-French relations, argued successfully against the
plan and a decision was made to ask French authorities to arrest
Mugniyeh. France did not act on the request, the official said.
   National Public Radio, which first disclosed the plan in a
broadcast Wednesday morning, said its sources disagreed on whether
President Reagan approved the plan. At any rate, the broadcast
said, Secretary of State George P. Shultz and FBI Director William
Webster scuttled the proposal.
   NPR said the idea was conceived by William J. Casey, then
director of the Central Intelligence Agency, but that it was never
completely proven that Mugniyeh was in France at the time his
abduction was to be carried out.
   In early 1986, following a second report of Mugniyeh's presence
in France, local authorities did act on the U.S. request and went
to a hotel to arrest him. But instead of a Lebanese terrorist,
police found a family of vacationers, NPR reported.
   Mugniyeh has been identified by U.S. terrorism experts as the
leader of Islamic Jihad, an Iranian-backed group held responsible
for the kidnapping of westerners in Lebanon, including Associated
Press Chief Middle East Correspondent Terry Anderson and several
other Americans.
   Mugniyeh is under indictment in the United States on charges of
participating in the June 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner and the
killing of Navy diver Robert Stethem, one of the passengers.
   State Department officials have also said they suspect that
Mugniyeh was involved in last month's hijacking of a Kuwaiti
jetliner, which was held for two weeks by gunmen demanding the
release of more than two dozen Shiite Moslems being held on
terrorism charges in Kuwait. Mugniyeh's brother-in-law is said to
be one of the prisoners.
   The plane hijackers disappeared in Algeria after they released
their remaining hostages.
   The U.S. official who spoke of the proposal to abduct Mugniyeh
said ``there's always a lot of brainstorming about this sort of
thing. It was an idea that was floated. People were saying, `How
can we do this?'''
   ``The State Department felt strongly that if something like this
was to be done it could not be through secret connivance _ there
had to be a decision by French political authorities to arrest him
and turn him over to the United States,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-TahoeVote     05-25 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tahoe Vote,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Threat Was Key To Defeat Of New City Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATELINE, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fear of higher taxes was the key factor
behind voters' rejection of the proposed new city of Lake Tahoe,
spokesmen for both sides said.
   The measure, which was fought by local hotel-casino interests,
lost by a 1,001-802 vote in a special election Tuesday in this
mountain resort area.
   The proposed city would have embraced the casino area of
Stateline and smaller communities along about 15 miles of Lake
Tahoe's southeastern shore. It would have had a population of about
6,500.
   ``The tax scare did it,'' said Bill Bigham, a leader of the
movement to create the city. He also blamed casinos for the outcome.
   ``The casinos scared their employees into voting against the
city, saying there would be chaos,'' said Bigham, a local bank
manager.
   The leader of the opposition, Ron Nino, said he was very pleased
with the vote. ``Our arguments were more credible, particularly
regarding a tax increase,'' he said.
   The opposition's vigorous advertising campaign received
financial support from the Stateline casinos, whose tax burden Nino
said would rise by at least $300,000 yearly under a city government.
   Commissioners of Douglas County, which would have lost about
$1.8 million in yearly tax revenue to the city, mostly from the
large Stateline casinos, had advised voters to reject the plan.
   ``We believed there was going to be a substantial tax
increase,'' said Nino, who runs a property management business.
``People will pay more for more but we didn't see where there was
going to be more. We saw the same or less.''
   The proposal lost in all the lakeshore communities, although
proponents had argued that those communities, which comprise 25
percent of Douglas County's population, do not receive a share in
services proportionate to the tax revenue they contribute.
   The issue prompted an unusually high turnout of 60 percent, said
Douglas County Clerk Barbara Reed. She said a normal turnout was
35-40 percent.
</TEXT>
