<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StolenTelephones     05-25 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stolen Telephones,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Charged With Stealing Pay Telephones, Continuing To Reap
Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men stole 81 pay telephones, altered
their electronics and reinstalled them elsewhere, enabling one of
the thieves to continue collecting callers' money, police said.
   The alleged ringleader, Lou Vagnoni, 60, changed the locks on
the coin boxes, removed labels identifying the owner and changed a
computer chip inside, police said.
   The telephones were valueda at $265,275; the amount of money
received by operating them illegally could not be determined,
police said.
   Police Commissioner Kevin Tucker and District Attorney Ronald
Castille charged Tuesday that Vagnoni paid Robert Paige, 31, and
David Olsen, 22, to steal phones for him at $150 each throughout
Philadelphia.
   The stolen telephones were then operated by Need-a-Phone, a
Philadelphia pay telephone company in which Vagnoni is a silent
partner, police said. Other partners were unaware of the
activities, police said.
   About one-quarter of the telephones belonged to Bell of
Pennsylvania, while the remainder belonged to members of the
Central Atlantic Pay-Phone Association, a network of private
companies that operate pay telephones.
   The three men were charged with 60 counts each of theft,
conspiracy and unlawful use of computers.
   The case broke in February when police Sgt. Terry Levins spotted
Paige and Olsen dislodging a telephone and its steel base, said
Detective Philip Silverman. An investigation traced the men to
Vagnoni, he said.
   ``Bystanders would spot the two men, but they appeared to be
utility people,'' said Deputy Police Commissioner Willie Williams.
   ``It was when the owners of the equipment came by to service the
phones and found the equipment gone that a pattern began to be
noticed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
