<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0728 05-25 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Shuts Down Territories; Army Imposes Curfews</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE extraneous words ``Palestinians in.''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian general strike shut down the
occupied territories Wednesday and the Israeli army imposed curfews
that confined 200,000 Arabs to their homes.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, chief of staff, said the army has punished
dozens of soldiers for violating orders since the Arab rebellion
began Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   He did not elaborate, but the army has issued rules on when
soldiers are allowed to fire on or beat protesters.
   Shomron also said the violence has lessened the influence of
Jordan's King Hussein in the territories, which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war, and undermined his
usefulness in peace negotiations.
   ``The uprising in the territories has weakened Jordan's ...
position as a potential partner for negotiations,'' he told foreign
reporters. ``We hear voices today that King Hussein is retreating
from positions he had taken before the uprising began.''
   Soldiers shot a Palestinian youth during a clash with young
Arabs hurling rocks and bottles in the Nur Shams refugee camp near
Tulkarem in the West Bank, the army said. Officials at Rafidiyeh
Hospital in Nablus said he was critically wounded in the chest.
   Hundreds of Arabs have been wounded since the rebellion began
among the 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza. At
least 195 have been killed, and an Israeli soldier and a Jewish
settler also have been slain.
   Indefinite curfews were imposed on the Dheishe refugee camp in
the West Bank and on nine camps and villages in the Gaza Strip.
   Underground leaders called the one-day strike in a leaflet
signed by the Palestine Liberation Organization to mark the end of
mourning for Khalil Wazir, the PLO military commander, 40 days
after he was assassinated at his home in Tunis.
   Wazir, whose code name was Abu Jihad, spent his boyhood in Gaza
City. His cousin Ahmed Wazir, who lives there, said soldiers barred
mourners from attending a reception in the slain leader's honor.
   ``The army is outside our house,'' Ahmed Wazir said by telephone
from his home, where the reception was to have been held. ``They
turned back anyone who came here.''
   He said 10 army jeeps and other military vehicles were outside
his house and soldiers with megaphones ordered all residents on his
street to remain indoors.
   Stores were closed throughout the territories and in Arab east
Jerusalem, which Israel took from Jordan in 1967 and has formally
annexed. Public transport was halted and most Palestinians who have
jobs in Israel stayed home.
   Vendors selling newspapers and doughnut-shaped bread covered
with sesame seeds, an Arab staple, provided the only signs of
commercial activity.
   Classes were conducted at kindergartens and elementary schools
in the West Bank, which were allowed to open Monday for the first
time in nearly four months.
   Olivier Rafovicz, spokesman for the military government, said
about 90 percent of the 200,000 students showed up Wednesday.
``This shows the strengthening of the military government,'' he
said.
   In the leaflet that called the strike, however, underground
leaders said the school re-opening was a victory and urged children
to attend.
   Israel radio said the army threatened Arab property owners with
up to five years in jail if they failed to wash anti-Israeli
graffiti off their buildings and remove Palestinian flags, which
are outlawed by Israel.
   Army spokesmen had no immediate comment on the report, which
also said those who did not comply could be fined 15,000 shekels
($9,670).
   A Jewish settler was charged with manslaughter Wednesday in the
fatal shooting of a Palestinian shepherd May 5 near Shiloh, a
Jewish settlement in the West Bank, Israel radio reported.
   It quoted the charge sheet, Yisrael Zeev fired at Arab shepherds
despite their shouts that they would stop grazing sheep on disputed
land near Shiloh, the radio said. One shepherd was killed and
another wounded.
   Government prosecutors also charged two editors of the left-wing
newspaper Derech Hanitzotz with membership in a guerrilla
organization and maintaining contacts with a foreign agent, the
radio said.
   Yaacov Ben Efrat and Assaf Adiv, and two other staff members
charged earlier this week, face up to 40 years in jail if
convicted. They are accused of belonging to the Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical PLO faction, and meeting
with Arab guerrillas in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
