<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Taiwan-Military     05-25 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Taiwan-Military,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Announces Military Shakeup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui has conducted his
first major shakeup of the military leadership since becoming
president in January, an official report said Wednesday.
   Lee, the first native Taiwanese president of Nationalist China,
has toured military establishments seeking to win popularity since
he succeeded the late President Chiang Ching-kuo.
   Gen. Hau Pei-tsun, 69, chief of the military's general staff
since 1981, remained in his post. He is believed to support the new
president.
   The Central News Agency said Adm. Yeh Chang-tung, 59, was named
navy commander-in-chief, succeeding Adm. Liu Ho-chien, 62.
   Gen. Huang Hsing-chiang was appointed army commander-in-chief,
replacing Gen. Chiang Chung-ling, 66. Chiang was appointed senior
vice chief of the general staff.
   Huang's age was not available, but officials said he is in his
late 50s or early 60s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
