<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AmtrakCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0707 05-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0707,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineer Pleads Guilty To Federal Charge In Amtrak Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `In exchange ...' to CORRECT that
obtruction charge was dropped and guilty plea was entered to
conspiracy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Conrail engineer at the controls
during the worst crash in Amtrak history pleaded guilty today to a
federal charge of conspiring to obstruct an investigation of the
wreck.
   Rick Gates, 34, already is serving a five-year prison sentence
after pleading guilty to a state charge of manslaughter for running
a string of locomotives past a signal and into the path of an
Amtrak passenger train.
   Sixteen people were killed and 175 were injured in the Jan. 4,
1987 crash near Chase, Md.
   Gates could receive up to five years in prison and a $250,000
fine at sentencing July 15.
   Gates' public defender, Fred Warren Bennett, called the federal
charges ``morally unjust.'' Gates was indicted March 31, two days
after pleading guilty to the state charges.
   ``It amounts to kicking the dog when he's down,'' Bennett told
U.S. District Judge Norman Ramsey.
   In exchange for his guilty plea to conspiracy, charges of
obstruction and making false statements were dropped. Under the
plea bargain, Bennett said, prosecutors will recommend a five-year
sentence to be served after Gates' state term.
   Gates was accused of lying to National Transportation Safety
Board investigators in denying that he and brakeman Edward Cromwell
had smoked marijuana while operating the train.
   The federal indictment also accused Gates of lying about having
tested cab signals to make sure they were in working order.
Cromwell received state and federal immunity for his cooperation in
the investigation.
   The crash prompted the introduction of federal legislation to
tighten regulation of train crews.
   The legislation, passed by the House on Monday, would require
train licenses for engineers, make it illegal for crews to tamper
with safety devices and give the government more clout in handling
safety violations.
   The Senate is expected to approve the legislation this week as
well.
   Gates, in state court, admitted he failed to replace a cab
warning light bulb and fix a whistle that was taped over to keep it
from sounding. Either warning device would have alerted him to the
stop signals, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-25 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the Lemington Home for the Aged
released more than 500 balloons May 1 in search of pen pals, and
they're feeling inflated by the results.
   The balloons carried messages inviting whomever found them to
write a letter, and two letters arrived in response.
   The missives delighted the residents, especially Rebecca Hayden,
84, who heard from a woman in Morgantown, W.Va., said activities'
director Chaunita Burnett.
   ``She was really excited. She was showing it around ...
grinning. She's one of those chipper people anyway,'' Ms. Burnett
said Wednesday. ``It was a nice letter.''
   The balloons, released to commemorate Older Americans Month,
also brought a letter from a couple in Masontown, W.Va.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry and Alma Meyers and Merrel and Mary
Welage were married in a double-ring ceremony and had their first
and last children within six weeks of each other.
   Now they're getting together again _ to celebrate their 50th
wedding anniversaries.
   ``Before I could tell her I was pregnant, she told me she was
pregnant, too,'' said Mrs. Meyers, now 76.
   Mrs. Meyers and Mrs. Welage are sisters. Their husbands have
been friends since childhood in Cincinnati's Western Hills
neighborhood, where the couples still live. For years, the four
shared a house.
   The couples started celebrating Saturday with a party, and they
plan to return Saturday to St. Francis DeSales Church, the site of
their wedding, for a special Mass.
   ``Everyone wants to know how we did this, but it's just
coincidence,'' said Mrs. Welage, 74.
   The only thing the sisters actually planned was the
double-wedding ceremony on May 28, 1938.
   Meyers and Welage, both 73, presented the sisters with
engagement rings on Christmas Day in 1936 and 1937, respectively.
   ``We had a double wedding to spare my father the expense,'' said
Mrs. Meyers. ``We had the same dress when we got married. We bought
the material, and a dressmaker made them for $10 each. Can you
imagine?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
