<DOCNO> AP880525-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Economists'Book     05-25 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economists' Book,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Galbraith And Soviet Economist Are Co-Authors of Book</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economist John Kenneth Galbraith says he and a
Soviet counterpart, in collaborating on a new book, found that both
their countries are experiencing what they call superpower syndrome.
   Galbraith and Soviet economist Stanislav Menshikov, who have
known each other for more than 20 years, wanted to find out whether
each could write fairly about the other's economic system,
Galbraith said.
   Under a joint publication agreement, the book, ``Capitalism,
Communism and Coexistence: From the Bitter Past to a Better
Prospect,'' is being released in both the United States and the
Soviet Union.
   Today, Galbraith said, there are many similarities between the
United States and the Soviet Union, and the book offers hope that
both sides can work together.
   One of those similarities, he said, is the ``superpower
syndrome.''
   ``Both powers, the United States in Vietnam and the Soviet Union
in Afghanistan, have recently collided with the determination of
other peoples everywhere to conduct their own governments and run
their own lives,'' he said.
   Galbraith, 79, and Menshikov, 61, were in Chicago on Wednesday
to discuss the book at an awards breakfast sponsored by Clergy and
Laity Concerned, an interfaith group.
   The book is compiled from discussions Galbraith and Menshikov
conducted at Galbraith's summer home in Vermont.
   ``We wanted to see whether we could write a book that dealt
fairly and squarely with the problems of the two systems,''
Galbraith said Tuesday night in a telephone interview from his
hotel.
   Galbraith said the topics of the discussions include past
achievements of socialism and capitalism, the current problems of
both systems and suggested reforms for those problems.
   Galbraith, a native of Canada, has taught at Harvard and
Princeton universities and is the author of more than 20 books on
economics and other subjects. He has also held a number of
governmental posts including that of ambassador to India from
1961-63.
   Menshikov is staff editor of the World Marxist Review, published
in Prague, Czechoslovakia, and author of a number of books,
including an economic comparison of the United States, the Soviet
Union and Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0172 </DOCNO>
