<DOCNO> AP880525-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Migrants     05-25 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Migrants,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hindu Migrant Workers Flee Punjab After Sikh Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAJJAT, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Hindu migrant workers are
fleeing Punjab following attacks by Sikh extremists who are waging
a war of terror in their quest for a separate homeland.
   Police say 65 migrant laborers have been killed by Sikh gunmen
in the past week.
   ``Even if I have to die at this age, I must die among my
relatives,'' said Piara Ram, 26, who was leaving for his home in
Uttar Pradesh state. ``There would be someone to cry for me.''
   The migrant workers' departure could seriously undermine
Punjab's economy.
   The Punjab Labor Department estimates the state employs about
700,000 migrant workers a year, most for planting and harvesting in
the nation's richest agricultural state.
   Several sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about
one-third have left since the Sikh extremists' raids escalated
earlier this month. The state government acknowledges laborers have
returned home but gives no figures.
   Construction work has nearly stopped on a major canal designed
to carry Punjab river water to neighboring states, and even migrant
rickshaw pullers and other manual laborers are leaving.
   Although radical Sikhs have frequently attacked Hindus in their
six-year struggle for greater autonomy or an independent nation in
Punjab, they started singling out Hindu migrnt laborers during the
police siege of the Golden Temple. The 10-day siege, aimed at
driving armed Sikhs out of the shrine, ended May 18 after more than
200 Sikh extremists and their supporters surrendered.
   Although Punjab officials have pledged to protect the migrants _
who come mainly from the poor northern states of Bihar, Orissa and
Uttar Pradesh _ many say they are returning home rather than face
more terrorism by Sikh extremists.
   Police say the attacks may have a dual purpose: to reduce the
number of Hindus in Punjab and to undermine the state's economy.
   The attacks began May 17 when 31 men and women working on the
Sutlej-Yamuna Link Canal were shot to death by Sikhs at their camp
near Majjat, 30 miles northwest of the state capital at Chandigarh.
The gunmen then burned the bodies.
   Seventy other camp workers fled to nearby fields and hid from
the gunmen. A day later, they begged the government to arrange for
their return to Bihar and Orissa states.
   The attack was claimed by the Khalistan Commando Force, one of
the largest of a dozen Sikh extremist groups active in Punjab. In a
note left with the bodies, the group said it avenging the siege of
the Golden Temple and threatened more reprisals.
   The charred bodies of the 31 laborers remain in the deserted
campsite, and bloodstains still can be seen on the muddy footpaths
leading to their tents.
   The canal project they were working on has lost almost 7,500 of
its 10,000 workers, according to figures provided by the canal
headquarters at Chandigarh.
   The Sikh militants, and some Sikh moderates, oppose the canal
because it is designed to carry water from Punjab to the
neighboring states of Haryana and Rajasthan. The militants contend
it will reduce the water available for irrigation in Punjab, a
``breadbasket'' state of wheat fields, rice paddies and sugar cane
plantations.
   Romesh Kumar Sharma, a contractor on two bridges being built
along the canal, said work was all but stopped on the canal and
could not be resumed unless the migrants were lured back to the
project.
   The average migrant worker in Punjab earns betweeen $38 and $46
per month. Most send money home to support their families. Jobs in
their native states are hard to find and pay much less.
   Lubhaya, a rickshaw puller, worked for seven years in Ludhiana,
the district capital, but was at the railway station this week
waiting for a train. He said he was leaving ``the death land of
Punjab'' for good.
   Ram Kumar Sharma, owner of a brick kiln in Ropar District just
north of Chandigarh, said many of his 35 migrant employees have
left. Chaman Lal, another kiln owner, estimated that two-thirds of
the district's 1,700 migrant kiln workers have fled.
   An official at the state's Home Ministry, which is responsible
for internal security, said special camps would be set up for
migrants to make them feel more secure.
   In Ropar District, Deputy Commissioner J.R. Kundal said security
would be provided for the canal workers' camps, and he urged
laborers to stay.
   ``If you don't work here, what will you or your family members
eat?'' he asked them. He did not say when the security would be
provided.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
