<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmScene 1stLd-Writethru a0649 05-25 0987</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,1016</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers To Earn Less Than Last Year, Department Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf of 2nd item pvs, bgng: Curran disclosed, to
CORRECT pension amount to $35,000</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising production costs and cutbacks in
federal payments are keeping up the pressure on farmers this year,
says a new outlook report by the Agriculture Department.
   Net cash income of farmers is forecast at $50 billion to $55
billion this year, down from the record of $57 billion in 1987, the
report released Tuesday said. That is unchanged from USDA's
previous forecasts.
   The department's Economic Research Service added that underlying
the forecast are improvements in several of agriculture's key
fundamentals:
   _ Use of most of the major commodities has increased, thereby
reducing burdensome stockpiles.
   _ Market prices for those commodities are approaching or are
higher the government's support levels.
   _ Higher cattle prices have offset minor declines in production.
   _ Interest rates have continued to be moderate.
   _ Total farm debt is declining for the fifth consecutive year,
indicating further gains in the financial position of operators.
   ``Production expenses are expected to rise, after declining at
an unprecedented rate the last three years,'' the report said.
   Spring fertilizer prices were up 10 percent from a year ago, and
those ``will be felt most by corn and barley producers, whose
outlays for fertilizer make up 38 percent and 30 percent,
respectively, of variable costs,'' the report said. ``The Corn Belt
will be the region most affected.''
   Energy expenses may rise about 5 percent this year, with cash
grain, and cattle and hog operations accounting for more than 60
percent of fuel costs last year. Again, the Corn Belt will be most
affected.
   Thus, the drop in 1988 net cash income _ the difference between
gross cash income and cash expenses _ will be mostly due to higher
cash expenses outweighing greater cash receipts from the sale of
crops and livestock.
   Further, the report said, direct payments to farmers in 1988 are
expected to drop by as much as 20 percent from last year's $17
billion.
   Despite the dip in cash income this year, analysts said the
balance sheet of U.S. agriculture continues to show improvement
from the hard-pressed economy of a few years ago.
   ``With improving income, lower debt and adequate credit for farm
real estate loans, buyers are coming back into the real estate
market,'' the report said. ``With recent improvements in cash flow,
many land sales have been for cash.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has hired a new
administrator for the Agricultural Research Service under an
arrangement that gives him an annual benefits package worth
$126,500 a year at taxpayer expense.
   Ronald D. Plowman, 59, is leaving his job as head of the
department of animal, dairy and veterinary sciences at Utah State
University to take over the Agricultural Research Service, or ARS,
at a salary of $77,500. Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng
announced the appointment on April 15.
   But that is only part of the story, says Ed Curran, a retired
USDA editor who writes a twice-monthly newsletter that often
includes gadfly accounts of department goings-on.
   Curran disclosed in his latest issue that Plowman will continue
to draw a federal pension of about $35,000 a year, earned in 27
years on the job with ARS from 1956 to 1984, when he retired and
went to work for Utah State.
   The Plowman job package involves an ``IPA'' maneuver provided by
the federal Intergovernmental Personnel Act, which allows state
governments to get the loan of federal experts or send their
employees to Washington on a short-term basis.
   In this particular case, confirmed Tuesday by agency officials,
Plowman technically will be on loan from the university, which will
pay his salary while in Washington. The USDA, in turn, will
reimburse the university $77,500 a year.
   Plowman also will get $14,000 a year in federal per diem to help
pay moving expenses and make up for higher living costs in the
Washington area.
   Normally, Plowman would give up his federal retirement income
while returning to work at the USDA agency. But under the IPA
arrangement, Plowman will be able keep his pension income. Although
the ``loan'' deal with Utah State is for a year, officials said the
contract is renewable on the same terms.
   Thus, Plowman's prospective income of $126,500 a year is
substantially more than Lyng's pay of $99,500 or members of
Congress, who get $89,500 a year.
   If Plowman converts over to federal employment, severing his
connection with Utah State, he automatically would be cut off from
his old pension benefits _ at least until he retires again from
federal service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rains last month brought temporary relief to
many parched areas of the West where the outlook for this summer's
water supply had been poor, says the Agriculture Department.
   ``While drought continues in many areas, it certainly is good to
see an increase in rainfall,'' Wilson Scaling, chief of the
department's Soil Conservation Service, said Tuesday. ``We're
hoping this change will develop into a long-term pattern.''
   Scaling said precipitation in April was near to above normal in
most areas west of the Rocky Mountains. The Columbia Basin got
above-normal precipitation, and Arizona received twice its April
average.
   ``Reservoir storage is very good in the Colorado and Rio Grande
basins,'' he said. ``We also expect reservoirs in Arizona and New
Mexico to fill.''
   But Scaling said the water supply outlook in other areas is not
nearly so bright.
   ``Some areas in Montana will be facing water supply shortages as
early as next month,'' he said. ``There are also sections of
California, Nevada, Oregon, Idaho and Washington that remain very
dry despite the recent increase in precipitation.''
   Scaling added: ``It's going to take a lot more than just one
good month of precipitation to ease the drought in those areas.''
</TEXT>
