<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviet     05-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviet,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Diplomats Going to Moscow for First Time 21 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel will send diplomats to Moscow to take up
consular duties for the first time in 21 years, a Foreign Ministry
official said Wednesday.
   Another Ministry official told Israel army radio he hoped the
agreement between the two countries would eventually lead to full
diplomatic ties. The official, political adviser Nimrod Novick,
declined to describe the pact as a breakthrough in Soviet-Israeli
relations.
   ``What we are talking about is dipping ourselves in the water to
check if it is hot or cold,'' he said. ``It remains to be seen when
our delegates reach Moscow, how well they will be received.''
   The Soviets agreed to issue visas to the Israeli diplomats
during a secret meeting Monday in Zurich, Switzerland, Novick told
the station.
   The other ministry source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said diplomats from the Jewish state could leave for the Soviet
capital as early as next week.
   The Soviet Union broke ties with Israel when the Jewish state
captured the occupied West Bank, Gaza Strip and Golan Heights from
the Kremlin's Arab allies in the 1967 Middle East war.
   This week's agreement came 10 months after Soviet consular
officials began operating from the Finnish Embassy in Tel Aviv.
   Novick, who negotiated for the visas, said the Soviets resisted
Israeli efforts to have the diplomats handle visas to Israel for
Soviet Jewish emigres. ``It looked like it was broadening things to
the Soviets,'' he said.
   But he added that the Soviets agreed not to restrict other
contacts between the Israelis and Soviet Jews.
   Israel's diplomats will administer an embassy building that has
been vacant since 1967 but for which Israel has continued to pay
monthly rent, Novick said.
   The diplomats, up to six in number, will work from the Dutch
Embassy, where visas for Jewish emigres are processed, according to
sources quoted by Israeli media.
   The agreement followed two months of secret contacts with
Vladimir Terrasov, deputy head of the Soviet Foreign Ministry's
Middle East Department, Novick said.
   In the past two years, Kremlin leaders have improved ties with
Israel to try to gain a role in peace efforts in the Middle East.
That led to the agreement nearly a year ago for the eight-member
consular team to come to Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
