<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   05-25 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0815</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   May 19
   The Dispatch, Union City, N.J., on Reagan administration and
Noriega:
   The Reagan administration ... reportedly has offered to dismiss
15 indictments brought against Gen. (Manuel Antonio) Noriega by
grand juries in Miami and Tampa, Fla., if he will resign as
Panama's military commander ... and leave the country until after
the 1990 presidential elections.
   Somebody must be kidding.
   Noriega is accused ... of taking $4.6 million in payoffs from
Colombia's violent Medellin cartel to protect cocaine shipments,
launder money, supply drug laboratories and shelter the gang's
leaders from law enforcement.
   Why should it bother him to go into ``exile'' until 1990? He
will simply leave his corrupt cronies in place to keep the drugs
and money flowing, while he serves his time in some pleasure spot.
   President Reagan's ``war against drugs'' has been anything but
successful and dismissing the indictments would indicate the United
States condones drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   Providence (R.I.) Journal-Bulletin on the addictiveness of
smoking:
   On the surface, the essence of the U.S. surgeon general's annual
report on smoking _ that nicotine is potently addictive _ is
nothing new. Anyone who has ever smoked regularly then tried to
stop knows painfully well the hold nicotine has on people.
   Yet this year's report equates the addiction of nicotine to that
of heroin and cocaine, and in the process raises some eyebrows.
   Can it really be as difficult to give up smoking as it is to
stop shooting up with heroin?
   With such a comparison isn't there a danger that now smokers
will begin to be equated with drug users and, perhaps, shunned by
employers _ when their functioning under the influence of nicotine
has no relation to one's functioning under that, say, of heroin?
   Adults who choose to indulge their habit ... ought to be free to
do so, except in outlawed premises, for in their cases they are the
only ones affected.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 24
   Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch on the ouster of Hungary's party
leader Janos Kadar:
   (Janos Kadar's) successor as Communist Party chief, the
reputedly pragmatic Karoly Grosz, urges faster moves to a freer
market, and a party more open to dissent _ but only, of course,
from within.
   It is Soviet General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev's experiment on
a smaller scale. ...
   His loyalty to Moscow is assured: He first made his mark in the
party on the Soviet side in the 1956 revolution.
   He has considerable experience as the party's agitation and
propaganda chief, useful skills in attracting the attention and
assistance of a sympathetic West and in deflecting internal
criticism.
   Just the man for Mikhail Gorbachev to wish well, and watch
closely.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   Springfield (Mo.) News-Leader on barring a student for school
office:
   Mike Landgrave learned his lesson at La Quinta High School in
Westminster, Calif.
   The student was barred from seeking office as student council
president after he said in his campaign speech that it is
``important to promote safe sex.''
   The question is what lesson school officials hoped to teach
young people. Maybe the Westminster board of education should ask
itself is who needs an education. And who should be listening to
whom?

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   Medford (Ore.) Mail Tribune on the Supreme Court's decision on
garbage:
   Individuals who view their garbage as being forever theirs
should be aware that things have changed.
   The U.S. Supreme Court ruled ... that trash placed outside for
the weekly pickup is not covered by the Fourth Amendment's
protection against illegal search and seizure by police. ...
   Anyone who has ever had a nighttime visit by roving mutts knows
better than to talk about the safety of trash bags.
   One experience with toppled trash cans, tattered bags and
littered sidewalks affirms the majority's conclusion that people
have ``no expectation of privacy'' when they haul their trash out
to the curb.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   The Duncan (Okla.) Banner on Edwin Meese:
   If Attorney General Ed Meese is an honorable man, he should see
that now is the time for him to step aside.
   While Meese has not been convicted or even indicted for any
offense, he has at the very least been guilty of poor judgment.
   Meese's effectiveness has been lost as he has to spend virtually
all of his time responding to the various ongoing investigations
concerning his conduct while in government.
   If Meese is really concerned for the good of his country, then
he should see that it is time to go.
</TEXT>
