<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   05-25 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: their effects?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 18
   The Commercial Appeal, Memphis, Tenn., on congressional
appropriations:
   Members of Congress hoping to dip into the congressional pork
barrel this year for new water and energy projects will find
themselves on a well-deserved starvation diet if the House
Appropriations Committee has its way.
   The committee decreed, for the first time in the memory of those
who serve on it, that no money will be appropriated for the next
fiscal year to start construction of new water or energy projects.
   It isn't that the committee has suddenly become allergic to
``pork.'' It's just that committee members felt constrained to
honor a two-year agreement reached at last December's White
House-Congress budget summit to keep costs down to reduce the
federal deficit. ...
   But this being an election year, few politicians are eager to
endorse increased taxes, even to satisfy the desires of House and
Senate members who gain bragging rights for federally funded
projects that benefit their districts and states. ...
   It's gratifying that, however brief and limited it may be, the
House Appropriations Committee decided to give taxpayers a break
from higher pork-barrel spending.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 21
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on George Bush:
   (Last) week (George) Bush began the task of cutting the apron
strings.
   Although the Reagan administration is apparently willing to drop
drug trafficking charges against Panama strongman Manuel Noriega if
he'll relinquish power, Bush has declared he would never negotiate
with drug dealers.
   The conflict doesn't bother the president. White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater says the president takes no offense, adding that
``I expect a number of them (Bush's positions) will be different
than existing policies'' during the campaign. ...
   There are other good reasons for Bush to stop masquerading as
Son of Reagan.
   First, it's not all positive. Reagan's refusal to fire Attorney
General Edwin Meese III is a millstone around Bush's neck. So are
charges that the Reagan administration had links with Noriega.
   Beyond that, however, although he's been in government for
decades, Bush has never articulated clearly where he stands in
terms of political philosophy. He's drifted from one administration
to another, his beliefs often shifting with political winds.
   Cutting loose from Reasgan provides Bush with the opportunity to
develop his own clear agenda in a post-Reagan presidency. And he's
got to if he is to have any hope of succeeding the boss.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   The Augusta (Ga.) Chronicle on Michael Dukakis:
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis says he wants
to ``end Reaganomics.''
   But wait a minute. America is in its 66th straight month of the
longest and strongest recovery in U.S. peacetime history.
   The economy is still creating jobs at a 3 million annual rate
through the first four months, for a record 15.6 million since the
recovery began in December, 1982.
   Incidentally, according to economist Warren Brookes, over the
past year 63 percent of new jobs were ``professional and
managerial,'' and only 1 percent were in ``service occupations,''
thus finally silencing all the yammering about ``hamburger
flippers.''
   Democrats are trying to claim that inflation looms as the nation
moves closer to full employment. The policies of the Federal
Reserve Board, of course, will determine if this could become a
serious problem.
   But Brookes reminds us of some recent history: In the last seven
years, as the jobless rate has fallen two points (28 percent),
inflation as measured by the Gross National Product deflator has
also fallen, by more than 7 points (75 percent).
   Vice President Bush needs to tell voters about it; the liberal
Big Media won't.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 23
   Milwaukee (Wis.) Sentinel on the drug war:
   The wages of sin can be an effective weapon in the war against
crime _ but less so in Wisconsin.
   That's because money or property seized from criminals in drug
raids isn't kept by state or local law enforcement agencies for use
in future drug buys, but is turned over to the state school fund.
   As a result, and because the state civil forfeiture proceeding
takes longer than the federal procedure, local prosecutors often
involve federal authorities in the cases.
   After custody of money has been obtained by federal officials,
they return the cash to local authorities, keeping 10 percent to 20
percent for administrative costs.
   That 10 percent to 20 percent could be used here in Wisconsin if
state law was changed to speed things up and to allow local
agencies to keep the loot they seize. The loss to the school fund
probably would be negligible, considering that local authorities
now use the federal option anyway.
   Far from negligible would be the gain if that money helped
capture another drug trafficker.
</TEXT>
