<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DutchThefts     05-25 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dutch Thefts,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rash of Thefts From Dutch Museums</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thives struck museums in two
cities in the days following the biggest art theft in Dutch
history, officials said Wednesday.
   On Sunday, thieves at Amsterdam's Biblical Museum forced open a
glass showcase and stole six antique Egyptian statuettes, according
to the Rotterdam newspaper NRC Handelsblad.
   The bronze and clay figures, worth an estimated $7,800 to
$10,400, apparently were stolen while the museum was open, the
report said.
   The theft came two days after thieves broke into Amsterdam's
Municipal Museum and stole three paintings estimated at up to $52
million, including works by Vincent van Gogh and Paul Cezanne. The
theft highlighted the relatively low security at the museum which
houses 3,000 mainly modern masterworks but has no night guard.
   The burglary triggered an electronic alarm, but it took up to 20
minutes for police and security officials to arrive on the scene.
   Later that day, thieves smashed a showcase and stole two jewelry
items in the Dutch Literary Museum in The Hague, according to
museum director Anton Korteweg.
   The stolen cameo brooch and a gold-edged medallion were worth
several thousand dollars, Korteweg told The Associated Press,
adding the incident at his museum also occurred while it was open
to the public.
   The Literary Museum, housed in the ultra-modern Royal Library
complex, has electronic surveillance and a night guard, and owns a
collection of manuscripts, books and other objects associated with
Dutch literary figures.
   The Biblical Museum, which has a collection of artifacts from
the Holy Land, had only one guard on duty at the time of the theft,
the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
