<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTC-Trucking     05-25 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Trucking,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truck Deregulation Said Saving Billions Without Hurting Safety,
Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The partial deregulation of the trucking
industry has saved the economy tens of billions of dollars a year
while having little effect on safety or service to small
communities, a staff report by the Federal Trade Commission
concluded Wednesday.
   FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver cited the report in calling for the
removal of remaining federal and state economic restrictions on the
commercial trucking industry. His views were endorsed by Heather
Gradison, chairman of the Interstate Commerce Commission.
   According to the FTC staff study, between $39 billion and $63
billion are being saved annually because of increased competition
and efficiencies flowing from the partial deregulation of the
trucking industry eight years ago.
   ``The best available estimates ... suggest that the gains have
outweighed the losses by approximately 20 to 1,'' concluded the
report released by the FTC's bureau of economics. The commission
has not formally endorsed the findings.
   The Motor Carrier Act of 1980 greatly eased entry into the
trucking business by making it easier for a trucking company to
begin operating along a particular route. In recent years
applications for a route have been denied only rarely. It also has
become easier for carriers to set their own rates.
   The FTC staff report by economist Diane Owen said the easing of
government control over the trucking industry ``has resulted in new
shipping services and greater scheduling and pricing flexibility,''
leading to increased savings and allowing shippers to better
compete with foreign companies.
   Ms. Owen acknowledged that there have been concerns about
deregulation on some trucking companies as well as about truck
safety and a possible decline in services to small and rural
communities.
   The report said that despite these concerns trucking services to
small communities generally have improved or remained unchanged,
deregulation ``does not appear to have adversely affected safety''
and while many trucking companies have gone out of business the
overall number of companies and employees in the industry has
increased.
   The report said that while interstate commerce has benefited
from deregulation, ``continued state regulation costs consumers and
the economy billions of dollars annually.''
   Oliver called for additional action, ``removing the yoke of
unnecessary economic regulation'' that still exists of the trucking
industry. The Transportation Department has sought further
deregulation of trucking, but Congress so far has not taken action.
   Meanwhile, Oliver said, states should eliminate many of their
retrictions on commercial trucking.
   ``In California it now costs more to ship goods from Oakland to
San Francisco, a distance of 15 miles, than to ship interstate from
Reno to San Francisco,'' Oliver said.
</TEXT>
