<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Reagan     05-25 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Reagan,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Fifth Summit Could Bring Strategic Missile Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says he may hold
another summit with Mikhail S. Gorbachev yet this year to finish
work on a treaty to reduce long-range nuclear missiles, according
to a published report.
   In an interview with the Die Welt newspaper published in its
Thursday editions, Reagan also said he wants his NATO partners to
pay more of the alliance's expenses.
   The interview was conducted in Washington before Reagan left for
Moscow and his fourth summit with Gorbachev.
   ``President Reagan figures that the START treaty, which foresees
the halving of nuclear intercontinental missiles, still can be
brought to completion before the end of his term,'' the
conservative daily said.
   Advance copies of the report were provided to other media
Wednesday. The German-language excerpts were translated into
English by The Associated Press.
   Die Welt said Reagan told the journalists that the Soviets are
interested in concluding an Intercontinental Ballistic Missile
treaty with him, rather than waiting until his successor takes over
in January.
   ``Therefore, the president doesn't exclude the possibility of a
fifth summit conference with Gorbachev this year on neutral
ground,'' the newspaper said.
   Reagan, who left Washington for Finland on Wednesday en route to
Moscow, met with Gorbachev in Geneva in November 1985, in
Reykjavik, Iceland in October 1986, and in Washington in December
1987.
   During the interview, Die Welt said Reagan was asked how he gets
along with Gorbachev.
   ``We can discuss delicate issues without lingering on personal
bad feelings. I believe there is actually a certain degree of
friendship between us,'' Die Welt quoted Reagan as saying.
   The newspaper also said Reagan touched on problems facing the
Americans in financing costs of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and urged that other NATO partners share more of the
burden.
   ``I don't think this is an area that should cause bad blood
between us,'' Die Welt quoted Reagan as saying.
   ``But it would be helpful if the allies would carry more of the
load, especially since the American Congress for years has declined
to approve further increases for defense,'' the newspaper quoted
the president as saying.
   Reagan told the reporters he is pleased that Gorbachev's policy
of glasnost, or more openness in Soviet society, has influenced
other East bloc countries.
   Die Welt said Reagan also made reference to last weekend's
Communist Party leadership change in Hungary, in which Janos Kadar,
who had led the party 32 years, was replaced as premier by Karoly
Grosz.
   Reagan said Kadar had ``simply been in office too long,'' Die
Welt reported.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Following material embargoed by source until 2 a.m. EDT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thursday
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Asked what chance he saw for the signing of a START treaty at a
fifth summit meeting with the Soviets before he leaves office on
Jan. 20, 1989, Reagan said: ``I can't discount that. I certainly
don't want to say that it is impossible, because I believe we can
exclude signing a START treaty at this summit.''
   ``I believe however, that negotiations in this summit will bring
us further, and I hope that it can be concluded while I am still in
office,'' he told the newspaper.
   ``I also believe that the other side also thinks this way, that
unnecessary delay could be caused if they had to wait until my
successor becomes familiar with the job and is in the position to
work with them (the Soviets).
   ``Therefore, I hope that we can clear up all remaining questions
during my time in office. Then it can be that we decide to sign
this treaty at a new meeting and not separated by thousands of
miles.
   ``Since we have visited each other in our home countries, we
would probably decide on a neutral location,'' for the signing,
Reagan told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End embargoed material</HEAD>
