<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomeSales     05-25 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increase in Sales of Existing Homes at 17-Month High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes increased 4.5 percent
in April, the biggest advance in 17 months, as buyers rushed to
close deals before interest rates went up, a real estate trade
group said Wednesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said existing single-family
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.48
million units last month, following increases of 2.5 percent in
both February and March.
   John Tuccillo, chief economist for the association, predicted
that sales would be slowed in the months ahead by rising mortgage
rates.
   Rates for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages hit a low this year of
9.84 percent on Feb. 12 and have been rising since then, climbing
to 10.52 percent last week, according to a survey by the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Home prices edged down slightly in April with the median price
of a home falling to $87,700. While this was down $200 from the
March median sales price, it was still up from a year ago, when the
median price was $86,000.
   The slight March-to-April decline in the median price masked
wide regional differences. Home prices rose 5.3 percent in the
Northeast to $145,100, the highest in the country. Prices were up a
slight 0.4 percent in the Midwest to a median of $67,500. Prices
fell 4.6 percent in the West to $113,700 and were down 1.4 percent
in the South to $82,100.
   Tuccillo said the slight overall decline in home prices was an
indication that prices were finally leveling off and would increase
only modestly for the remainder of the year.
   The association is predicting that resales of existing homes
will total 3.31 million this year, down 6 percent from the 3.52
million homes sold in 1987.
   The overall April increase was led by a 6.2 percent increase in
sales in the Northeast, which climbed to an annual rate of 690,000
units.
   Sales were up 5.7 percent in the South to an annual rate of 1.3
million units, while the Midwest had a 2.3 percent increase in
sales to an annual rate of 900,000.
   The West was the only region of the country to have a decline in
sales, a drop of 1.8 percent to an annual rate of 560,000 units.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
