<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VASlaying     05-25 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VA Slaying,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect Ordered To Psychiactric Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KERRVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A World War II veteran accused of
shooting his benefits counselor has been ordered to undergo
treatment at a state hospital after being found incompetent to
stand trial for murder, officials said.
   A jury ruled Tuesday that Rufus William Smith, 63, of Stonewall
was incompetent to stand trial on charges that he killed John
Walker Pettit, 54.
   State District Judge V. Murray Jordan ordered Smith committed to
Vernon State Hospital. Smith had been in the Kerr County Jail in
lieu of $250,000 bond in the slaying Jan. 20.
   Jurors heard two days of testimony before deciding that the
former Marine was incompetent to stand trial now, and that ``there
is no substantial probability that he will attain competency in the
foreseeable future.''
   Pettit was a veterans affairs counselor for the Texas Veterans
Commission who was handling Smith's claims.
   District Attorney Ron Sutton said Smith was enraged by delays in
his medical claims and shot Pettit in the counselor's office near
the Veterans Administration Hospital, as Pettit's wife, Linda, and
other workers watched.
   Testimony Monday indicated Smith believed that VA officials had
been keeping duplicate files on him.
   Smith claimed officials removed information from his records
that showed he killed Japanese soldiers during World War II. He
believed the lack of that information was keeping him from getting
full disability payments, Sutton said.
   Smith, who had undergone treatment at the VA hospital, had
sought full medical disability instead of the partial claims he was
being awarded.
   Dr. Robert G. Harper of the Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston testified that he examined Smith in 1982 and diagnosed him
as a paranoid schizophrenic who believed Pettit was the source of
his troubles.
   Smith's attorney, Scott Stehling of Kerrville, said Smith's
family wanted him to receive treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
