<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Singapore     05-25 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Singapore,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Assails Singapore Over Allegations Against American Diplomats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States assailed Singapore on
Wednesday for continuing to allege that American diplomats are
meddling in its domestic politics.
   ``In spite of our denials, the government of Singapore continues
to allege that U.S. diplomats engaged in activities not in keeping
with accepted international practice and interfered in Singapore's
domestic affairs,'' said State Department spokesman Charles Redman.
   ``The United States is not, and has not been, engaged in
interference in Singapore's domestic affairs. All activities of
U.S. government officials in dealing with Singapore have been
legitimate and in full accordance with customary diplomatic
practice,'' he added.
   The dispute centers around allegations by Singapore that
American embassy officers met with Singaporan lawyers and urged
them to run against Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, who is expected to
retain control of the island nation's parliament in elections
scheduled for next year.
   The United States contends that its diplomats meet routinely
with members of the constitutional opposition in other countries to
keep abreast of political developments.
   Earlier this month, Singapore asked the United States to remove
one of its embassy officers, and the United States retaliated by
asking for the ouster of a Singaporan diplomat stationed in
Washington.
</TEXT>
