   Jacobs listed exact amounts and items for which no reporting is
required, such as his home, equity in his pension plan,
automobiles, and home and office furnishings. The $111,358 he
reported as ``gifts'' was an estimate of the value of his defense
without fee by the Washington law firm of Arnet, Fox, Kintner,
Plotkin & Kahn in a libel case brought by evangelist Pat Robertson.
Jacobs won the case, but still had to pay $14,000 for other
expenses.
   This was the case that revolved around Jacobs' tip to reporters
that Robertson had bragged that his father, a U.S. senator, had
pulled strings to keep Robertson out of combat in Korea. Robertson
later dropped a similar action against McCloskey.
   Jacobs counted himself extraordinarily wealthy, since he claimed
his dog, a Great Dane named Friend, as a ``priceless'' asset.

