<DOCNO> AP880525-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam 1stLd-Writethru a0733 05-25 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam and U.S. Discussing High-Level Meeting on Resettlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead to clarify; SUBS last graf with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with number of prisoners released</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam and the United States are considering
a high-level meeting to discuss the resettlement of Vietnamese who
worked with Americans during the war and have been freed from
prison camps there, the State Department said Wednesday.
   Spokesman Charles Redman said Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen
Co Thatch sent a May 23 message through the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok, Thailand, asking for a meeting with U.S. presidential
envoy retired Army Gen. John Vessey.
   Vessey held talks with Vietnamese officials in Hanoi last year
on stepping up efforts to find some 2,500 Americans missing in
action from the Indochinese war.
   Contacts with Vietnam, which does not have diplomatic relations
with the United States, have been sporadic in recent years. The
United States has adopted a policy of isolating Vietnam
economically and diplomatically in order to pressure the Hanoi
government into ending its 10-year military occupation of Cambodia.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz sent a letter last month to
Thatch welcoming Vietnam's release of hundreds of prisoners from
so-called re-education camps in September 1987 and February 1988,
Redman said.
   But Shultz's letter also expressed ``our concern about the fate
of these prisoners because of their association with us and the
former Saigon government,'' Redman said.
   The former Vietnamese officials and loyalists were placed in
prison camps after Communist North Vietnam defeated U.S.-backed
South Vietnam in 1975.
   Shultz asked Thatch to discuss resettlement of the released
prisoners in the United States, a move which ``reflects our
continuing concern for the welfare of our former allies,'' Redman
added.
   Slightly more than 1,000 political prisoners were freed in
February 1988, and Vietnamese officials have assured the United
States that fewer than 150 people remain in re-education camps,
said a State Department official.
   The official, who asked not to be named, said some 900,000
Vietnamese had undergone short-term or long-term ``re-education''
since 1975. He said only a handful of those who were released from
the camps have come to the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0204 </DOCNO>
