<1ST_LINE>r p AM-StatePrimaries     05-25 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Primaries,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Kentucky Incumbents Win Primaries; Idaho Voters Select
Challengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three incumbent Democratic congressmen easily won primary
contests in Kentucky, while Idaho's two incumbent congressmen
prepared to face challengers selected in that state's primary.
   Rep. Carroll Hubbard, who represents Kentucky's 1st District,
won a lopsided victory Tuesday over Lacey T. Smith in what was
called the nastiest campaign in the country.
   ``This has been a long, expensive and arduous campaign and I'm
glad it's over,'' Hubbard said after receiving 73 percent of the
vote. Hubbard is all but assured of election victory since the only
Republican who filed for the nomination has withdrawn. One
little-known independent candidate will provide Hubbard's only
opposition.
   Hubbard buried Smith, 63,136 votes to 23,153 votes.
   The other two members of Kentucky's seven-member congressional
delegation who faced opposition also won handily.
   Rep. Romano Mazzoli, who has represented the 3rd District since
1970, rolled up 61 percent of the vote. Mazzoli received 31,288
votes to Jeffrey Hutter's 20,207.
   Mazzoli will face former assistant U.S. Attorney Philip Dunnagan
in the general election. Dunnagan won the GOP nomination against
three others on the ballot.
   Rep. William H. Natcher, who has held the 2nd Congressional
District seat since 1953, won 76 percent of the vote. Natcher
pulled 26,918 votes to 8,319 for Bob Evans.
   Natcher's opponent in November will be retired Army officer
Martin A. Tori who was unopposed for the Republican nomination.
   In Idaho, two-term Democratic state Rep. Jeanne Givens, 37, of
Coeur d'Alene, won a three-way primary Tuesday to face four-term
Republican Rep. Larry Craig in the state's 1st Congressional
District. Givens had 18,097 votes, or 63 percent.
   In Idaho's 2nd Congressional District, former state legislator
Dane Watkins, 44, of Idaho Falls defeated one other candidate for
the Republican nomination to oppose two-term Democratic Rep.
Richard Stallings. Watkins garnered 20,547 votes, or 59 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
