<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LotteryWinners     05-25 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottery Winners,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lottery Bill: You Can't Take it With You, So Get it Up Front</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because you can't take it with you, the
state Senate approved a bill Wednesday that would allow lottery
winners over 65 to receive their winnings sooner than younger
people who hit the jackpot.
   Older lottery winners could take the current value of their
lottery prize in one lump sum or in periodic payments over their
expected lifetime.
   ``The usual 20-year payoff on a lottery prize will not always
result in a total benefit to the winner who is over 65, as he may
not live to receive the full benefit,'' said a memo on the bill.
   ``The fact that the unpaid balance would be paid to his estate
is of little consolation to many elderly winners who may wish to
fully enjoy the fruits of their good fortune,'' the memo said.
   But John Quinn, director of the Lottery Division, said he
opposes the bill because it would substantially reduce jackpots.
   The jackpot up Wednesday was $3 million.
   ``I don't have $3 million to give them, I have $1.4 million,''
he said. ``The difference is interest money.''
   Under the current plan, a winner would receive 21 annual
payments of $114,000 after taxes, said Quinn. If someone opted to
take the prize in a $1.4 million lump sum, they would owe about
$580,000 in taxes, he said.
   Quinn said he didn't believe any state lotteries now offer the
lump-sum option.
   The average million-dollar lottery winner is 49 years old, said
Quinn.
   Quinn said he had not informed the state Legislature of his
opposition to the bill, now before the Assembly Ways and Means
Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
