<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-White     05-25 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-White,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Dealers Give AIDS Victim Ryan White New Set Of Wheels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A beaming Ryan White climbed behind the
wheel of his very own car Wednesday and said he planned to drive
``anywhere and everywhere'' _ just as soon as he gets a driver's
license.
   The 16-year-old AIDS victim received the black 1987 Chevrolet
Cavalier from the Indiana Independent Automobile Dealers
Association during brief ceremonies at the Auto Dealer's Exchange,
an auto auction house.
   ``Ryan has shown that the ordinary things in life can be
ennobling. He has the kind of courage that I think most of us would
like to have,'' Fritz Kreutzinger, president of the association,
said before handing Ryan the keys.
   ``I just want to tell everybody thanks, and I really appreciate
it,'' Ryan said.
   When asked what he planned to do with the car, White said,
``Drive it. I'm going to go anywhere and everywhere.''
   Ryan has completed driver's education classes and plans to get
his license June 9.
   ``Somebody came up with the idea for Ryan because we saw on TV
that he was going to get his driver's license,'' said Kreutzinger,
of Fishers. ``The heart of this is just a bunch of guys willing to
kick in and do something.''
   Kreutzinger said individuals had donated the sunroof and stereo
for the car, which has 25,000 miles on it. Ryan's mother, Jeanne
White, said the car met all her son's requirements: black with
tinted windows and bucket seats.
   Ryan was diagnosed as having acquired immune deficiency syndrome
in December 1984. He contracted the AIDS virus through blood
products used in the treatment of his hemophilia.
   In the summer of 1985, officials at Western School Corp. near
Kokomo banned him from classes at Western Middle School. Although
he won a long legal battle to stay in school, Mrs. White moved her
family early last year to Cicero, 25 miles north of Indianapolis.
Her son enrolled in Hamilton Heights High School, where
administrators and classmates welcomed him.
   The Whites were expected to travel to New York on Thursday for a
UNICEF benefit with Nancy Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
