<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialMoney     05-25 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Money,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Matching Funds Distributed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission distributed
$1.7 million in federal matching funds to presidential candidates
Wednesday, bringing to $56.2 million the total the government has
given out in the primary campaign this year.
   Four candidates were certified for money on Wednesday:
Republican Vice President George Bush, $289,792; Democrats Michael
Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, $369,442, and Jesse Jackson,
$967,942, and independent Lenora Fulani, $42,289.
   The candidate who has received the most matching funds overall,
Republican Pat Robertson, has suspended his campaign and received
no money on Wednesday.
   He has received $8.6 million, compared to Bush's $8.3 million.
   Dukakis has received $7.7 million in all, and Jackson $4.2
million. Fulani has received less than $500,000.
   To be eligible for matching funds, a candidate must raise an
initial $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less.
Thereafter the FEC matches each contribution of $250 that
candidates raise privately.
   The matching fund is supported by the voluntary $1 checkoff on
individual income tax returns.
</TEXT>
