<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WheatProgram     05-25 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat Program,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acreage Idling Requirement to be Cut in 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat farmers will be required to idle only 10
percent of their base acreage for the 1989 harvest, compared with
27.5 percent for 1988, the Agriculture Department announced
Wednesday.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers also said the government's price
support loan rate for 1989 will be reduced to $2.06 per bushel from
$2.21 this year. The 1989 target price will be $4.10 per bushel,
down from $4.23 for the 1988 wheat crop.
   Farmers who wish to qualify for price supports and other program
benefits are required to go along with acreage set-aside, or
idling, requirements.
   The loan rate is how much a farmer can borrow from the USDA by
using the crop as collateral. If market prices are significantly
higher later on, the producer usually repays the loan and sells or
uses the commodity at will. If market prices are lower than the
loan rate, the producer has the option of forefeiting the grain to
USDA, thereby canceling the debt.
   Target prices are used to compute federal direct payments to
producers. When market prices are below the target, ``deficiency''
payments are made to make up the difference between the basic loan
rate or the average market price, whichever his higher.
   Myers said the reduction in the loan rate was necessary to
maintain U.S. wheat's competitiveness in domestic and international
markets.
   The reduction in the set-aside for 1989 reflects a draw-down in
U.S. wheat stockpiles and a decision to rebuild those inventories
in order to meet future export demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Trump     05-25 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Trump,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ivana Trump: Wife, Mother, Businesswoman _ and Now, U.S. Citizen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ivana Trump, wife of billionaire developer
Donald Trump, became a U.S. citizen Wednesday at federal court,
where she and other new citizens were told that America was
``vastly enriched'' by their presence.
   Mrs. Trump, 38, a former fashion model and current president of
the Plaza Hotel and Trump's Castle Hotel & Casino, stood with 141
other naturalized citizens.
   The presiding judge, Charles S. Haight Jr., welcomed them to the
``freedom to follow your dreams'' adding: ``by your presence,
America is vastly enriched.''
   Mrs. Trump, whose salary is $1 a year and all the dresses she
can buy, wore an off-white suit, cut above the knee, with a
blue-and-white striped blouse.
   She kissed her husband on the cheek and was embraced and kissed
by her friend, Jackie Miner, wife of U.S. Circuit Court Judge Roger
Miner.
   Miner, who sat next to Haight on the bench, gave a 10-minute
speech on the duties of new citizens. He did not mention Mrs. Trump
by name, but referred to ``a special friend'' who was being
naturalized.
   ``I'm very proud of my wife,'' a beaming Trump said outside the
courthouse. ``I'm very proud of my country. It's a great country
and that's where a great woman should be. Now they're both matched
up perfectly.''
   Mrs. Trump, an Austrian-born, former Czechoslovakian national,
came to this country 10 years ago after working as a model in
Montreal. She said she, too, was ``very proud.''
   After the crowd cleared out, the Trumps chatted in the courtroom
with the two judges before leaving with the Miners in a limousine.
</TEXT>
