<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Markets-Phelan     05-25 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Markets-Phelan,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Chief Ties Investor Uncertainty to Future Doubts, Not October
Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the New York Stock Exchange
said Wednesday that continuing market skittishness is due to
uncertainty over the future of the economy, not to lingering
aftershocks of the October market crash.
   ``I think the markets are really looking toward the future ...
and cannot make up their minds about it,'' John J. Phelan Jr. said.
``I think when they make up their minds, confidence will return.''
   Phelan, in a luncheon speech to Congressional Clearinghouse on
the Future, acknowledged that small investors have pulled out of
the market since the plunge of last October, but said, ``I think
they are behaving very prudently now, which is, in times of
uncertainty, do nothing.''
   Phelan said his own view of the economy's prospects was
somewhere between that of the pessismists who have predicted a
1930s style depression and optimists who assert the economy is
headed for a ``rolling correction,'' entailing little more than
somewhat higher interest rates and slower growth.
   ``Unless you believe in the tooth fairy, you don't believe the
business cycle has gone away,'' he said. ``There are the beginnings
of certain classic signs of the end of an economic expansion. ...
Unless something is very strange, the next 18 months to two years
are not going to be easy.''
   But looking toward the 1990s and beyond, Phelan said the future
looks bright.
   ``I'm 57 years old and the bears have always lost,'' he said.
   The clearinghouse is a bipartisan caucus of senators and
representatives concerned with long-range trends and issues of the
future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
