<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     05-25 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Leader Urges Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a political
coalition allied with leftist guerrillas said Wednesday the
government's refusal to resume negotiations on ending the
8-year-old war threatens a deeper crisis.
   ``This is a moment of life and death for the Salvadorans, for
the national economy and the social structure,'' Guillermo Manuel
Ungo said. He arrived Wednesday on only his second visit to El
Salvador since going into exile soon after the war began.
   Ungo, president of the Democratic Revolutionary Front, said he
would stay for about a week. He also returned for a week last
November.
   His coalition is allied with the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, the guerrilla alliance fighting the
U.S.-supported government.
   He criticized the rejection Tuesday of a May 11 rebel proposal
for renewed negotiations. President Jose Napoleon Duarte's
government said it was not an opportune moment for talks.
   In view of the nation's problems, Ungo declared, ``an opportune
moment comes every day.''
   A dispute over the results of March 20 elections left Duarte
without a legislature. The National Assembly has yet to be seated.
   Peace talks with the rebels broke down in October.
   The main purpose of Ungo's visit is to promote his political
party, the National Revolutionary Movement, and a coalition called
Democratic Convergence.
   Ungo's party formed the coalition last year with another member
party of the Democratic Revolutionary Front and the Social
Democrats, an officially recognized leftist party.
   He said the Democratic Convergence might run a candidate in next
year's presidential election.
   ``We don't rule out participation,'' he said. ``We will see what
role our growing presence and influence might play.''
   The guerrillas and their allies have boycotted elections in the
past.
</TEXT>
