<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Reagan     05-25 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reagan,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Says Reagan Coming in Interests of Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass adopted an upbeat pre-summit tone Wednesday,
quoting President Reagan as saying he was coming to the Soviet
Union in the interests of peace.
   The evening television news program Vremya carried a report from
a Washington correspondent on Reagan's visit and later showed
Reagan leaving for Helsinki, Finland, en route to Moscow.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, quoted Reagan's departure
statement that he intended to work in the interests of peace during
his visit to the Soviet capital next week.
   It quoted Reagan as saying measures to reduce tension between
the superpowers, capped by the signing of the agreement banning
medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles at the last summit in
Washington last December, were ``only a beginning.''
   The agency said Reagan pledged to work for an agreement to cut
U.S. and Soviet long-range missiles during his meetings with
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Moscow.
   It relegated Reagan's comments on the deep differences that
still divide the Soviet Union and the United States to the final
paragraph of its dispatch.
   A pair of later articles distributed by Tass were more critical.
   One was a commentary by military analyst Vladimir Bogachev. He
said the Reagan administration had backtracked on a pledge at the
Washington summit to observe the anti-ballistic missile treaty as
signed in 1972, rather than using Reagan's broad interpretation
that would allow more free development of the ``Star Wars'' program
for a space-based nuclear defense.
   ``Isn't it time that Washington began showing a more responsible
attitude to its commitments?'' Bogachev asked.
   In a separate story, Tass said a group of Soviet scientists
appealed to Reagan for more flexibility in allowing Soviets to
travel to the United States. It cited the cases of several
scientists who it said were denied visas.
   Tass quoted Viktor Karpov in another report as saying that
Reagan and Gorbachev could exchange in Moscow instruments of
ratification of the December agreement if the U.S. Senate ratifies
the treaty soon.
   Karpov, head of the Foreign Ministry's arms control department,
said Monday that the Soviet Union should not ratify the treaty
before the United States does.
   Senate majority leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said Wednesday
that the Senate should be prepared to take final action on the
treaty Friday or Saturday.
   ``There are no doubts that the Soviet Union will not delay that
historic act by taking too long to ratify the INF (intermediate
nuclear forces) treaty,'' Karpov said.
   The treaty must be approved by the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet, the country's top executive body.
</TEXT>
