<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0764 05-25 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0764,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says `Liberal Elite' Jeopardizing U.S. Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New grafs 2-3 with Bush on Noriega; INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th
graf pvs, bgng: ``But what,'' with more Bush comment on Noriega</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said Wednesday that a
``liberal elite'' is jeopardizing U.S. security by opposing every
new weapons system that would preserve a strong defense.
   He also expressed optimism that Panama's Gen. Manuel Noriega
could be induced to step aside, despite Secretary of State George
Shultz' announcement that negotiations aimed at achieving that had
failed, and no new talks were set.
   ``I'm convinced Noriega will be out of power,'' Bush told
reporters in Lakehurst, N.J.
   Speaking at a commencement ceremony at the U.S. Military
Academy, the vice president said of unnamed liberals, ``They are so
blinded by ideology that they cannot see what Americans have
understood for 40 years: that peace flows from strength.''
   The Republican presidential nominee-to-be did not say who he was
referring to, apparently in deference to a federal ban on political
activity on military installations. But it was clear he was talking
about Democrats Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson.
   ``I'm sure they'd claim it isn't so and they're all in favor of
a strong defense,'' Bush said. ``They look the part, sober and
measured in their gray suits, moving their hands on the Sunday talk
shows with just the right amount of gravity and earnestness.''
   ``But what are we to think, when they say they're for a strong
defense but they oppose every new weapons system that would
preserve that strength?'' Bush asked.
   Asked about Noriega, Bush told reporters in New Jersey, ``The
fact that we haven't solved this doesn't depress me.''
   ``I don't want a bad deal. I want a good deal,'' he said.
``We'll have to go back and figure it out.''
   Bush's aides said last week that the vice president had urged
that talks with Noriega be suspended. However, Bush said while he
and President Reagan had some differences on the matter, they both
had the same ``policy objective of getting Noriega out.''
   The vice president again denied that he had known of Noriega's
alleged drug-dealing before the Panamanian leader was indicted on
U.S. drug charges. He said he thought Noriega should be extradited
to the U.S. to face the chargs, but acknowledged that would be
``difficult'' in light of the lack of a U.S. extradition treaty
with Panama.
   At West Point, Bush delivered the speech under a small canopy on
the field of the academy's football stadium in a driving rainstorm,
then stayed to shake hands with each of the 939 graduating cadets
and watched as they hurled their caps aloft.
   Bush, who in the past has criticized both Dukakis and Jackson by
name for a lack of foreign policy experience, noted that Reagan
left Wednesday morning for the upcoming superpower summit in Moscow.
   Praising the ``five years of patient effort'' toward a nuclear
arms limitation treaty, Bush said the summit was no reason for
complacency toward the Soviets.
   ``We must be confident that those who will lead our country
understand what it means to stand up to a challenge and meet our
commitments,'' Bush said. ``We must be confident that they will
pursue negotiations with the Soviets realistically.''
   Bush aides had billed the speech as non-partisan. And the vice
president did praise former Democratic presidents Harry S. Truman
and John F. Kennedy.
   They, along with Republican president Dwight Eisenhower, were
part of a bipartisan consensus on dealing firmly with the Soviets
that Bush said lasted from the 1940s to the mid-1960s.
   ``There are some today who have abandoned those principles,'' he
said. ``The liberal elite do not understand _ they never understood
_ the common sense behind the consensus.''
   Later, addressing a group of senior citizens at a retirement
village in Lakehurst, N.J., Bush continued on the same defense
theme and said ``we've got to keep our eyes wide open'' while
negotiating with the Soviets.
   ``I am not naive aboutt Soviet intentions. We are on the right
track. We should not be afraid to talk. We should never talk from a
position of weakness,'' he said.
   Bush's campaign, meanwhile, acknowledged that chief spokesman
Peter Teeley was shifting to other duties.
   ``He's going to make a job switch,'' said campaign manager Lee
Atwater. He said Teeley would be ``a more creative type guy and
work specifically on the surrogate teams.''
   No reason was given for the change, but Teeley and Bush chief of
staff Craig Fuller were known to be at odds.
   On Thursday, after campaigning in the Newark area, Bush will fly
to his oceanside vacation retreat in Kennebunkport, Maine, where he
will spend the next week in a series of strategy and issues
sessions while Reagan is in Moscow.
</TEXT>
