<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NearCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0846-a0866 05-25 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Near Collision, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0846-a0866,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jetliners Report Near Collision Over Ocean</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs, CORRECTS spelling of spokesman's name in 9th
graf, bgng: ``Pan Am ...''; minor editing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jetliners carrying a total of 286 people
were assigned the same altitude and missed colliding head-on by 300
feet over the ocean north of Puerto Rico last Monday, officials
disclosed Wednesday.
   According to the officials, the pilots of the southbound Pan
American World Airways A-300 and the northbound American Airlines
Boeing 727 did not see each other until the planes were passing at
better than 500 miles an hour.
   Neither pilot had time to take evasive action, spokesmen for the
two airlines said.
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Fred Farrar confirmed
that both jetliners were assigned to 29,000 feet and were under the
control of the San Juan air traffic control center at the time of
the incident. That section of airspace is beyond FAA radar, so
separation is maintained by assigning specific altitudes.
   The incident ``is being investigated as a possible operational
error'' by air traffic controllers, Farrar said. He said he did not
know whether the controllers involved have been removed from
directing aircraft, normally the procedure after such an incident.
   The Pan Am plane was Flight 217 from New York to Caracas,
Venezuela and on to Trinidad and carried 131 passengers and 10
crewmembers. The northbound plane was American Flight 902 from San
Juan to Philadelphia with 138 passengers and seven crewmembers
aboard.
   The section of airspace about 550 miles north of Puerto Rico in
the so-called Bermuda Triangle is beyond FAA radar at both San Juan
and on the U.S. mainland.
   Commercial jets operate under oceanic flight rules and are still
under radio air traffic direction. They are assigned specific
altitudes to maintain proper separation.
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said the Pan Am pilot filed a
near-collision report with the FAA. The American jet's pilots also
filed a report, according to American spokesman John Hotard.
   Farrar said the FAA still was investigating who gave the planes
their altitude assignments.
   A source who asked not to be identified by name said the
incident occurred near where control of planes switches from the
FAA center in New York to the San Juan center and the handoff may
have resulted in an altitude mixup.
   Farrar said he could not confirm that.
   Farrar said the two jetliners had about 300 feet horizontal
separation as they passed. ``Both aircraft observed each other as
they passed,'' he said.
   Investigators for the National Transportation Safety Board flew
to San Juan on Wednesday to interview the controllers involved,
said NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz.
   ``We are investigating the incident. We're looking into it,''
Lopatkiewicz said. He said the investigators may later interview
the pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     05-25 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Senate Approves Anti-Nuclear Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators approved on second reading
Wednesday a bill that bans nuclear weapons on Philippine territory
but allows port calls by nuclear-powered ships.
   Orlando Mercado, majority floor leader, said the Senate is
expected to pass the bill next week on third reading, a formality
where the legislators register their votes.
   The bill prohibits manufacture or storage of nuclear weapons in
the country, but was amended to allow nuclear-powered vessels to
make port calls after they are inspected by Philippine authorities.
   The chief sponsor of the measure, Sen. Wigberto Tanada, is an
anti-nuclear activisit and opposes U.S. bases in the Philippines.
   Most senators hailed passage of the bill and said it would give
President Corazon Aquino's administration a stronger hand in
negotiating with U.S. officials on the future of Clark Air Base,
Subic Naval Base and four smaller U.S. military facilities here.
   Sen. Mamintal Tamano, who earlier expressed concern about the
bill's implications, said, ``This is a backdoor way of repudiating
the existing treaty between the U.S. and the Philippines and the
termination of the bases agreement.
   ``The Americans will be very uncomfortable with such a law,
which will render the bases ineffective.''
   Anti-nuclear activists have accused the Americans of using the
bases as storage or transit points for nuclear weapons. U.S.
authorities have refused to say yes or no.
   U.S. policy also is to remain silent on whether a Navy vessel is
carrying nuclear weapons.
   On April 5, U.S. and Filipino negotiators started a three-month
review of the 1947 agreement governing U.S. bases here. The
agreement expires in 1991.
   Tanada said his bill ``will strengthen the position of our panel
in their negotiations with the U.S.'' A colleague, Sen. Rene
Saguisag, said it gives Mrs. Aquino ``a credible option'' on the
bases issue.
   The president has said she would ``keep her options open'' until
1991.
   Sen. Aquilino Pimentel, an opponent of the bases, said the bill
``will send a very strong signal to the world that the Philippines
is an independent nation.''
</TEXT>
