<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FrommeSentencing     05-25 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fromme Sentencing,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fromme Receives Another 15 Months In Prison On Escape Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, serving a life
sentence for her 1975 assassination attempt on President Ford, was
ordered Wednesday to serve an additional 15 months for escaping
from a federal prison.
   The disciple of imprisoned mass murderer Charles Manson told
U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Hallanan during the sentencing
hearing that she had no remorse about her Dec. 23 escape.
   Another escape ``floats through my mind now and again,'' Fromme
said. ``I couldn't say I wouldn't try to escape again.''
   Federal attorneys said she would be transferred from the
minimum-security Federal Correctional Institution at Alderson,
W.Va., to another prison.
   The judge also fined Fromme $400.
   Fromme, 39, was sentenced to life in prison after she pointed a
gun at then-President Ford during a visit to California. She was
recaptured on Christmas Day, two days after her escape, about two
miles away from the Alderson prison.
   A U.S. District Court jury in March deliberated less than 10
minutes before finding her guilty of escape. She faced a maximum
additional sentence of five years and a $250,000 fine.
   Fromme acted as her own lawyer during the trial and told the
jury it didn't ``have any choice'' in finding her guilty.
   ``I'm guilty as charged, legally, and without remorse morally,
so that's that,'' she said in closing arguments.
   She testified that overcrowding was one of the reasons she tried
to escape.
</TEXT>
