<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     05-25 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Criticizes U.S. Policy In Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson loaded food and medical supplies destined for Central
America onto a truck Wednesday, urging a change in U.S. policy
toward the region.
   Jackson made an impassioned speech to some 300 people gathered
in a parking lot off Fisherman's Wharf, including some veterans who
sponsored the 3,000-mile ``Veterans Peace Convoy'' to Nicaragua.
   Jackson was in the state campaigning for California's June 7
primary, which Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis is favored
to win.
   ``The $10 billion spent chasing 3 million Sandinistas ...that
money should have been spent chasing poverty, illiteracy and
disease and building houses ... in Central America,'' said Jackson.
``It was immoral and illegal and a misappropriation of funds.''
   Jackson's 30-minute address focused on Central America, but he
also referred to the upcoming Reagan-Gorbachev summit in Moscow,
calling it a ``step in the right direction.''
   ``The American-Soviet future is not one of more threats, more
arms buildup, more insecurity in the name of security, weaponizing
the heavens and threatening to destroy the whole planet,'' said
Jackson.
   Jackson also urged the crowd to ``keep hope alive.''
   ``Twenty years ago this year, our dreams were lofty and our
hopes were high. And then Martin Luther King was killed April 4th
and then Robert Kennedy on June 5th,'' Jackson said. ``Our hopes
were dashed, our dreams were busted. We went through a crucifixion.
   ``But now 20 years later, we keep on dreaming. The stone has
been rolled away. Without a crucifixion in California, there's now
a resurrection. New hope, new life, new possibility. And we're
winning every day.''
   Jackson, citing his candidacy as evidence of progress in civil
rights, said ``If we can debate the direction of our nation at the
highest levels, we're winning every day.''
