<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hastings-Impeach 1stLd-Writethru a0759 05-25 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hastings-Impeach, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Witness Refuses To Testify at Hastings Impeachment Hearing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 5 grafs with later testimony</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington attorney convicted of arranging a
bribe for his close friend, federal judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Miami, refused to testify Wednesday before a House panel
considering Hastings' impeachment.
   Accompanied by two lawyers, William A. Borders invoked his Fifth
Amendment protection against self-incrimination and told the House
Judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice that he would ``refuse
to answer any and all questions'' about the case.
   Borders was convicted in 1982 of arranging a $150,000 bribe for
Hastings from two Miami racketeers, Frank and Tom Romano, in
exchange for a promise of lenient sentences. One year later, a
separate trial jury acquitted Hastings of conspiring with Borders
to solicit a bribe from the Romano brothers.
   Borders was fined $35,000, served 33 months in a federal prison
at Allenwood, Pa., and was disbarred by the District of Columbia
Court of Appeals.
   ``I believe that my legal debt to society expired on May 22,
1988, after my release from parole,'' Borders told the House
subcommittee that is investigating impeachment charges by a
judicial panel against Hastings.
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., who is presiding over the
televised hearings, deferred what he called the subcommittee's
``very difficult'' decision whether to grant Borders immunity from
prosecution to compel his testimony.
   Borders has remained silent about the alleged bribery conspiracy
since he was indicted in late 1981. He refused to testify at both
his and Hastings' trials, and never appeared before a special
investigative panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that
was appointed shortly after Hastings was acquitted.
   The judicial panel, after a 3{-year study, concluded there was
``clear and convincing evidence'' that Hastings not only had
engaged in a bribery schee but tried to conceal his role by lying
under oath and fabricating evidence at his trial.
   Hastings has insisted that he knew nothing of the bribery plot
and accuses Borders of trading on his name in an attempt to shake
down the Romanos. Hastings, who is Florida's first black federal
judge, says the case against him is racially and politically
motivated.
   After Borders was excused, Conyers led the subcommittee in close
and sometimes critical questioning of John Doar, chief counsel to
the five-judge appellate panel whose charges against Hastings
prompted the House impeachment proceedings.
   Conyers said it was ``amazing'' that FBI agents arrested Borders
after he had received $125,000 in bribery money from an undercover
agent posing as Frank Romano, but before Borders could have given
the money to someone else.
   Hastings was staying at a hotel five minutes away when Borders
was arrested Oct. 9, 1981, inside a car with the undercover agent
and a garment bag stuffed with $125,000 in cash.
   A few hours later, Hastings presumably would have met Borders at
an evening boating party which he and other friends were giving in
Borders' honor. But Hastings flew home to Miami shortly after he
learned of Borders' arrest.
   ``The FBI, in effect, broke up its own entrapment,'' Conyers
said. He said that seemed to suggest that ``they didn't believe
there was anyone else involved'' in a bribery scheme.
   Doar said he understood that the FBI ``was not prepared to let
the money get out of their control.'' In any event, he said, the
judicial panel believed there was plenty of other evidence
implicating Hastings in a bribery scheme.
   ``They did not need the money to arrive in Judge Hastings'
hands, no sir,'' Doar said.
   Doar agreed with Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., that the case
against Hastings would have been ``almost impregnable'' if Borders
had actually passed money to Hastings. Edwards said he felt it was
significant that the FBI did not wait to see if this happened.
   Conyers said it also was ``very important'' for his subcommittee
to determine why the Justice Department decided against bringing
perjury charges against Hastings before the statute of limitations
expired in his case in January 1987.
   Under questioning by Conyers, Doar conceded that William Dredge,
a Miami drug runner who tipped authorities to a possible bribery
scheme, could have made ``false and reckless charges against the
judge'' because of Dredge's known racial prejudice.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., asked Doar if ``there is any way you
think you could be wrong'' in contending that Hastings was involved
in a bribery conspiracy and an attempted cover-up.
   Doar, a former assistant U.S. attorney general who was special
counsel for House impeachment proceedings against President Nixon
in 1974, said, ``No there's not.''
   Later, U.S. District Judges William Terrell Hodges of Tampa,
Fla., and Anthony A. Alaimo of Brunswick, Ga., testified about
their decision to file a post-acquittal complaint against Hastings
that sparked the judicial panel's investigation.
   Hodges said their complaint was prompted partly by an appeals
court decision upholding Borders' conviction, which suggested
Hastings may have been involved in a conspiracy with Borders.
Hodges emphatically denied the complaint was filed because Hastings
is black.
   Hastings, allowed to cross-examine his fellow judges, said
``litigants will be the losers when collegiality is destroyed''
among federal judges who file charges against each other.
</TEXT>
