<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1934EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama-Analysis     05-25 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama-Analysis,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Says No, and the Administration Looks Powerless</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The breakdown in negotiations with Panama's
Manuel Antonio Noriega is the latest twist in a bizarre
confrontation that has left the United States seemingly powerless
to engineer the military chief's ouster.
   Instead of controlling events in Panama, U.S. policymakers seem
to be the victims of a wily military chief and of their own failure
to realize the strength of his grip on power.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz announced the collapse of
the negotiations on Wednesday. He said the United States would
continue efforts to get Noriega out of power, but he announced no
specific steps.
   What to do about Noriega has been a major preoccupation of the
Reagan administration since February, when he was indicted by a
federal grand jury in Miami on charges of taking at least $4.6
million in payoffs from Colombia's Medellin cartel to protect
cocaine shipments, launder money and hide drug smugglers from law
enforcement officials.
   It's not clear if officials ever thought they would actually be
able to bring Noriega to trial. If they did _ or if they thought
the indictment would lead to a withering of Noriega's power _ they
were mistaken.
   On Feb. 25, in what may have been a move suggested by the United
States, President Eric Arturo Delvalle announced Noriega's
dismissal. Then the Noriega-dominated National Assembly ousted
Delvalle and replaced him with Education Minister Manuel Solis
Palma.
   U.S. pressure began. The Reagan administration continued to
recognize Delvalle. Federal courts blocked the withdrawal of
Panamanian funds from American banks. Economic sanctions were
imposed. Washington gave verbal support to striking Panamanians and
deplored police actions against demonstrators.
   State Department officials whispered privately that Noriega
would be ``history'' in just a few days or weeks at most.
   On March 16, Noriega survived a coup attempt by dissident army
officers and the next day a state of emergency was declared, giving
soldiers power to patrol the capital.
   When pressure didn't work, the United States tried negotiations.
   The first offer, made March 18, was to allow Noriega to go to a
third country and to assure him he would not be extradited to the
United States on the drug charges. The offer was tempered two days
later, when Shultz said the indictments would not be dropped and
that Noriega would have no say in the formation of a transition
government.
   By early May, the situation appeared to be in a stalemate, as
Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Michael Kozak began a set of
secret negotiations with Noriega. The U.S. officials who had
predicted Noriega's imminent departure were no longer talking about
it.
   Kozak was reported to have reached a tentative agreement with
Noriega that would include his resignation as defense chief,
departure from the country in August, not to return until after May
1989 elections. The deal also would permit Noriega to have a hand
in forming a transition government.
   The offer divided the administration, because it included the
dismissal of the drug indictments against Noriega. Officials in the
Justice Department and the prosecutors who won the indictments
denounced the proposal.
   Vice President George Bush, who prides himself on his loyalty to
Reagan, had to confront questions every day on whether he supported
dropping the charges. Finally, he made his answer known: he said as
president, he would not negotiate with drug traffickers at home or
abroad.
   Shultz argued that the situation in Panama warranted the
dropping of charges against Noriega _ since he wouldn't allow
himself to be extradited anyway _ and the deal was set.
   In another demonstration of Noriega's power to control events,
Shultz delayed his departure for Helsinki on Wednesday, where he
was to join Reagan in preparatory sessions for next week's
superpower summit in Moscow.
   His wait was in vain. Noriega still said, ``No.''
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Hank Gottlieb covers the State Department for
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
