<DOCNO> AP880525-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO-Europeans     05-25 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Europeans,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Allies Rebut U.S. Criticisms Of Defense Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Europe-SDI, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European NATO members bristled at U.S.
complaints that they spend too little on defense and insisted on
Wednesday that they were carrying their weight in the alliance.
   They issued a joint rebuttal stressing their non-financial
contributions to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   ``Europe is taking a fair share of the burdens in the
alliance,'' said Wim van Eekelen, the Dutch defense minister and
chairman of Eurogroup, an informal bloc of 12 European countries.
   Van Eekelen and defense ministers of the other member countries
presented a detailed brochure explaining their current role in NATO.
   The report said that of NATO's standing forces, the United
States' allies provide 90 percent of the manpower and artillery, 80
percent of the tanks and combat aircraft and 65 percent of the
major warships.
   It said 3.5 million European men and women are on active duty
and another 3.5 million are in reserve. The United States has 2.3
million soldiers on active duty and 1.5 million in reserve, the
report said.
   Van Eekelen said he planned to address the issue on behalf of
the European NATO members Thursday at the regular spring meeting of
alliance defense ministers, including U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
C. Carlucci.
   The NATO meeting is expected to authorize an in-depth study of
how the allies share the burdens of Western defense and how they
can make better use of funds now available by cooperating more in
building arms.
   Van Eekelen told a news conference that while Washington was
justified in urging the allies to do more for the common defense of
the West, many members of Congress were wrong to say Europe is
shirking its duty.
   ``It's one of the perceptions that have grown steadily, but it
is not entirely warranted,'' van Eekelen said. ``It is important
that the true extent of the European contribution to the alliance
be properly understood.''
   He noted that the administration of President Reagan had taken a
less confrontational approach to the issue than some members of
Congress.
   The West German newspaper Die Welt on Wednesday quoted Reagan as
saying in an interview with European newspapers, ``I don't think
this is an area that should cause bad blood between us.''
   The Eurogroup report acknowledged that all the allies should try
to do more for the common defense, in part by better managing their
budgets.
   ``They recognize that a stronger European defense effort is
necessary in order to maintain the effectiveness of the alliance's
deterrent strategy and to satisfy legitimate American concerns over
burden sharing,'' the report said.
   Van Eekelen said that while U.S. defense spending has grown much
more rapidly than Europe's since Reagan took office in 1981, the
comparison looks much different if calculations are based on a
longer time span.
   Between 1970 and 1987, for example, the defense expenditures of
the European NATO members grew by 34 percent, compared with a 15
percent increase for the United States, the Eurogroup report said.
   Actual U.S. defense spending last year was 6.7 percent of the
U.S. gross national product, which is the broadest measure of
economic output. The equivalent figure for the Europeans was 3.3
percent.
   The Eurogroup report said comparisons of defense spending ``tell
only half the story'' of how the 16 NATO allies share the burdens
of their common defense.
   It said the money figures do not take account of such other
burdens born as environmental damage caused by NATO military
maneuvers. It also cited a sacrifice of income from European real
estate that is dedicated to military bases and other defense
facilities.
   In a related matter, van Eekelen said he expected Thursday's
NATO meeting to issue a formal request for Italy to accept the
basing of 72 U.S. F-16 fighter jets that Spain is forcing off its
territory. The main problem, he said, is deciding how the cost of
transferring the planes and 4,000 U.S. soldiers to Italy will be
shared in NATO.
</TEXT>
