<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OAU 1stLd-Writethru a0763 05-25 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OAU, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0763,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organization of African Unity Celebrates 25th Anniversary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 2nd graf pvs, President Kenneth ...
UPDATING with declaration. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Groups from .. .</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Organization of African Unity
marked its 25th anniversary Wednesday with calls to unite to crush
South African apartheid and to resolve Africa's $200 billion debt.
   President Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia, the outgoing OAU chairman,
celebrated the anniversary with a chorus of ``Happy Birthday,
OAU,'' as he cut a cake.
   The African states declared ``our determination to be master of
our own destiny'' in an 11-page declaration marking the jubilee.
The states called for total political and economical liberation of
the continent.
   Many of the 40 points in the declaration resembled previous OAU
resolutions. The declaration offers no new plans of action.
   It expressed disappointment at ``inadequate support'' provided
by the international community despite promises to provide money to
help Africa put austerity programs into effect.
   Groups from Sudan, Zambia, Guinea and Algeria danced and sang as
African leaders planted trees and unveiled a marble plaque with
gold engraving of the organization's silver jubilee theme: Unity,
Solidarity, Liberation, Development.
   A helicopter gunship roared overhead, but otherwise security was
light for the more than 30 heads of government and state gathered
at the 50-member body's headquarters in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia's
capital.
   In Zimbabwe, which won independence eight years ago and is the
OAU's youngest member state, the Harare Herald newspaper praised
the organization as having played a key role in ending colonial
domination, prescribing ways of resolving the African debt, and
promoting regional cooperation in transport, communications, health
programs and refugee care.
   Those attending the celebration in Ethiopia included Hosni
Mubarak, of Egypt, who wore a dark suit; Jerry Rawlings of Ghana,
in camouflage fatigues and dark glasses; Sadiq el-Mahdi of Sudan,
in flowing white robes and turban; and Maj. Gen. Ibrahim Babangida
of Nigeria, in khaki dress uniform emblazoned with red and gold
braid.
   Kaunda said that although 19 African nations had achieved
independence since the organization's founding May 25, 1963, the
OAU should resist complacency.
   ``Africa must rise to strike the last blow against the racist
regime of South Africa to rid the continent of the last bastion of
racism and colonialism,'' he said. ``We must therefore be even more
united than before.''
   The celebration is followed by a three-day summit that begins
Thursday.
   Denunciation of South Africa is a familiar theme at OAU
gatherings and summits, which always end with calls to crush
apartheid and with criticism of Western governments for failing to
impose mandatory sanctions on South Africa's white-dominated
government.
   The OAU also calls regularly for the freeing of Namibia, which
is under South African control.
   At the same time, black Africa does about $1 billion a year in
business with South Africa, much of it covertly.
   The state-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said in a
commentary that the OAU had failed to resolve the continent's major
problems.
   ``There will be much South Africa-bashing to cover up the lack
of unity, the social and economic crisis that plagues the continent
_ and the heart-rending suffering of the people of Africa,'' it
said of the gathering.
   OAU Secretary-general Ide Oumarou of Niger said Africa's
economic problems have weakened the organization's impact.
   ``The words of a united Africa would have been more resounding
if its political and diplomatic influence had been matched by its
economic power,'' he said.
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam of Ethiopia said the OAU could
count among its successes the rapprochement between Ethiopia and
Somalia, who restored diplomatic ties in April after an 11-year
break following the Ogaden desert war.
   The OAU was not directly involved in the Ethiopia-Somalia
rapprochement and has had limited success in mediation. Last year,
Kaunda persuaded members Chad and Libya to accept a cease-fire in
their territorial dispute after the United Nations failed to do so.
   President Hissene Habre of Chad attended the OAU's silver
jubilee, but Col. Moammar Gadhafi of Libya stayed away from the
meeting, as he has in recent years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Olympics-TV     05-25 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympics-TV,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Hoping For Lift With Winter Olympics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Longer version on sports wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS officials said Wednesday that getting the
television rights to the 1992 Winter Olympics was the first step in
rebuilding the beleaguered network and making it No. 1 again.
   ``It's going to be a hard fight, but we're ready for an all-out
assault,'' CBS President Laurence Tisch said.
   The longtime ratings leader among the three major networks
slipped to last place this season. But Tisch said the network's
winning $243 million bid Tuesday for the Winter Games in
Albertville, France, shows that CBS is determined to regain its
former status.
   ``We're on the right track _ we just have to get the train
moving faster,'' he said at a news conference.
   CBS, which last televised the Olympics in 1960, outbid NBC by
$68 million for the Albertville Games. CBS Sports president Neal
Pilson said he expected CBS to make a small profit on the Games,
but NBC Sports president Arthur Watson said Pilson was ``blowing
smoke.''
   Tisch, also chief executive officer of CBS, called the bid
``very realistic.''
   ``I think we can make money,'' he said. ``At worst, I see us
breaking even.''
   Gene Jankowski, president of the CBS Broadcast Group, said the
bid reflected CBS' ``new aggressiveness.''
   ``We are not the No. 1 network, but we intend to be,'' he said.
``We have promised our affiliates that we will go after the big
events, and that's what we're doing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
