<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0871 05-25 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0871,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Deal Collapsed Over Control of Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 6 grafs, more quotes from paper and fixes
translation of quote in 2nd graf; picks up 5th `When the'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper said Wednesday the army
rejected a U.S. proposal for Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to step
down because it did not guarantee his chosen president would remain
in power.
   ``The high command of the Defense Forces and the Strategic
Military Council rejected the points of conversation because they
found no guarantee of the continuity of the constitutional mandate
of President Manuel Solis Palma,'' said the pro-government La
Republica, citing sources it did not identify.
   The front-page story carried the headline ``There is No
Agreement.''
   It said the military believed ``there would be security risks,
political confrontations among Panamanians'' and that the U.S.
proposal would impede the process of turning over the Panama Canal.
Treaties signed in 1977 require the United States to relinquish
control of the canal on Dec. 31, 1999.
   The report in the afternoon paper said the military leaders felt
any further talks should be held ``in a broader parameter in which
other sectors of the Panamanian state might be included.''
   Secretary of State George Shultz announced Wednesday afternoon
in Washington that the talks had collapsed.
   When the negotiations on Noriega's removal began several weeks
ago, the United States insisted on retaining Eric Arturo Delvalle
as president. That position appeared to have softened recently.
   Delvalle was deposed by Noriega on Feb. 26, a day after the
president tried to fire Noriega. The United States continues to
recognize Delvalle's presidency.
   There was no immediate public comment from Noriega on the
failure of the talks. He is to address the Legislative Assembly on
Thursday, said an assembly spokesman.
   Noriega, the head of the 15,000-strong Defense Forces, is under
federal indictment in Florida for drug trafficking. Removal of the
indictments was reportedly part of the agreement that had been
considered.
   Other terms were said to be lifting U.S. economic sanctions,
Noriega's departure from Panama at least temporarily and agreement
on who should head the civilian government until May 1989 elections.
   Sources close to Romulo Escobar Betancourt, Noriega's chief
negotiator with the United States, told The Associated Press early
Wednesday that the two sides still had not reached agreement on
what would happen to $50 million in Panamanian funds frozen in
American banks and on the status of Solis Palma, whom Noriega
installed as president after deposing Delvalle.
   Hours later, Shultz announced that the talks were off.
   DelValle has been in hiding in Panama since he was deposed and
warrants are out for his arrest, although the Panamian government
has made no serious recent attempt to find him.
   The military has been the de facto ruler in this country of 2.2
million since 1968 when Gen. Omar Torrijos ousted Arnulfo Arias
Madrid.
   Panamanian-American relations have dropped in the past year to a
25-year low. The U.S. economic sanctions have taken a heavy toll on
Panama's economy.
   International confidence in Panama's banking industry has been
shaken and scores of businesses have gone bankrupt or are
struggling to stay open.
   The opposition press has been silenced since early this year.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, president of Panama's opposition
Christian Democratic Party, said recently it may take a generation
to restore Panama to what it was economically and socially before
the crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0257 </DOCNO>
