<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-US 1stLd-Writethru a0755 05-25 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0755,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves New Japan-U.S. Nuclear Cooperation Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RESTORES dropped time element in lede.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese Parliament on Wednesday approved a new
nuclear cooperation pact with the United States that the U.S.
Congress had accepted earlier.
   The 30-year agreement allows Japan to transfer spent nuclear
fuel from the United States to reprocessing plants in Britain and
France without seeking U.S. permission each time. It was required
to do so under a previous agreement.
   The new accord also limits cooperation to peaceful purposes and
allows Japan to bring in American-made nuclear materials, including
plutonium, which can be used to make nuclear weapons.
   During heated U.S. congressional debate on the pact in March,
Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, expressed concern about potential risks of
nuclear proliferation, terrorism and environmental damage.
   Yozo Hosokawa, an official at the Science and Technology Agency,
said the new pact will go into effect as early as fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
