<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0726 05-25 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Issues First Official Report on Soviet Casualties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf ``The war...'' with one graf to ADD non-combat
deaths in Vietnam</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union announced Wednesday for the first
time how many casualties it suffered in Afghanistan, with a Red
Army general telling a nationwide television audience that 13,310
soldiers died in the war.
   Gen. Alexei D. Lizichev also said 35,478 soldiers were wounded
and 311 are missing from the Soviet Union's 8{-year battle with
Moslem insurgents.
   Soviet soldiers began leaving their bases May 15 in accordance
with a peace accord signed in Geneva that aims to end foreign
involvement in the Afghan civil war and improve chances for
internal resolution of the 10-year-old conflict.
   The general said in a news briefing which was also carried on
the evening news program ``Vremya'' that the death and injury tolls
included casualties suffered between Dec. 27, 1979, when Soviet
troops and tanks entered the war, and May 1. The total of 49,099
dead, wounded and missing was slightly higher than some Western
analysts estimated.
   A U.S. State Department report last year estimated there had
been 33,000 to 38,000 casualties, about one-third of which were
deaths.
   Lizichev said the Soviet government would make every effort to
learn the fate of the missing soldiers, and indicated that there
would be no barriers to the return of those ``who fell into the
hands of the opposition or found themselves abroad.'' He appeared
to be referring to deserters as well as prisoners of war.
   Lizichev's casualty figures were in line with Soviet journalist
Eduard Rosental's statement May 19 that news reports estimating
deaths between 12,000 and 15,000 were ``more or less correct.''
   The war in Afghanistan often has been compared to U.S.
involvement in Vietnam, where about 58,000 Americans were killed
and about 150,000 were wounded.
   Since the withdrawal began 10 days ago, 9,500 Soviet troops have
left their bases, as well as 1,000 pieces of military equipment,
Lizichev reported.
   Asked whether the departing forces had suffered any casualties,
the general replied that there had been ``attempts to prevent them
from leaving,'' but that there had been no marked increase in rebel
attacks.
   He declined to verify the size of the Soviet contingent in
Afghanistan. But Western intelligence reports have indicated that
prior to the start of the withdrawal, about 115,000 Soviet soldiers
were in Afghanistan to back the government of President Najib
against anti-communist rebels.
   Lizichev and Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli M. Vorontsov held fast
to the Kremlin position that sending Soviet troops into a
neighboring country's civil war was justified.
   ``Soviet troops had been invited to Afghanistan by the
government,'' Vorontsov said. ``That is a fact. This cannot be
reassessed.''
   Lizichev was asked whether Soviet advisers would remain behind
after the withdrawal is completed, and replied that if the Afghans
appealed for such assistance, ``we would consider this request.''
   Najib told reporters in Kabul last month that his government was
counting on the continued help of Soviet advisers.
   Vorontsov was asked whether the retreat signaled an end to the
Brezhnev Doctrine, former leader Leonid I. Brezhnev's policy of
military intervention to protect socialist revolutionary gains.
   ``This was not our baby,'' Vorontsov said of the doctrine. But
he added that the Soviet armed forces are committed to protecting
allies as well as Soviet territory.
   Lizichev said Soviet policy has not changed, that conditions
appeared only recently that allowed the Kremlin to leave the Afghan
troops to fight on their own.
   Soviet officials and the state-run media have cast the pullout
as a successful conclusion to the war.
   The U.N.-mediated Geneva accords require all Soviet soldiers to
be out of Afghanistan within nine months, and half of the
contingent to withdraw by Aug. 15.
   Lt.-Gen. Boris Gromov, head of the Afghan-based troops, told
reporters in Kabul before the start of the withdrawal that 25
percent of the soldiers would leave before President Reagan's visit
to Moscow, which begins Sunday.
   Earlier Wednesday, the Afghan government charged for the fourth
time in recent days that Pakistan is violating provisions of the
peace accord that prohibit arms transfers to the anti-communist
rebels.
   Much of the weaponry supplied to the insurgents has come from
the United States, and Vorontsov joked that some of the
U.S.-supplied Stinger missiles provided to the rebels have been
captured by Soviet forces. After claiming that the insurgents were
selling the Stingers to other countries for as much as $300,000,
Vorontsov said the Kremlin had obtained some ``free of charge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabiesDead     05-25 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Babies Dead,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Investigated After Four Infants Die</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said she had ``had it up to my nose
with doctors and monitors with my children'' is under criminal
investigation after she had four children die before the age of 4
months, officials said Wednesday.
   A family court judge ruled that Bonnie Lambert and her husband,
Bruce, were guilty of ``at the very least, gross negligence'' and
issued a finding of abuse of their only surviving child, a
10-month-old boy who is currently in foster care.
   One of the children who died had previously been held at a
hospital because the city's Special Services for Children
department had received anonymous reports that the mother was
killing her children for insurance money to sustain her drug habit,
Judge Judith Sparrow said in her report.
   Brooklyn District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman confirmed
Wednesday she was investigating the three deaths that occurred in
her borough.
   ``The circumstances under which these infants died are under
investigation by my office. This matter is being taken very
seriously and is being investigated thoroughly,'' Holtzman said in
a statement.
   Sparrow called the parents' descriptions of how their children
died ``inconsistent and incredible'' in the May 2 decision, made
public Tuesday.
   The decision was in response to a petition by the city alleging
that the Lamberts abused their surviving child, Bruce Jr., through
reckless disregard for his care. No specific acts of physical abuse
were alleged. A hearing to determine the child's future is
scheduled for Friday.
   A call to the Lamberts' attorney, Jeffrey Karan, was not
returned Wednesday.
   Sparrow's decision outlined the deaths of the four infants. The
report, based on the Lamberts' testimony, medical and social
workers' accounts and other records, said:
   _Kristen, the couple's first child, died in August 1983 five
weeks after birth in Monticello, N.Y., of apparent natural causes.
The medical examiner's report said the baby died of cardiac arrest
and pneumonia.
   _A daughter, Heather, was hospitalized three weeks after birth
in June 1985 for an apnea disorder, described as a tendency to stop
breathing without cause. She died in July at age 5 weeks, just 1{
days after being released from the hospital.
   The judge said Maimonides Hospital gave the Lamberts a monitor
to record Heather's breathing and heart rate. The parents testified
they used the monitor but ``aspects of their description ... lacked
veracity,'' Sparrow wrote.
   Heather's cause of death was given as sudden infant death
syndrome, but no autopsy was performed because the parents opposed
it.
   _A third daughter, Erin, was diagnosed as having drug withdrawal
symptoms shortly after birth Oct. 10, 1986, and doctors recommended
that she be monitored for the apnea disorder. She died Feb. 9, 1987.
   Mrs. Lambert admitted she missed Erin's follow-up medical
appointments and told the judge she ``had it up to my nose with
doctors and monitors with my children,'' the judge's decision said.
Erin's cause of death was listed as SIDS but later changed to
``sudden unexplained death, circumstances undetermined.''
   _The last infant to die was Jason, the twin of surviving Bruce
Jr. Sparrow said the twins were kept at a hospital after the
children's services department received the anonmymous reports that
the mother had killed the children to collect insurance money.
   The department had previously received such reports, the judge's
decision said. A social worker was assigned to the family after the
third death and had been in contact with the parents.
   The allegations of abuse were evidently not confirmed, and the
twins were released to the parents, authorities said. Jason died
last October, with the cause of death listed as SIDS. Bruce Jr. was
then placed in foster care.
   The twins had infrequent bouts of apnea during their hospital
stay, but a doctor who handled the case said Mrs. Lambert told him
she did not plan to use monitors with them, Sparrow said.
   The physician, Dr. Sheela Laungani, told the judge it was
extremely rare for there to be multiple deaths in one family from
SIDS.
   The child's maternal grandparents have requested custody of the
child, said Lenore Gittis of the Legal Aid Society's juvenile
rights division.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
