<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-25 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Triggers Rain on East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front stretching from New England into the Southeast
Wednesday carried rain along the East Coast from Maine to the
Florida Keys.
   Scattered thunderstorms also rumbled over the Texas Panhandle
and into New Mexico, central Colorado and northeast Utah.
   In Florida, heavy storms doused the Keys, with wind gusts of 65
mph clocked at Marathon. Cudjoe Key reported gusts of 57 mph and
Boca Chica, 50 mph. Homestead, just south of Miami, got 1.53 inches
in the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Rain spread from central New England through the Middle Atlantic
States, with many locales reporting between a quarter and half-inch
of rain falling during the morning. Brunswick and Portland, Maine;
Hartford, Conn.; Concord, N.H., and Willow Grove, Pa., all received
more than a half-inch of rain in a six-hour period.
   Overnight frost warnings were issued for western Pennsylvania
and western New York.
   Elsewhere, skies were partly cloudy across the Great Lakes and
the Pacific Northwest. It was mostly sunny over the Southwestern
states.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 98 at Needles, Calif., and Phoenix,
Ariz. The morning low for the nation was 21 degrees at South Lake
Tahoe, Calif.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across
central and southern Florida, with the heaviest rain across the
southern third of the state. More widely scattered showers were
predicted over the northern Pacific Coast and the northern high
Plains of Montana and over the central Rockies into the northern
Plains. Sunny skies should prevail elsewhere.
   High temperatures should be in the 70s or 80s across much of the
nation, dipping into the 60s along the central and northern Pacific
Coast, and from the lower Great Lakes and Ohio Valley through the
Middle Atlantic states into New England. In the Southwest, highs
should read from the middle 90s to 105 in desert regions.
</TEXT>
