<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Chad     05-25 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Chad,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Says Libya's War with Chad Is Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi on Wednesday declared an end to
Libya's war with Chad and said he now recognizes the Chadian
government, Libyan television reported.
   The Libyan leader also said that Chadian prisoners will be
handed over to the Organization of African Unity and that Libya
will resolve all its problems with Chad in a ``friendly and
fraternal way.''
   He made his remarks to African ambassadors in Tripoli, the
Libyan capital, in a speech marking the 25th anniversary of the
OAU. The address was broadcast by Libyan television and monitored
in London.
   Gadhafi has declared the Chad war over before, most recently in
September 1987.
   He said he was making his Wednesday declaration so the 50-nation
OAU _ which has been trying to resolve the Libya-Chad dispute for
12 years _ could concentrate on solving Africa's economic problems,
confronting racism in South Africa, supporting the Palestinians,
and other issues.
   A spokesman for Chad's delegation at the OAU meeting in Addis
Ababa, Ethiopia, said Wednesday night that President Hissene Habre
of Chad could not be reached for comment because of the late hour.
   However, the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
noted that Habre said Tuesday he was ``very optimistic'' about the
possibility of resolving the dispute with Libya.
   Gadhafi also used the occasion to declare unilaterally that
Libya will resume ties with eight African countries _ Kenya,
Liberia, Zaire, Mauritius, Gabon, Senegal, Gambia and Ivory Coast.
   ``We want this day to be a day of joy for Africa and a reduction
in the burden of the organization so that it may devote itself to
the historic objectives for which it was set up: the unity of
Africa and the liberation of Africa,'' Gadhafi said.
   ``In order to salute and express appreciation for this day, the
day of Africa, the leadership of the (Libyan) revolution wants to
declare the following as a present to Africa on the 25th
anniversary. Libya declares its recognition of Chad and ends all
the outstanding problems between it and Chad.''
   Chad and Libya declared a cease-fire last September, but Chad
has accused Libya of continuing to mass troops for an attack. Libya
entered Chad in 1983 in support of rebels led by former Chadian
President Goukouni Queddei. France, the one-time colonial ruler of
Chad, gave military support to Habre, who ousted Goukouni in June
1982.
   Habre's forces pushed Libyan troops out of Chad early last year,
but Chad and Libya continued to dispute the mineral-rich Aouzou
Strip on Chad's extreme northern border. An OAU committe was set up
to examine the issue.
   Gadhafi invited Goukouni and Habre to met in Libya and said
``Libya will do its utmost for the sake of national reconciliation
between them.''
   He said that if Chad does return to civil war, ``Libya announces
that it will not intervene.''
   Gadhafi said Libya was offering what he described as a Libyan
``Marshall Plan'' to reconstruct northern Chad.
   The Marshall Plan was set up by the United States to aid in
European recovery after World War II.
   Gadhafi also said that that under the Libyan Constitution the
country did not to have a head of state and so his absence at the
OAU meeting should not offend that organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
