<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoodPlea     05-25 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Plea,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Pleads For Work With Young Daughters</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two honey-haired young girls brought
traffic to a crawl and tears to the eyes of motorists reading their
sign ``Will Work For Food.''
   Michelle Cannon, 8, and her sister Shirley, 6, were holding the
sign Tuesday for their father, who moved his family from
Philadelphia earlier this month and spent their $1,500 savings in
the process.
   The sight of the blue-eyed girls and their cardboard sign
inspired an outpouring of $20 bills and sympathy.
   ``I saw those two kids there and I just started crying,'' said
Hallandale postal worker Alicia McLoughlin, 36, who gave the
children's father, Bill Cannon, $3 in coins. ``It was all I had,''
she said, before returning 30 minutes later to give him two $20
bills.
   In two hours, Cannon collected $135 and the promise of a day's
work Saturday for $100.
   Even police contributed, but the officer who pushed $5 into
Cannon's hand refused to be identified.
   State social workers were not touched. They told Cannon his
children should have been in school where they have been registered.
   ``You're doing a dangerous thing, having these kids out here,''
said social worker Brenda Miller. ``You shouldn't be playing upon
the emotions of people with these kids.''
   Cannon said he would not use the girls to seek work again.
   ``I just want to get on my feet,'' he said.
   Cannon, his wife Bonnie, 27, Shirley, Michelle, sister Samantha,
5, and brother Jesse, 16, have been living in a $150-a-week
Hollywood hotel since their 1964 truck broke down there. Earlier
breakdowns cost the family its savings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
