<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Noriega-Miami     05-25 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Miami,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys Say Noriega Talks Could Resume</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega says he
isn't convinced talks are off between the indicted Panamanian
leader and U.S. officials, despite Secretary of State George
Shultz's statement to that effect Wednesday.
   ``I've heard that only from the secretary of state, and I
remember hearing the secretary of state say that last March,'' Neal
Sonnett said after the Shultz announcement.
   ``That was followed by more negotiations over the last 10 days,
so I don't think it would be useful to comment on whether the
negotiations are at a permanent end or not,'' said Sonnett, one of
several Miami attorneys for Noriega, who faces drug indictments in
Miami and Tampa.
   The federal prosecutors who brought those indictments last
February remain eager to meet him him in court rather than have
charges dropped in a poltical deal in which Noriega would give up
power.
   ``I stand ready to prosecute Mr. Noriega,'' said Robert Merkle,
U.S. attorney in Tampa.
   However, getting the defendant to Florida to stand trial won't
be easy because Noriega cannot be extradited by the United States.
   ``I offered him a trip to Disney World, but I don't think he'll
take me up on that,'' Merkle said.
   Merkle's successful prosecution of Colombian drug kingpin Carlos
Lehder Rivas took place after Lehder was captured in a Colombian
jungle and immediately flown to Tampa.
   Noriega is charged in a 12-count indictment in Miami with taking
at least $4.6 million in payoffs from the violent Medellin drug
cartel led by Lehder and others.
   The three-count Tampa indictment accused Noriega of helping
smuggle 1 million pounds of marijuana.
   Both Merkle and Leon Kellner, U.S. attorney in Miami, were
opposed to dropping their drug charges against Noriega in exchange
for his giving up power in Panama.
   ``All I can say is we are prepared to go forward with the case
and we will do so,'' Kellner said, declining further comment.
   But Sonnett said he thought charges against his client could
well be dismissed _ and not necessarily as a result of negotiations.
   ``I have continued to work on our motion for dismissal of the
indictment on legal grounds and we will continue to do so,'' he
said. ``We still feel that we have a strong case for dismissal on a
variety on various grounds.''
</TEXT>
