<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     05-25 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senior Official Denies Anti-Americanism is Widespread</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-American sentiment expressed by
radical South Korea students is ``not shared by the mainstream,'' a
senior government official said Wednesday.
   An influential newspaper on Wednesday meanwhile accused the
United States of meddling in South Korean affairs, but opposed
calls for expulsion of U.S. troops.
   Hyun Hong-choo, minister of legislation, said: ``We are
confident the majority of the people are happy with our relations
with the United States.''
   He was commenting at a lunch with the press about a wave of
anti-government and anti-American demonstrations in South Korean
cities in the past week.
   Referring to calls by some radicals for the U.S. Army to
relinquish its operational control of the South Korean army, Hyun
said the government ``feels there should be changes as time
progreses and situations change.''
   The United States has 42,000 troops based in South Korea under a
mutual defense pact. A U.S. general heads the combined military
forces.
   The newspaper Chosun Ilbo said in an editorial that South
Koreans resent ``U.S. interference in domestic politics and economy
in a high-handed manner, its support for dictatorship and coercive
demands to open Korean markets.''
   Radicals contend the United States has supported military rule
in South Korea and encourages the continued division of the Korean
peninsula. The peninsula was divided in 1945 into communist North
Korea and pro-Western South Korea.
   ``The recent anti-U.S. criticism apparently indicates students
and dissidents are mounting a major anti-U.S. campaign aimed at the
removal of U.S. troops,'' Chosun Ilbo said.
   But the newspaper backed the presence of the American troops. It
called on Koreans to maintain critical but balanced views of the
United States instead of blind opposition.
   The editorial's criticism of the United States was quite unusual
for the South Korean press.
   Student protesters claim South Korea is not a democracy, as they
did during the authoritarian regime of President Roh Tae-woo's
predecessor and ally, Chun Doo-hwan.
   Roh was elected last December in South Korea's first direct
elections in 16 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
