<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FloridaGunControl     05-25 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida Gun Control,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislator Charges NRA's Power Gutted Seven-Day Waiting Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) The lawmaker proposing a statewide
cooling-off period for handgun sales Wednesday withdrew a version
of his bill weakened by legislators he accused of knuckling under
to the National Rifle Association.
   ``I cannot personally allow the bill in its current posture to
come out with my name on it,'' said Rep. Ron Silver, a Democrat
from North Miami Beach.
   ``The National Rifle Association is a very powerful, financially
secure organization and the Legislature is responding more to the
National Rifle Association than to the people of Florida.''
   Silver distributed a memo to the other 119 House members
decrying a Tuesday vote that reduced his proposed weeklong waiting
period to three working days at the option of each county. The
proposed constitutional amendment would have been put to voters in
a November referendum.
   State law already allows counties to enact waiting periods of up
to two days.
   A lobbyist for the NRA dismissed Silver's claims that the
association was improperly influencing lawmakers.
   ``He knows that's not true,'' said Marion Hammer, director of
the Unified Sportsmen of Florida, the NRA's Florida arm. ``There's
no hue and cry out there for waiting periods. ... He only wants to
let the people decide if he can pick the question. Who's fooling
who?''
   Silver said he will mount a petition drive to place the
seven-day question on the ballot anyway, which will require him to
collect several hundred thousand signatures of registered voters
across the state by August.
   If that drive succeeds and voters adopt the constitutional
amendment, Silver said he would push separate legislation to
require gun buyers to sign their intent to purchase weapons. The
current 48-hour waiting period, which several counties have
enacted, has been faulted because it doesn't require written intent
to purchase a weapon.
   Rep. Ron Johnson, who sponsored the amendment to weaken Silver's
proposal as well as last year's controversial law that made it
easier for Floridians to carry concealed weapons, responded to
Silver's memo by telling his colleague, ``I find it personally
offensive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
