<DOCNO> AP880525-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     05-25 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Walking Point: A Vietnam Voyage,' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Bird was 19 years old when he first saw
Vietnam in 1965.
   ``This is paradise,'' he remembers saying as he looked down from
an airplane at a pristine beach. ``There can't be a war here.''
   Some 23 years later, the image of that paradise still haunts
him. So do images of the Vietnam War, a conflict he experienced
first hand as a member of the battered First Cavalry Division.
   In ``Walking Point: A Vietnam Voyage,'' now on view at
off-Broadway's Samuel Beckett Theater, Bird tries to reconcile the
two memories. His reconciliation forms the core of ``Walking
Point,'' a harrowing yet hopeful tale of Vietnam that eloquently
tries to explain the hold this strange, wonderous country had _ and
still has _ over the American servicemen who fought there.
   In ``Walking Point,'' Bird, founder and artistic director of the
Vietnam Veterans Ensemble Theater Company, sits alone on stage and
talks for some 80 minutes about his visits to Southeast Asia. In
the fervent, almost monotone voice of a true believer, he tells the
audience about three trips he made to Vietnam after the war ended.
   Bird's postwar journeys, including one he made with performance
artist and clown Bill Irwin, become vivid travelogues. He describes
a calm, strangely tranquil Vietnam, no longer divided into North
and South. There's a visit to a water puppet show in Hanoi, a
magical, almost mystical experience that suddenly brings back
horrific memories of the war. And there are profiles of various
guides and interpreters, men who a few years before were part of
the enemy.
   The juxtaposition of past and present never is far from the
surface in any of Bird's stories. They overlap when Bird travels
south to Saigon _ he can't bring himself to call it Ho Chi Minh
City _ to visit places he saw during the war.
   He finds the city alive and vibrant, full of reminders of an
American presence that left abruptly more than a decade ago. There
are the fading signs in English proclaiming U.S. military
installations. There is the burned hulk of an American tank that
sets Bird wondering about who were the soldiers who died in its
wreckage. And there are the Amerasian children, the questioning
faces of the young who bear the unmistakable imprint of America.
   What finally makes the evening such a moving and unsettling
experience is Bird's extraordinary feeling for Vietnam. It embodies
love, hate and just about every emotion in between.
   But ``Walking Point'' never sinks into despair, even though
Bird's story is melancholy and, at times, painfully sad. Maybe
that's because its author won't give up. He's a determined
storyteller who won't stop talking until he understands why it all
happened and what have been consequences of America's attempt to
save Vietnam from communism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The Wonder Years,'' now playing at off-Broadway's Village
Gate, may be the first musical built entirely on name and product
recognition.
   Virtually every pop icon and every fad from the 1950s and '60s
are mentioned in this mild little revue that examines the baby boom
generation from birth to the year 2018, the 50th anniversary of
Woodstock. They are all here _ from Lucy Riccardo to Mr. _ and Dr.
_ Spock; from hula hoops to the Watusi; from Wally Cleaver to
Polaroid Swingers.
   The music and lyrics by David Levy are as unsurprising as the
cast which is headed by the always cheerful Lenny Wolpe. He plays
an irritating character named Skippy, billed as the first baby-boom
baby, born one minute after midnight on Jan. 1, 1946.
   At least Wolpe is enthusiastic. But ``The Wonder Years'' is as
bland as the white bread it celebrates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
