<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UNESCO     05-25 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UNESCO,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director Presents Plan Calling For Drastic Cuts, Cost-Saving
Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNESCO chief Federico Mayor on Wednesday proposed
slashing programs and reining in spending to woo back the United
States and other ex-members, but ran into opposition from Soviet
bloc and Third World nations.
   The director-general said the 158-nation organization faced
``new challenges that required fresh solutions'' and called for
reduction of UNESCO's 16 major programs to five and of its 60
general programs to 16.
   Mayor's plan, officially called a sketch to indicate that it
could be considerably modified, proposed austerity measures aimed
at saving $8 million. It called for shorter conferences, reduced
travel and controls on document production.
   The Paris-based United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization should do fewer things but do them better
``with fewer activities and more follow-up,'' Mayor said, adding
that the agency had to be ``more visible in order to be more
credible.''
   Mayor, elected to head UNESCO in November, outlined the
preliminary plan to members of the 51-nation Executive Board at the
start their three-week-long spring meeting.
   On Monday the Spanish scientist said he was asking the United
States, Britain and Singapore to rejoin UNESCO.
   The United States and Britain, which paid 30 percent of UNESCO's
budget, pulled out in 1984 and 1985 to protest the organization's
alleged anti-Western bias and squandering of resources. The UNESCO
budget was $289.3 million for 1986-87.
   Mayor had described his proposals as ``provocative'' and likely
to stimulate a major debate at UNESCO.
   In fact, some members found them so disturbing that the agenda
was changed at the last minute so that Mayor could present his plan
at the opening session instead of Monday of next week as scheduled.
   The Group of 77 Third World countries circulated a paper sharply
critical of the plan, which they said treated them as ``objects for
whose benefits activities have been proposed rather than as actors
and equal partners.''
   It said the proposals do not reflect the wishes of the member
states and should be re-drafted and presented at the board's 1989
spring meeting.
   Another indication of the tough sledding Mayor's plan will face
came from Indian delegate Swaran Singh.
   He said the document contained contradictions and that it dealt
in terms of concepts and not real problems and played down the role
of governments.
   Singh called for restoration of one of the dropped programs that
deals with peace and development, and the struggle for human rights
and against discrimination.
   Polish delegate Kazimiierz Zygulski said there was an
``obsession with change and efficiency'' in Mayor's proposals. ``We
can't be just a pragmatic organization, we have to have specific
goals,'' he said.
   In opening the meeting, Board President Jose Israel Vargas of
Brazil praised the ``orginality, freshness and broadness of view''
in Mayor's proposals.
   Mayor said the agency should concentrate on five major areas:
education, natural science, culture, communications and social
science.
   He has promised to consult intellectuals, artists, scientists,
educators and journalists before preparing a final version of the
plan.
   During his presentation, Mayor made no reference to UNESCO's
controversial plan to establish a new world information and
communication order, which has been sharply criticized by Western
governments and news media organizations.
   In speeches to media professionals last week in Rome and
Istanbul, Turkey, Mayor said he favored a ``new phase'' at UNESCO
that would allow a ``free and uninhibited flow of information.''
</TEXT>
