<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SmokingBan     05-25 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking Ban,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago City Council Approves Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aldermen in the nation's third-largest city
approved an ordinance Wednesday that sponsors said would bar
smoking in most public areas and force restaurant owners and
employers to set aside smoking sections.
   New York and Los Angeles, the first and second-largest cities,
already have smoking restrictions.
   ``Those of you who want to die _ do it yourselves,'' declared
Anna Langford, one of 33 City Council members who voted for the
ordinance. Eight voted against it.
   ``Law enforcement officials would be better placed trying to
chase criminals than smokers,'' said Alderman Edward Burke in
speaking against the ordinance, whose quick passage surprised even
some supporters.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer, a smoker, favors the ban, said aide Monroe
Anderson.
   ``We thought the vote was going to be closer, and he was
prepared to break the tie and vote for it. The mayor smokes, but he
has cut back dramatically. He never smokes in public,'' Anderson
said.
   The ordinance bans smoking entirely in enclosed public areas
like meeting rooms and taxicabs and requires restaurants with 40
seats or more to set aside smoking and non-smoking areas, said
Alderman Raymond Figueroa, the ordinance's main sponsor. He said
the amount of designated restaurant space would be based on the
percentage of smoking and non-smoking clientele.
   Bars and private meeting rooms would be exempt from the ban.
   In addition, Figueroa said, employers must designate smoking and
no-smoking areas if workers request them. No-smoking signs must be
posted in all designated areas, he said.
   The ordinance, which takes effect in 60 days, carries fines
ranging from $25 to $100.
   ``Chicago has to line up with the rest of the major cities. We
have been lagging,'' Figueroa said.
   A state House committee blocked legislation in late April to
restrict smoking in most public places in Illinois, even though the
proposal had been watered down to appease business groups. Similar
legislation has been introduced annually in recent years without
success.
   Los Angeles' smoking ban, the city's fifth anti-smoking
legislation since 1964, went into effect in January. It bans
smoking in indoor sports arenas, concert halls, stores not
specializing in tobacco products, transportation terminals, day
care centers and most private schools. Restaurants seating more
than 50 would be required to reserve more than half their seats for
non-smokers.
   New York's anti-smoking law, one of the toughest in the nation,
went into effect last month. Although small establishments are
exempt, the bill forbids smoking inside sports arenas, theaters,
banks, hospitals and taxis. It limits smoking in offices,
restaurants and hotel lobbies. Smoking has been limited in all city
buildings since June 1986.
   When the New York legislation passed, health officials said
about 150 cities had enacted some kind of smoking restriction
legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
