<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0949 05-25 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0949,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Round of Peace Talks to Begin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with arrival of part of Contra
delegation. Pickup 15th graf pvs ``In Washington...''; EDITS
thereafter to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the U.S.-backed Contra
rebels arrived in Managua late Wednesday for a new round of talks
with the leftist government on reaching a permanent cease-fire in
the 6-year-old war.
   The negotiations were expected to begin Thursday.
   One group of negotiators for the rebels, known as Contras,
arrived in Managua from the Costa Rican capital of San Jose.
   ``We come with great political will so that a permanent solution
will be arrived at to (resolve) the situation in Nicaragua,''
Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros told the Sandinista government's
Voice of Nicaragua radio station.
   A few hours later, Col. Enrique Bermudez, the rebel military
leader, arrived on a private plane from the Honduran capital of
Tegucigalpa. He was accompanied by Alfredo Cesar, head of the rebel
delegation, and other Contra officials.
   The two dozen rebel delegates went immediately to the Camino
Real Hotel near the international airport on the outskirts of the
capital.
   Matamoros said the first known visit of Bermudez to Managua
during the war underlines the Contras' ``political will to search
for a Nicaraguan solution to the war.''
   Contra leaders initially refused to return to the capital,
complaining that their movements were restricted in two previous
sessions this year.
   Roberto Ferrey, secretary of the Nicaraguan Resistance, said
representatives of the Contra umbrella organization were going to
Managua ``with the understanding that there will be complete and
unrestricted freedom of expression and the free right to meet with
organizations and leaders.''
   He spoke by telephone with The Associated Press from San Jose.
   The government said Tuesday it would allow the rebels to meet
with the most important opposition group in the country, the
Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate, and to visit the Roman Catholic
bishops' conference, the opposition daily La Prensa and relatives.
   President Daniel Ortega rejected Contra demands the talks take
place in the border post of Sapoa, where the two sides agreed to
the 60-day truce scheduled to expire May 30.
   In Washington, Wilson Morris, an aide to House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, said the rebels planned to offer to lay down their
arms on Sept. 1.
   Ortega said on Monday he was unilaterally extending the
temporary truce for an additional 30 days.
   Rebel leaders have rejected extensions of the truce, but members
of the political directorate said in Washington they would not
break the truce even after May 30.
   A major obstacle to agreement has been the issue of delivery of
non-lethal aid to the rebels gathered in cease-fire zones inside
Nicaragua.
   Under the Sapoa agreement, the aid was to come through a neutral
international organization. Contras insisted in the talks that they
had the right to choose the organization.
   Contra leaders were quoted as saying they would accept a
proposal for delivery of humanitarian aid to their forces inside
Nicaragua by an agency with ties to the Organization of American
States.
   Cesar said in Washington that the rebels would propose a
timetable for political changes that include a free and fair
electoral system, an independent judiciary with the power to
guarantee human rights, removal of the military from Sandinista
party control, and guaranteed property rights.
   The pro-government newspaper Nuevo Diario said Wednesday the
government sent the National Assembly a bill providing for direct
elections of city councils in Nicaraguan municipalities, includng
Managua, late this year or early next year.
   Mayors, who now are named by the executive branch, would be
chosen from the city councils, it said.
   Maria Elena Martinez, an assembly spokeswoman, said the bill was
not yet available to the news media.
   The constitution provides for election of municipal governments
through ``direct, free and secret'' balloting.
   Ortega says the war has killed 26,500 people and caused $3
billion in damage to the economy.
</TEXT>
