<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Marcos 2ndLd-Writethru a0943 05-25 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0943,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Consul Says Marcos Faking Chest Pains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with tests ruling out heart
attack. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``Marcos began...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical tests showed former Philippines
President Ferdinand Marcos did not suffer a heart attack, and the
Philippine consul Wednesday accused the hospitalized Marcos of
faking chest pains to gain sympathy in his homeland.
   ``I think these are charades, these chest pains are not
substantiated medically,'' Tomas Gomez, the consul here, said. ``We
are faced with a master manipulator.''
   Marcos' physician, Dr. Derek Pang, ruled out a heart attack as
the cause of the discomfort and ordered Marcos to undergo tests
Thursday for a possible lung ailment, said Marcos spokesman Gemmo
Trinidad.
   ``He's in high spirits, but will have to have additional tests
to determine the cause of the pain,'' Trinidad said.
   Marcos, 70, was listed in guarded condition Wednesday in the
intensive care unit after being admitted Tuesday night, St. Francis
Medical Center spokeswoman Cheryl Yoshina said.
   Marcos began suffering chest pains Tuesday before an hour-long
interview with Allen Neuharth, chairman of the Gannett newspaper
group, according to Arturo Aruiza, Marcos' chief spokesman. After
consulting his personal physician, Dr. Derek Pang, Marcos was
admitted to the hospital, Aruiza said.
   Marcos admitted during the interview that his health was poor, a
rare statement for the former president who has often denied
earlier reports of ill health.
   Gomez said Marcos' hospitalization was a ploy to gain support in
the Philippines for his bid to return home.
   ``He went to the hospital voluntarily, under his own steam,''
Gomez said. ``We know what he's up to.''
   The hospital would release no specific information about Marcos'
condition except that he would be hospitalized at least until
Thursday.
   Gomez would not speculate on whether Marcos would be allowed to
return to the Philippines, but, in Manila, several politicians said
he should be allowed to come home.
   ``This is going to create another problem if (Marcos) comes home
in a box,'' said Sen. Ernesto Maceda. ``Now is the time for the
government to act and allow him to return.''
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino has refused to allow Marcos
to return for the funeral of his mother, who died May 4 and awaits
burial. Aquino said Marcos poses a threat to national security.
   The hospital's intensive care unit section was guarded closely
by Marcos security guards, who also manned every entrance to the
hospital.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, spent most of the night with her husband,
according to spokesman Gemmo Trinidad, but she made no statement to
the news media.
   Marcos and his wife have lived here since fleeing the
Philippines during the February 1986 civilian-military revolution
toppled him after 20 years in power.
</TEXT>
