<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-NewYorkOpera     05-25 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-New York Opera,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Met Opens To Enthusiastic Welcome In Tokyo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Placido Domingo led New York's Metropolitan Opera
to a thunderous welcome from Japanese fans Wednesday as the Met
opened its Japan tour with Domingo in the leading role in ``The
Tales of Hoffman.''
   The Spanish tenor's impassioned interpretation of a poet who
relates three love fantasies, one each act brought him eight
curtain calls and roaring approval from an audience that included
Crown Prince Akihito, his wife Princess Michiko and son Prince Hiro.
   With ``Hoffman,'' the Met began its second tour of Japan and
only its fourth tour outside North America. Mozart's ``The Marriage
of Figaro,'' featuring sopranos Kathleen Battle and Hong Hei-kyung
as Susanna and bass-baritone John Cheek as Figaro, opens Friday.
The Met is also performing Verdi's ``Il Travatore.''
   Wednesday's four-hour performance in the 3,450-seat NHK Hall was
punctuated by applause and shouts of approval after each aria, duet
or trio. By the fourth curtain call, most of the audience was on
its feet.
   Applause continued for 11 minutes after the final curtain.
Hundreds in the audience surged toward the front of the stage,
tossing small bouquets to the 47-year-old Domingo and Erie Mills,
Martine Dupuy and Roberta Alexander, who played Hoffman's three
loves.
   Domingo picked up the flowers, handing some to the three female
singers and tossing some to the orchestra pit and the audience.
   The audience also applauded wildly for bass James Morris, who
lustily sang four roles throughout the three acts and prologue and
epilogue, and artistic director James Levine, who conducted the
Metropolitan Opera Orchestra.
   Joining the imperial family on opening night were business and
cultural luminaries, including the Sony Corp. chairman, Akio
Morita; novelist Yukiko Kato and veteran actor Osamu Takizawa.
   ``Domingo's high notes really extended far. He was lovely,''
said Miss Kato. ``As a writer, I think the story of `Hoffman' is
captivating, and that's why I particularly wanted to see it.''
   The New York company's performance ``was wonderful,'' said
Takizawa, 81. ```Figaro' is probably the best known opera in Japan,
but I've seen it done by other troupes. This is my first time to
see the Met, and I'm delighted.''
   For opera devotees who didn't understand the French lyrics, a
Japanese translation was projected onto a narrow screen above the
stage.
   ``If you knew the story slightly, you didn't need to read the
screen,'' Miss Kato said. ``In fact I think it's better not to.''
   While the cheers were clearly heartfelt, the promoter, Japan
Arts Corp., did what it could to encourage them. In a series of
three newsletters sent to those who had purchased advance tickets,
opera lovers were urged to add to the crescendo of bravos _ and not
to boo.
</TEXT>
