<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AirplaneStolen 1stLd-Writethru a0844 05-25 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airplane Stolen, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0844,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Takes Stolen Jet On 1,600-Mile Joyride, Then Kills Self</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with two grafs and subs 16th graf pvs ``Bob
Cunningham'' with four grafs to UPDATES with news conference, in
which pilot says he knew and liked Christiansen, wasn't nervous
talking him down.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight mechanic stole a private Learjet from
Virginia on Wednesday and took it on a 1,600-mile joyride to
Denver, where he killed himself as authorities approached the
plane, officials said.
   Mike Christiansen, 24, who was not a licensed pilot, was found
dead at the controls of the twin-engine plane, a Learjet 36a,
moments after a pilot he knew talked him through a relatively
routine landing at Stapleton International Airport at 5:18 a.m.,
authorities said.
   The pilot, Bob Cunningham, said he was not nervous in talking
Christiansen down, ``because I was confident he was going to listen
to me.''
   Police, FBI agents and emergency personnel were waiting at the
edge of the runway with their lights off when Christiansen landed
the plane, five hours after stealing the 10-seat plane from Patrick
Henry International Airport in Newport News, Va.
   Christiansen, of Newport News, worked as a flight mechanic at
the airport for Atlanta-based Flight International, which owned the
plane and operates the world's largest fleet of Learjets, officials
said.
   ``As the crash crew and law enforcement personnel approached, he
was ordered to lock his brakes,'' said Stapleton spokesman Richard
Boulware. ``They heard a noise and when they looked in the cockpit,
they found him dead. Things happened really fast.''
   Denver FBI spokesman Dick Schussler said the agency knew little
about Christiansen. Gordon James, executive vice president of
Flight International, would only confirm he had been employed
there. The Associated Press made 30 calls to the apartment complex
where he lived and found only one resident at home. She said she
never had heard of him.
   Authorities said they do not know why Christiansen, who was
alone in the plane, killed himself or where he got the gun. The FBI
and Federal Aviation Administration were investigating.
   No motive for the plane theft was given, although Boulware said,
``The indication was that he just wanted to fly around for awhile.''
   ``This guy obviously was a proficient pilot,'' said Boulware.
``He made a good landing right in the middle of the runway with no
damage to the plane or the runway. The very fact that he got off
the ground shows that he knew something.''
   Pete Daikos, spokesman for Patrick Henry airport, said
Christiansen did not have a pilot's license and had been employed
with Flight International since March.
   As the plane was taking off around 2:15 a.m. EDT, it clipped a
security guard's van on a runway, shearing off part of a wingtip
fuel tank and damaging the driver's side of the van, said Daikos.
The guard escaped injury because he had gotten out of the van
moments earlier, Daikos said.
   The plane apparently was airborne for the next five hours,
although FAA officials in Denver said they did not know
Christiansen's whereabouts until he was detected over western
Kansas.
   Controllers at several airports had tracked the plane during
parts of its flight, said Dick Stafford, an FAA spokesman in
Washington, D.C.
   Frank Johns, senior FAA official at the Stapleton tower, said
the FAA contacted International Jet Aviation Services in Englewood
and asked whether a Learjet pilot was available to help
Christiansen land the plane.
   In the meantime, the FAA rerouted some flights along
Christiansen's projected flight path, and Stapleton officials
cleared runways.
   Cunningham, an International Jet Aviation pilot, talked
Christiansen through the landing. The FAA played a 19-minute tape
recording of their conversation, which dealt exclusively with
altitude, airspeed and other technical adjustments Christiansen was
asked to make before setting the plane down.
   In a news conference Wednesday evening, he said he quickly
recognized the voice on the radio as Christiansen, a former
employee of his own company whom he recalled as a ``very personable
man.''
   ``He did his job well. I never had any problems with him,'' he
said, adding that he did not find out that Christiansen had
committed suicide until 10 minutes after the landing.
   ``I was shocked to get that news, and I though it was very
tragic,'' he said.
   After Christiansen landed, Cunningham asked, ``Are you OK, Mike?
Mike, are you OK? Have you got that thing shut down yet?'' There
was no reply, and Boulware said Christiansen was found dead moments
later.
   Vern Alexander, a spokesman for Learjet in Tucson, Ariz., said
the Learjet 36a has a range of 2,568 miles and a cruising speed of
over 500 mph. A standard-equipped model, which sells for $4.25
million, seats 10 passengers and a crew of two.
</TEXT>
