<1ST_LINE>u a AM-St.Elsewhere 1stLd-Writethru a0907 05-25 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-St. Elsewhere, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0907,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC's `St. Elsewhere' Bows Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with two grafs to UPDATE with details of ending. Picks
up 2nd graf pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After six years and a dozen Emmy Awards, NBC's
unconventional hospital show ``St. Elsewhere'' left the air
Wednesday night after a final scene that may have perplexed many
viewers.
   In a maniacal twist on the ``it-was-all-a-dream'' plot that
``Dallas'' made famous, the final scene revealed that the entire
series had never existed, except in the mind of the autistic son of
one of the doctors, Westphall.
   Up until the surprise ending, the final episode, titled ``The
Last One,'' seemed a basic end-of-series sendoff. In view of the
show's irreverent philosophy, perhaps it was, in fact, an obscure
satire on final episodes.
   ``I expect a very mixed reaction (to the ending),'' said Bruce
Paltrow, one of the show's executive producers. ``I think some
people will think it's extraordinary and existential and
quintessential `St. Elsewhere.' I think other people will find it
puzzling, odd, maybe unfulfilling in some way. I think we'll get a
broad range of responses, those being the poles.''
   When it made its debut six season ago, the show was part of a
wave of creativity, mainly from MTM Productions, that
revolutionized stodgy network programming in the 1980s. ``St.
Elsewhere'' followed the MTM series ``Hill Street Blues'' onto NBC
and was inevitably compared to the earlier show's groundbreaking
style _ quick cuts, subplots, overlapping dialogue and hand-held
cameras.
   But ``St. Elsewhere'' went beyond ``Hill Street,'' a police
show, in social satire, even making fun of its own network and
previous MTM shows.
   The ``St. Elsewhere'' writers had wanted to go all out in the
final episode, but prohibitive costs kept their script, a
futuristic view of St. Eligius hospital at the edge of apocalypse,
from being filmed.
   Set in the year 2013, it depicted the St. Eligius doctors, as
well as some now-practicing offspring, waiting for a huge cloud of
toxic gas released in a war between ``U.S. Inc.'' and ``Corporate
Africa.'' The script revealed that Fox and NBC are the only two TV
networks of the future, and that Ed McMahon will become a major
cultural figure.
   In the end, prohibitive costs knocked down not only the intended
final episode but the show itself. ``St. Elsewhere'' was produced
at a loss by MTM at a time when hour-long series are not selling
well in syndication.
   The show has been sold in syndication, though MTM will release
no details. In an apparently personal, inside joke in the dialogue
of the final script, Dr. Wayne Fiscus (Howie Mandel), says of his
years at St. Eligius, ``Grueling hours, bad food, egomania, death
and moral confusion. It'll be hard to leave.''
   The producers of the show have long since left and are busy on a
new series for NBC, ``Tattinger's,'' an offbeat romantic comedy set
in a popular New York restaurant. It is being shot on location here
and stars Stephen Collins, Blythe Danner and Jerry Stiller. The
show is on NBC's fall schedule in the same time period that ``St.
Elsewhere'' is leaving.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
