<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras-Attack     05-25 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Attack,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Clash With Honduran Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduran soldiers battled leftist
Salvadoran guerrillas near the border between the two countries,
leaving 17 rebels dead and three soldiers seriously wounded,
military sources said Wednesday.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
fighting occurred early Tuesday on the outskirts of Marcala, about
90 miles northwest of the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa and 40
miles from the Salvadoran border.
   Since the incident, Honduran air force helicopters have flown
over the area to discourage further fighting, the sources said.
   No further details were available.
   On Saturday, the armed forces said there were intelligence
reports that guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front were planning to carry out terrorist actions in an effort to
destabilize Honduras, a strong U.S. ally in Central America.
   The front, made up of five guerrilla armies, has been fighting
the U.S.-supported government in El Salvador for more than eight
years.
   The armed forces said a rebel unit entered Honduras late last
week to try to take advantage of anti-American sentiment stirred by
the arrest and deportation to the United States of Juan Ramon
Matta, a suspected drug trafficker.
   The Honduran Constitution forbids the extradition of Honduran
citizens.
   In early April, demonstrators burned the U.S. Consulate in
Tegucigalpa.
</TEXT>
