<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TruckExplodes 2ndLd-Writethru a0694 05-25 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Truck Explodes, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0694,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Open Propane Valve to Increase Leak, Speed Up Burning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with firefighters opening valve
after three tries, revises downward number of evacuees to reflect
official change, other details. Pickup 10th graf, `Fire
communications...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters opened a vent on a blazing,
overturned propane tanker Wednesday to try to speed up the burning
of a fire that closed two highways and a commuter rail line for a
second day, officials said.
   Some 500 families remained evacuated Wednesday, police said.
   A vent atop the truck, normally used to let air out as the
tanker is filled, was opened on the firefighters' third attempt to
increase the flow of fuel without setting off an explosion.
   Officials said they couldn't predict how long the fire would
burn because they didn't know how large the rupture was or how much
opening the valve helped. The blaze started when the tanker
overturned at 9:30 a.m. Tuesday.
   Fire Chief Raymond Kuhner said earlier Wednesday although the
``accelerated burn'' method was risky, it was no riskier than
letting the blaze continue. The 2,500-gallon tank could have burned
up to eight days if the flow had not been increased, he said.
   The Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway and the Sunrise Highway
remained closed for a second day, forcing thousands of motorists to
find alternate routes to New York.
   The Long Island Rail Road said 30,000 rail commuters were
directly affected by the closing of several stations on a branch
line, although extra trains were added to the main line.
   The threat of an explosion caused officials to evacuate homes
within a half-mile radius around the tanker, said Nassau County
Executive Thomas Gulotta. Police said 500 households were affected,
revising Tuesday's figure of 2,000 families. About 300 evacuees
spent the night at Seaford Middle School.
   Firefighters kept firetrucks spewing water on the fire to
control it even as they tried to open valves to increase the
propane flow.
   The first valve attempted was found to be melted shut. They then
tried to install a ``belly valve'' that would allow a controlled
flow, but that also failed. Finally, in late afternoon they opened
the vent and hoped propane would trickle out.
   Fire communications supervisor Douglas Wood said the fire
marshal's office and hazardous materials experts were at the scene,
and ambulances were standing by in case of an explosion.
   County police Lt. Willard Krausch said the truck _ owned by
Conservative Gas Co. of Hyde Park _ overturned on the expressway
Tuesday morning when the driver experienced a problem with the
truck's rear wheels.
   The driver, identified by police as Roger Vai, 35, of Westbury,
and a passenger escaped before the truck ignited.
   Vai, who was treated at the scene for a shoulder cut, was
arrested on an outstanding traffic offense and was charged with
driving with a suspended license and failure to produce a license.
He was released on $100 bail.
   Propane such as that carried on the truck meets a variety of
residential and commercial energy needs, particularly in areas not
served by natural gas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
