<1ST_LINE>a i AM-LondonZooFun Adv02   05-25 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-London Zoo Fun, Adv 02,0654</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs AMs, June 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>London Zoo Official Wants Animals to Have Fun, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Shepherdson's job is to take the boredom out
of life for the animals at the London Zoo, putting something more
into their day than sleeping, eating and watching humans.
   He has piped gibbon music into the the gibbon cage.
   For the mongooses, he has provided pieces of hollow wood filled
with crickets for the animals to try to catch. ``Cricket
dispensers,'' he calls them.
   He plans a light-and-sound show for the orangutans.
   The lanky 28-year-old Englishman, whose doctoral thesis had him
tracking wild badgers by radio at night, became behavioral
enrichment officer six months ago at the London Zoo, the first
British zoo to have one.
   Believing a little work for the animals is healthy, too,
Shepherdson is making some species work for their dinners.
   ``Zoos should show the animal as it behaves in the wild,'' he
said. ``For example, in the wild, most species spend more than 50
percent of their time foraging for food. ... In the zoo, they get
fed once a day.
   ``You have a choice _ either change the environment, or you
don't keep the animals properly.''
   Trevor Paul, director of research at the Universities Federation
for Animal Welfare, the independent body co-sponsoring
Shepherdson's post, says the project also works well for people who
visit the zoo.
   ``There isn't a great deal of point in them seeing an animal
sitting in a corner behind bars,'' he said.
   He and Shepherdson say that while zoos in many countries are
making cages more natural, few have spent much time studying animal
behavior in relation to their habitats.
   The 161-year-old London Zoo's gibbon monkeys never did much
loafing in their tree-lined outdoor enclosure, but with the change
in their zoo habitat they've become much more feisty.
   Gibbons usually have one mate for life and assert their
territory by singing. London Zoo's pair weren't as musical as they
should have been until Shepherdson hung stereo speakers near their
cage and played taped gibbon duets twice a day.
   Thinking they have neighbors, the gibbons now sing, too.
   Shepherdson is also working on a computer keyboard to produce
sounds, food or even slide shows when orangutans operate it.
   Paul said an electronic organ failed to excite the apes, ``so
we'll try to get a keyboard which does more things than produce
sound.''
   Simple toys, often involving food, are best for most animals,
Shepherdson said.
   He had praise for Hal Markowitz, a U.S. behavioral enrichment
pioneer who installed a machine to toss meatballs into a serval's
cage, but added that he believes more naturalistic tools should be
explored.
   Recently Shepherdson equipped the ring-tailed lemurs' cage with
poles that sway like the trees in the primates' native Madagascar.
   Paul said one of the best ways to simulate natural behavior ``is
to make an animal work for its food (and) spend normal amounts of
time foraging.''
   In the kinkajous' cage, carrots, bananas and apples hang from
the ceiling, some tantalizingly out of reach for the weasel-like
creatures.
   Before getting the snacks, the female paced for hours _ one of
the first signs of boredom, said Shepherdson, watching as she
pursued a banana just beyond nose-reach.
   ``Even tortoises pace, I'm told,'' Shepherdson added. ``It's not
a lack of space, it's what you have in that space that's
important.''
   After a cage is outfitted, zoo workers watch the animals for
hours to see how they respond.
   ``In every case so far, there's been a beneficial effect,'' said
Shepherdson. ``If every zoo in the country did these things, it
would be a great step forward in animal welfare.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, June 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
