<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv27   05-25 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 27,0840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs May 27, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Puzzlement Surounds Patriarch's Snub To Soviet Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was all set, a rare convergence in the Soviet
Union of Eastern Orthodox leadership, plus other top Christian
echelons. But then, by some labyrinthine tangle, unravelings
appeared in the Orthodox tapestry.
   Little was clear about why, and official statements about it
were couched in the vague circumlocutions of Byzantine innuendo. It
stunned and bewildered many churchmen.
   ``It's very strange and astonishing,'' says the Rev. John
Meyendorff, dean of St. Vladimir's Seminary at Crestwood, N.Y., and
a leading theologian of the Orthodox Church in America.
   ``However you interpret the official statements, there must be
other reasons. There is something more subtle and typically
Mid-Eastern about it. They never, never say anything directly, but
always sideways.''
   What jolted Eastern Orthdoxy was the abrupt word last week that
its top spiritual leader, Patriarch Demetrios of Constantinople
(modern Istanbul), won't attend Soviet celebrations of
Christianity's 1,000th anniversary there.
   Most all of the Eastern church's nine patriarchs apparently had
been going to be there June 5-16, including, or so it seemed,
Demetrios, making it an unprecedented modern gathering of leaders
of the world's 200 million Orthodox.
   Demetrios had visited the Soviet Union last August, had friendly
meetings with the Russian Orthodox Patriarch Pimen and other
clergy, and said he planned to take part in the June celebrations
there.
   Then came the cryptic announcement last week from Orthodoxy's
Ecumenical Patriarchate in Constantinople that Demetrios would not
attend ``because appropriate conditions for participation do not
exist.''
   An Orthodox official in Athens, Greece, maintained then that
Demetrios had determined he would not join in liturgies with
leaders of the Russian Orthodox church in America whose
independence he did not recognize.
   However, that was an old issue, going back 18 years to 1970,
when Russian Orthodoxy granted self-governing status to its U.S.
offspring, the million-member Orthodox Church in America.
   While that status was not officially recognized by the
Ecumenical Patriarchate, no open conflict or breach in communion
occurred over it, and the matter seemed largely disregarded.
   Working relationships have gone on between the Russian-derived
OCA and the 2-million-member Greek Orthodox Church, which remains
under governing oversight of the Ecumenical Patriarchate.
   ``There must be some other factor in Greek politics, memory or
worry'' behind Demetrios' somewhat last-hour decision to avoid the
gathering, says OCA's Meyendorff, who had a friendly visit with him
in 1986.
   ``I suspect there's something more to it than the American
situation,'' Meyendorff added in a telephone interview. ``It may be
just a pretext. That's very characteristic. Perhaps the Turkish
government is behind it. It may be an administrative, not
ecclesiastical, conflict.
   ``I personally don't understand it. Something is behind it with
which I cannot fully connect.''
   There also was puzzlement in Greek Orthodox offices in New York,
where the head of American Greek Orthodoxy, Archbishop Iakovos,
promptly called off plans to attend the Soviet celebrations, since
Demetrios isn't going.
   Iakovos, exarch (representative) of Demetrios in the America,
meanwhile was briefed by a Demetrios aide, Metropolitan
Chrysostomos, on the reasons for the sudden reversal of plans.
   Afterward, Iakovos said that Chrysostomos said ``it became
evident that through the millenium celebrations an attempt was
being made to gain pan-Orthodox acceptance of certain
`anti-cannonical conditions'''
   The circuitously worded May 24 statement added:
   ``The cancellation of the trip became obligatory because the
anti-cannonical conditions assume seemingly de facto recognitions
concerning matters, already included in the agenda of the
forthcoming preparatory meeting of the Pan-Orthodox Synod on which
most of the world's Orthodox churches have already taken a position
against.''
   Asked what that meant, Nikki Stephanopoulos, information
director for Greek Orthodoxy, said she just couldn't be sure.
``They didn't want to say what the conditions were. It's a matter
of trying to be diplomatic.
   ``They don't want to offend anybody. The powers that be must
know, but they evidently don't want to say. Maybe there are other
things, but as I see it, it's strictly ecclesiastical.
   ``It came so much out of the blue. It's a big shock. There's a
lot of stories and rumors floating around.''
   The Rev. Michael Roshak, an OCA clergyman, noted that the OCA is
a canonically recognized member of the council of Orthodox bishops
which Iakovos led in organizing 20 years ago.
   Roshak, who heads the Europe@Soviet office of the National
Council of Churches, said that for Demetrios to cancel
participation in the Russian Orthodox celebration was ``certainly
not a sign of conciliarity and unity.
   ``It was not an exemplary thing to do. The church in the Soviet
has enough problems. It has withstood difficulties and is at an
uneasy moment that also has hopeful possibilities. This shift is
very peculiar.
   ``It is too much a revival of Byzantine intrigue.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs May 27</NOTE>
