<TEXT>
   President Reagan vetoed a major trade bill for
the second time in three years, and the House swiftly countered by
voting to enact the measure over his objections.
   In his veto message Tuesday, Reagan focused his objections on a
provision that would require companies to give their employees
notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   Within hours, the House voted to override the veto, but it was
thought unlikely that the Senate would go along when it considers
the override after a Memorial Day recess.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to the nation's factories for ``big
ticket'' durable goods increased for the third consecutive month in
April, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that orders for durable
goods, items expected to last three or more years, rose 0.8 percent
last month to a seasonally adjusted $116.3 billion. The climb
followed gains of 0.9 percent in March and 0.1 percent in February.
