<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     05-25 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orders For Durable Goods Up; Reagan Vetoes Trade Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The Commerce Department reports on merchandise trade for the
first quarter at 10 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has vetoed major trade legislation amid signs
that the nation's export business is picking up.
   Reagan said he vetoed the legislation Tuesday, as expected,
because of his objections to a provision that would require
companies to give their employees notice of plant closings and
large-scale layoffs.
   ``I am convinced this bill will cost jobs and damage our
economic growth,'' Reagan said in his veto message.
   Within hours, the House voted 308-113 to override the veto. The
margin was well above the two-thirds majority required, but it was
thought unlikely that the Senate would go along when it considers
the override after a Memorial Day recess.
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said orders for ``big
ticket'' durables, items expected to last three or more years, rose
0.8 percent last month to a seasonally adjusted $116.3 billion.
   The climb followed gains of 0.9 percent in March and 0.1 percent
in February. Orders in April were 8.5 percent greater than a year
earlier.
   The moderate increase in durable goods reinforced earlier
signals of an improving trade picture, some economists said.
   ``It clearly shows that export orders are very strong,'' said
Lawrence Chimerine, chairman of WEFA group, a Philadelphia-area
economic forecasting firm.
   The Commerce Department last week reported that U.S. exports
surged 23 percent in March to a record $29 billion, with much of
the strength coming in machinery, aircraft and computers.
   The declining value of the dollar, which is less than half of
what it was three years ago when measured against the Japanese yen,
is bolstering sales of U.S. goods overseas by making them cheaper
when compared with foreign goods.
   Chimerine and David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston &
Co., a government securities dealer in New York, said the cheaper
dollar also is helping U.S. manufacturers by boosting the cost of
imported goods in the United States.
   ``There are some hints that consumers are beginning to turn away
from higher-priced imports in favor of domestic goods,'' Jones said.
   With the signs of economic strength, comes concern that
production in industries is approaching capacity limits, a
development that could fuel price increases.
   However, Chimerine said, ``I think the fears of an inflationary
boom have been exaggerated right from the start. ... Even with an
upturn in exports, we're not in the midst of an economic boom.''
   In other economic reports Tuesday:
   _Home prices continued to skyrocket in several Northeastern
cities during the first three months of 1988, but the hot New York
City market cooled somewhat after the October stock market crash,
the National Association of Realtors said.
   _Mid-May sales of domestically made cars and light trucks rose
2.6 percent from a year ago despite some trimming of buyer
incentive offerings, the auto companies said.
   In the financial markets Tuesday, stock prices rebounded, but
trading remained light. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 21.05 points to 1,962.53, or slightly more than 1 percent.
   Pessimism about interest rates continued to weigh on the market,
sapping investors' willingness to commit their money to stocks.
   In other markets, the dollar and gold slipped as bond prices
advanced slightly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
