<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have closed marginally higher
in another trading session of aimless drifting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Tuesday, contracts for July
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
settled at $17.40 per 42-gallon barrel, up 5 cents from Monday's
close.
   Among refined products for June delivery, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled at 51.80 cents a gallon, up 0.36 cent, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 47.31 cents a gallon, up 0.40 cent.
   Trading consisted of small price moves throughout the session,
said Chris McCormack, an analyst at the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
brokerage firm.
   But he said the market's underlying fundamentals remained
``clearly bearish'' _ despite Monday's gains.
   ``Domestic (oil) stocks are high and the worldwide market is
also stocked with plenty of inventories,'' McCormack explained.
   Given existing demand, these supplies are simply too plentiful
to encourage higher prices, he said.
</TEXT>
