<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   05-25 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Car and Truck Sales Up 2.6 Percent Despite Trimmed
Incentives</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto companies' decisions to offer leaner
incentives in mid-May may have slowed domestic car sales but didn't
hurt overall domestic vehicle sales, which rose 2.6 percent from a
year ago, analysts said.
   Sales of domestically built cars, which fell 2.2 percent in
mid-May from a year ago, also dropped in the wake of an early May
rush by buyers hurrying to beat the May 11 expiration of most
major-maker incentive campaigns.
   The eight companies that build cars and light trucks in the
United States sold 345,004 in the nine selling days from May 11-20,
up from 336,381 in the identical period a year ago, the companies
reported Tuesday.
   Sales of domestic cars slipped to 216,325 from 221,127, while
sales of light trucks rose 11.6 percent, to 128,679 from 115,254 a
year ago.
   ``The companies think we're moving into the strong spring
selling season and can afford to take off incentives, but every
time they do, car sales fall,'' said Kathleen Heaney, analyst with
Nikko Securities Co. International in New York.
   The incentive campaigns were extended, but many rebates were
trimmed and some models were removed.
   Sales have remained stronger than expected so far in 1988,
leading the Big Three to increase estimates of total 1988 vehicle
sales, import and domestic, to 15.3 million from 15 million.
   Buying conditions have improved for consumers nationwide through
lower interest rates, strong income gains and low unemployment,
said Ted Sullivan, analyst with Wharton Econometrics in
Philadelphia.
   But much of the additional strength has come along the Pacific
and South Atlantic coasts, where the weakness of the dollar against
foreign currencies has boosted sales of products such as textiles,
light machinery and lumber, he said.
   ``If the dollar does continue to weaken, then the price gap
between import and domestic goods will grow and you'll get this
boost in the interior section of the country, which produces heavy
industrial products,'' Sullivan said.
   Chrysler Corp., the No. 3 U.S. automaker, sold 3.1 percent more
domestic cars and 31.9 percent more domestic trucks during mid-May
than a year ago.
   Chrysler's share of the domestic car market grew to 14.7 percent
from 13.7 percent and its share of the domestic light truck market
rose to 22.9 percent from 21 percent a year ago.
   General Motors Corp., the world's largest automaker and the U.S.
industry leader, sold 6.4 percent fewer domestic cars during the
period than a year earlier. But GM's light truck sales rose 10.5
percent.
   GM's share of the domestic car market slipped to 49 percent from
51.3 percent a year ago while truck share held nearly steady at
39.1 percent.
   Ford Motor Co., the world's second-largest automaker, sold 2.6
percent more domestic cars than a year ago, but its light truck
sales slipped 2.4 percent, the company reported.
   Ford's share of the domestic car market rose to 29 percent from
27.9 percent a year ago but its truck share slipped to 35.5 percent
from 37.8 percent.
   Nissan Motor Corp., which reduced car production and increased
truck production at its factory in New Smyrna, Tenn., sold 52.4
percent fewer domestic cars and 112.9 percent more domestic trucks
than in mid-May a year ago.
   Volkswagen, which is gearing down its Westmoreland, Pa., factory
toward this summer's closing, sold 39.3 percent fewer domestic cars
than a year ago.
   Honda Motor Co.'s domestic car sales rose 37.2 percent and
Toyota Motor Corp.'s rose 43.4 percent from a year ago. Mazda Motor
Corp. began building cars at its Flat Rock assembly plant in
September and sold 992 in mid-May.
</TEXT>
