<DOCNO> AP880525-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LiberalArts Bjt   05-25 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liberal Arts, Bjt,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Study Finds Liberal Arts Grads In Demand By Corporations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's top companies are placing more
emphasis on creativity and communications skills and actively
recruiting students who major in the liberal arts, a new survey
shows.
   About one-quarter of 535 chief executives surveyed by Boston
University explicitly encouraged the hiring of liberal arts
graduates and almost half of their companies said they seek
humanities majors by recruiting on campus.
   ``There is a very substantial hiring of liberal arts graduates
by the nation's major employers,'' Michael Useem, director of the
university's Center for Applied Social Science, who conducted the
survey, said Tuesday.
   Useem said companies with chief executives who advocate a broad
education ``were out there hiring liberal arts graduates way above
average.''
   The study, completed earlier this month, was sponsored by the
Corporate Council on the Liberal Arts in collaboration with the
President's Committee on the Arts and Humanities.
   ``Top corporate executives are more concerned than before,
certainly than in the 1970s, about the overly narrow education of
some of those who are applying for white collar jobs in the
corporation,'' Useem said.
   Letters seeking information on hiring patterns were sent to the
chief executives of the Fortune 1000, the nation's 1,000 largest
corporations, and 200 mid-size companies. The survey had a 45
percent response rate, including more than half of the nation's top
100 companies.
   In addition, 505 middle and senior managers at large companies
were interviewed by telephone about their career experiences
working with other managers of varying educational backgrounds.
   ``What we've seen in recent years is perhaps more employers have
become convinced of the value of a liberal education in terms of
their long-range needs,'' said Skip Sturman, director of career and
employment services at Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H.
   Increasing corporate competition in the United States and abroad
has made students with diverse backgrounds more attractive, the
study showed.
   ``Some corporations are facing a much more competitive
environment that places a premium on creativity and innovation, and
they want people who can easily move across boundaries, think in an
interdisciplinary way,'' Useem said.
   A nationwide survey by the University of California at Los
Angeles cited by Useem found that student interest in liberal arts
is rebounding after a 10-year decline.
   It found that 25 percent of first-year college students reported
an interest in a liberal arts major, compared with a low of 21
percent in the early 1980s, but far below the 40 percent of 1970.
   At the same time, 27 percent of students said they were
interested in business arts majors, up from 24 percent in the early
1980s and 16 percent in 1970.
   ``(Companies) are looking for students who can be trained in
that specific industry but will bring to the company a broader
thinker,'' said Liza Bernard, director of career development for
Haverford and Bryn Mawr Colleges in suburban Philadelphia.
   Bernard said on-campus recruiting by businesses has doubled
since 1980, with about 60 companies seeking students last year at
the two liberal arts colleges, each of which have about 1,200
undergraduates.
   The principle attractions for liberal arts students are better
salaries to help pay off tuition debts and training that can be
applied to other jobs.
   ``If you do an undergraduate business degree and then a
(master's of business administration) it seems to me the education
is much too narrow,'' said Mary Maples Dunn, president of Smith
College in Northampton, Mass. ``After all, anyone who wants to make
a success out of a life in business or anywhere else needs to have
a broad understanding of the human condition.''
   At Smith, the largest of the nation's women's liberal arts
colleges, economics was the second most-popular major among this
month's graduates, 177 in a class of 700.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
