<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SouthKorea-Trade     05-25 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Trade,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea's Trade Surplus with U.S. Drops; Deficit with Japan
Shrinks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's trade surplus with the
United States shrank to $2.58 billion between January and April
from $2.69 billion in the same period last year, the Trade and
Industry Ministry reported today.
   Officials attributed the reduced surplus to efforts to increase
imports from the United States and reduce imports from Japan to
correct the bilateral trade imbalance, the source of friction with
the Reagan administration.
   The ministry officials said the Korean won's rise against the
U.S. dollar also slowed the pace of Korean exports to the United
States. The won, South Korea's currency, has risen 8 percent
against the dollar since January.
   South Korea's trade deficit with Japan during the January-April
period shrank to $1.31 billion from $1.85 billion a year earlier.
   The narrowed deficit with Japan was attributed to brisk exports
to Japan helped by the strong Japanese yen as well as less reliance
on Japan for machinery and raw materials.
   South Korean exports to the United States between January and
April were tallied at $6.07 billion, up 19.3 percent from a year
earlier, while imports equaled $3.49 billion, up 45.8 percent.
   South Korean exports to Japan jumped 59.1 percent to $3.56
billion, while imports from Japan rose 19.1 percent to $4.87
billion.
   South Korea posted a worldwide trade surplus of $1.88 billion in
the first four months of this year.
</TEXT>
