<DOCNO> AP880525-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TexasAir-Eastern Bjt   05-25 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Air-Eastern, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Texas Undermining Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the financial woes at Eastern Airlines must
be laid at the door of parent Texas Air Corp., which, even as it
decries labor costs, siphons money and assets from the Miami-based
carrier, a new report says.
   ``It is not possible for an airline to shrink its way to
profitability,'' says the report by Touche Ross & Co., an
international accounting and management consulting firm.
   The report, commissioned by the Air Line Pilots Association and
criticized by Eastern and Texas spokesmen, details the sale of
Eastern assets to Texas Air for what it called less than market
value and the apparently heavy management fees Eastern has paid
Texas Air since it was purchased by the Houston-based company in
1986.
   ``Management of Texas Air and Eastern have defined Eastern's
difficulties solely in terms of labor costs and unions; yet
non-union Continental lost substantially more than unionized
Eastern even after the adverse impact of the above transactions on
Eastern is taken into account,'' says the report, largely prepared
by analyst Farrell Kupersmith.
   ``Without the above transactions, the difference in performance
at Eastern and Continental would have been even more dramatic _
with Eastern performing substantially better than Continental,''
according to the report.
   Eastern lost $182 million last year, compared to $258 million at
Continental, also owned by Texas Air.
   Most of Eastern's losses and erosion of liquidity are because of
``upstreaming'' of payments and assets to Texas Air, the report
says.
   Texas Air, which lost a total $466 million last year, is heavily
leveraged with ``junk bonds,'' is dependent on ``upstreaming'' of
cash from its subsidiaries, has overstated its liquidity and
probably lacks credit standing for much new financial backing,
Touche Ross says.
   Texas Air spokesman Bruce Hicks called the report ``a work of
fiction.''
   ``The Touche Ross analysis is just replete with distortions and
false assumptions,'' Robin Matell, an Eastern spokesman said
Tuesday, citing examples of figures he said were inflated in the
report.
   Matell said the report's conclusions showed ``a lack of
understanding of normal business practices.''
   The Touche Ross report cited $22.5 million paid by Eastern to
Continental for strike preparation fees, $6 million in management
fees paid last year by Eastern to Texas Air, $9.1 million for
administrative and fuel purchasing services paid to TAC, and tens
of millions more paid for use of computers and reservations systems.
   Eastern, which has indicated plans to reduce flying further this
summer, lost available passenger miles estimated worth $50 million
to $75 million because of flying cutbacks, the report says. Some
routes were transferred to Continental.
   ``It is widely accepted that shrinking revenue raises cost per
available seat mile and results in an exaggeration of losses,'' the
report says.
   The Touche Ross report notes that Eastern attempted to sell its
profitable Northeast Shuttle to Texas Air to become a subsidiary; a
Machinists union federal lawsuit has blocked it. There has also
been talk of selling Eastern's Latin American routes.
   Matell said such transactions as the sale of the Systems One
reservations system to Texas Air injected badly needed cash into
Eastern. He said the fees Eastern now pays for use of the
reservations system are less than what Eastern's own cost of
operating the system would be.
   The management fees are ``a miniscule fraction of operating
costs,'' he said.
   Texas Air contends that Eastern labor costs are too high and
that the unions must make some concessions. Eastern is locked in
federal mediation with its largest union, the 12,000-member
International Association of Machinists local.
   The Department of Transportation is expected to soon release the
results of its own study, announced April 13, into the ability of
Texas Air to run airlines. A U.S. House resolution has questioned
Texas Air's commitment to keeping Eastern viable.
   In Washington on Tuesday, federally mediated hearings opened to
settle a bitter dispute between airline unions and Texas Air over
whether Eastern and Continental should be considered a single
airline for bargaining purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
