<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Better At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher at midday Wednesday after
British authorities cleared the way for Nestle S.A.'s $3.9 billion
bid for Rowntree PLC and for Jacob Suchard's 29.9-percent stake in
the company.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 9.0
points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,791.9 at 12:30 p.m. local time.
   Volume was a moderate 324.9 million shares compared with 243.5
million at midday Tuesday.
   Traders said the market was enlivened by Trade Secretary Lord
Young's decision not to refer the Nestle bid nor the Suchard stake
to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
   ``Lord Young's choice was terrific news for the whole market,''
said one equity salesman.
   Rowntree's share prices surged on news of the bid, which was
worth 2.1 billion British pounds. After moving down 5 pence to 912
pence, or $16.96, in early trading, the shares jumped to 988 pence,
or $18.37, before easing back to 984 pence, or $18.30.
   Other food shares also benefited from the news, including United
Biscuits, which was up 10 pence at 280 pence, or $5.20, and Cadbury
Schweppes, which added 15 pence to 376 pence, or $6.99.
</TEXT>
