<DOCNO> AP880525-0327 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0844EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-USBeef     05-25 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-US Beef,0519</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>US-Japan Beef Pact Seen Likely Soon</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. beef industry representative on
Wednesday praised the ``hardline approach'' by U.S. negotiators in
farm trade talks with Japan and predicted a favorable bilateral
beef agreement would be concluded by the end of May.
   Philip Seng, Asia director of the U.S. Meat Export Federation,
said recent concessions by the Japanese government should serve to
break an impasse in talks to renew a beef and citrus fruit pact
that expired in March.
   ``Our government's approach of hardlining it ... has already
paid dividends as far as the U.S. (beef) industry is concerned ...
I think hopefully we can actually realize a bilateral agreement
within the month,'' said Seng, whose federation represents major
U.S. farm organizations and businesses.
   Last week, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita instructed the
government party to seek a speedy solution to the dispute, brought
about by U.S. demands for full access to Japan's beef and orange
markets. He leaves next Monday for an official visit to the United
States.
   Other government officials, including Japan's ambassador to
Washington, have also indicated recently that an agreement was
expected soon.
   Bilateral talks to settle the beef and orange issue broke down
in April after Washington flatly rejected a Japanese plan to
counterbalance market-opening measures with variable surcharges on
beef imports, aimed at bringing import prices up to domestic levels.
   But Seng said the ruling Liberal Democratic Party, strongly
dependent on the rural vote, was prepared to scrap the levy or
surcharge and retain the present tariffs.
   LDP Secretary General Shintaro Abe ``indicated that they will
just have a tariff at the end of the day,'' Seng said. Other
officials have ``indicated that they would raise their quota (of
U.S. beef imports) to 40,000 metric tons per annum for the next
three to four years, that's a substantial increase over the
9,000-metric-ton (annual) increases that we've enjoyed so far.''
   Seng also said a bilateral beef agreement would include a
reduction in the power of the Livestock Industry Promotion
Corporation, which controls some 80 percent of beef sold throughout
Japan.
   He ruled out a U.S. move to abolish the quasi-governmental
organization that slaps a 50 percent tax on imported beef prior to
the complicated wholesale stage.
   ``Rather than trying to attack the LIPC open-faced ... (the U.S.
strategy is) to effect change, meaningful change, in the role of
the LIPC and limit the amount of control that they do have.''
   On May 4, the United States brought the dispute to the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a Geneva-based forum to rule on
international trade disputes. But both U.S. and Japanese officials
have maintained they will continue efforts to forge a new agreement
out of GATT.
   U.S. beef shipments to Japan account for some 85 percent of the
193 million pounds the nation exports annually, worth some $600
million. That figure, says Seng, could be multiplied by three to
four times if Japan fully liberalizes its market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0328 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 0845EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Deere     05-25 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Deere,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deere Posts 145 Percent Gain in Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm equipment manufacturer Deere & Co. says
an improved farm economy helped boost its net earnings in the
second quarter by 145 percent, compared with the year-ago period.
   ``North American retail sales of John Deere agricultural and
industrial equipment during fiscal 1988 have increased
significantly over last year's levels,'' Chairman Robert A. Hanson
said in a statement Tuesday.
   Deere reported net income of $86.4 million, or $1.26 per share,
for the three months ended April 30, compared with $35.3 million,
or 52 cents per share, for the same period a year ago.
   Net sales increased 27 percent, from $1.14 billion to $1.45
billion, the company said.
   ``During the remainder of the year, we expect retail sales ...
to exceed those in the final half of 1987,'' Hanson said.
   Worldwide production of all Deere products in 1988 was scheduled
to be about 30 percent higher than actual 1987 output, he noted.
   ``The agricultural economy has continued to strengthen in 1988
with improvement in a number of important agricultural economic
indicators,'' Hanson said. ``Price competition remains keen in our
markets, but the fundamentals of our businesses are stronger and
our operating results greatly improved.''
   Gary Benjamin of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago agreed that
Deere had been helped by a turnaround in the agricultural economy,
noting that record high farm earnings of $55 billion were posted in
1987.
   ``Earnings this year are expected to be close to last year's
record high,'' Benjamin said. ``That is helping to improve farmland
values. Farmers feel a little more confident now about going out
and making capital expenditures.''
   Deere's net income for the first six months of 1988 was about
$154 million, compared with last year's net loss of $157 million,
which included the adverse effects of a strike through the first
quarter.
   Analysts said the weak dollar probably helped Deere's exports to
increase by 36 percent, to $340 million from $251 million last year.
   They also noted that Deere has drastically cut its workforce in
the past nine years, lowering employment costs. Steven Colbert of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. said Deere employment last year
was only 37,931, compared with 65,392 in 1979.
</TEXT>
