<HEAD>Murray Ohio Urges Stockholders To Wait For Company Advice On
Electrolux Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Murray Ohio Manufacturing
Co. have urged shareholders to refrain from selling their stock
until the company can review a $197 million takeover bid by
Sweden's AB Electrolux.
   Murray Ohio stock jumped $8 a share to close at $59.25 Tuesday
in New York Stock Exchange composite trading, indicating that
investors expect Electrolux to sweeten its current $52-a-share
offer.
   In a letter to shareholders, Murray Ohio Chairman W.M. Hannon
and President J.L. Duncan said the company's board was
``considering the Electrolux offer. The board will complete its
review and communicate with you no later than June 7 to advise you
of the company's recommendation.''
   Analysts said the offer must rise to at least $227 million _ $60
per share _ to be accepted. Murray directors rejected an earlier
Electrolux bid of $48 per share, or $182 million.
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Wiseman removed one
roadblock to Electrolux's bid, but Murray immediately appealed to
the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Wiseman denied Murray's request to block Electrolux from
proceeding with its offer and said, ``I know of no law permitting
the court to enjoin the transfer of stock. We still have in this
country respect for private property.''
   A three-judge panel of the 6th Circuit scheduled a hearing
Friday in Nashville on Murray's appeal.
   Murray manufactures lawn mowers and bicycles at its
Lawrenceburg, Tenn., plant. AB Electrolux is an international
appliance giant with a product line that includes chain saws and
line weed trimmers.
   Boyd Poston, analyst for A.G. Edwards & Sons in St. Louis,
predicted AB Electrolux would have to bid at least $60 a share for
its offer to be considered, since the market price was so high.
Poston said he knew of no other company seeking to acquire Murray,
but ``you almost feel like there's got to be somebody else in
there.''
   David Leibowitz, analyst for American Securities Corp. in New
York, said the jump in Murray stock prices Tuesday ``is a great
indication that there are those on Wall Street who believe that the
offer will go higher.''
   AB Electrolux, which has no connection with vacuum cleaner
manufacturer Electrolux Inc. of Marietta, Ga., operates a Tappan
range plant at Springfield, Tenn., north of Nashville.
</TEXT>
