<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Trade-Communists     05-25 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Trade-Communists,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Parliament Leader Cites ``Historic'' Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Plumb, the president of the European
Parliament, on Wednesday hailed a ``historic'' agreement between
Europe's communist and Western trade organizations.
   Under the agreement, announced in Brussels, the Soviet-led trade
bloc known as Comecon grants diplomatic recognition to the European
Economic Community, including West Berlin.
   It will be initialed in Moscow on June 9 and officially endorsed
by EEC foreign ministers at a meeting in Luxembourg on June 14.
   In winding up a two-day official visit to Norway, which is not
an EEC member, Lord Plumb said at a press conference: ``This is a
historic moment we've waited for for a long time.''
   ``We can`t expect immediate results, but on long sight this
agreement will be of great importance for development of both trade
and political relations in Europe,'' he said.
   ``The agreement may be of especially great importance for
neutral countries like Austria,'' making it easier for them to
trade with the European Economic Community, he added.
   The EEC will set up an embassy in Moscow and Comecon will set up
an embassy in Brussels, Lord Plumb said.
   Members of Comecon, or the Council for Mutual Economic
Assistance, are the Soviet Union, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East
Germany, Hungary, Poland, Rumania, Mongolia, Vietnam and Cuba.
   According to Lord Plumb, Czechoslovakia and Hungary are
currently negotiating bilateral trade agreements with the EEC, and
Poland, Bulgaria and the Soviet Union have signalled that they also
want such agreements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
