<HEAD>Ali Raises Shoe Polish Issue at K mart Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former heavyweight boxing champion Muhammad
Ali showed up at K mart Corp.'s annual meeting Tuesday for another
round in his fight to sell shoe polish throughout the retail chain.
   ``Muhammad Ali's Champion Brand'' shoe polish is a product of
Champion Brand Industries, which the former boxer controls.
   Ali, a K mart shareholder, and several friends sat in the front
row at the meeting, held in the company's cafeteria and attended by
about 1,000 people.
   In response to questions from Ali's group, K mart Chairman
Joseph Antonini said K mart had accepted delivery of $500,000 worth
of Champion Brand wax shoe polish was test marketing it in selected
stores. He said sales would be monitored.
   Company officials would not disclose which stores are selling
the product.
   Ali's business partner and friend, Arthur Morrison, said K mart
agreed under pressure from Ali and supporters at last year's annual
meeting to buy $700,000 worth of liquid shoe polish along with the
$500,000 in wax shoe polish. But he said K mart turned away the
liquid shoe polish shipments.
   Morrison said Ali supporters are calling for a boycott of K mart
over the shoe polish issue.
   Separately, Antonini said K mart plans to open at least 100 new
discount stores and expand 80 of its current stores in 1988 and
1989.
