<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BAT     05-25 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-BAT,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BAT Industries' Profit Jumps 14.1 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC said Wednesday its
first-quarter, pre-tax profit rose 14.1 percent over a year ago on
a robust performance by its tobacco operations.
   That performance more than offset a decline in contributions
from financial services and disappointing results in the United
States, the company said.
   Pre-tax profit for the first three months of 1988 came to 283
million pounds, or $529 million at current exchange rates. That was
up from 248 million pounds in the year-earlier period.
   Net profit increased 14 percent to 163 million pounds, or $305
million, compared with 143 million pounds in the 1987 first
quarter, the company said.
   Revenues gained 4.2 percent, to 3.97 billion pounds, or $7.42
billion, from 3.81 billion pounds.
   The company said the adverse effects of currency movements
reduced pre-tax profit by 17 million pounds, or $32 million, in the
latest period. This reflected the pound's gains against European
currencies, it said.
   Tobacco operations contributed 163 million pounds, or $305
million, to operating profit, up from 120 million pounds, helped in
part by strong gains in exports to Japan following greater opening
of the Japanese market to imported cigarettes, BAT Chairman Patrick
Sheehy told a news conference.
   Operating profit from financial services, however, fell to 88
million pounds, or $165 million, from 92 million pounds, as a
result of a decline in the value of investments of BAT's Eagle Star
unit following October's stock market crash.
   Paper and pulp interests had operating profit of 64 million
pounds, or $120 million, up from 60 million pounds.
   The company said the weakness of the U.S. retailing market in
the fourth quarter of 1987 continued in the first three months of
1988.
   BAT has launched a hostile, $4.5 billion-dollar takeover offer
for Farmers Group Inc., a Los Angeles-based insurance company.
</TEXT>
