<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BankBid 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Grants Bank of New York an Extension in Bid for Irving</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, The Fed ..., to change to today sted
Wednesday to conform to style and 13th graf, On Monday ..., to
UPDATE with Irving board approving revised Banca Commerciale offer</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have given Bank of New York
Corp. a 45-day extension for completing its hostile tender offer
for Irving Bank Co., and the unwanted suitor extended its bid until
the end of this week.
   The Federal Reserve Board's action Tuesday prompted New York
State Supreme Court Justice Herman Cahn to delay acting on Bank of
New York's challenge to Irving's latest anti-takeover ``poison
pill'' defense.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, Irving reinstated its board of directors
after a final count showed it had beaten Bank of New York in the
bitter proxy battle for control of the company.
   Cahn also set up a briefing schedule for Bank of New York's
challenge of the election results. The company must submit
supporting documents by next Tuesday, and a hearing on the issue
will be held by June 3.
   Bank of New York had asked federal regulators for an extension
to consummate its proposed takeover of Irving, which has been
stalled by a number of factors, including a series of lawsuits, the
outcome of the proxy fight and from Irving's poison pill.
   Although the Fed granted a 45-day extension Tuesday, it noted it
was concerned about some possible adverse affects of the merger.
The board required Bank of New York to notify the Fed when it had
acquired 5 percent of Irving's shares and obtain the board's
permission before proceeding with the takeover.
   The Fed had given Bank of New York conditional approval for the
merger in February. That approval was scheduled to expire on today.
   Bank of New York has maintained it will proceed with its $1.1
billion tender offer, and run Irving as a separate subsidiary,
regardless of whether it could win control of Irving's board. The
offer is for $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's 18.5 million common shares outstanding.
   It was set to expire at midnight Tuesday, although it was
extended until midnight Friday and conditioned upon Bank of New
York receiving at least 67 percent of Irving's shares. As of last
Monday, Bank of New York held about a 50 percent stake in Irving,
including shares it owned and those tendered.
   Irving recently took steps to prevent Bank of New York from
proceeding with its tender offer. Last week, it amended its
``poison pill'' so that it would be activated should any unwanted
investor acquire at least 20 percent of Irving shares on the open
market. The poison pill previously would have gone into effect in
the event of a takeover not supported by management.
   Poison pill defenses are designed to discourage takeover bids by
greatly increasing the cost of an acquisition. In Irving's case,
all existing shareholders except Bank of New York would be allowed
to buy Irving shares for half-price once Bank of New York acquired
20 percent of Irving shares.
   Irving has steadfastly rejected Bank of New York takeover
proposals, instead opting for a friendly merger with the state-run
Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second largest bank.
   The company announced today that its board unanimously approved
Banca Commerciale's sweetened cash offer of $80 a share for a 51
percent stake in Irving. The revised bid, up $5 a share from the
previous offer, was conditional on Irving keeping intact the latest
anti-takeover defense it adopted to fend off Bank of New York.
   The Banca Commerciale bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that includes sale of Irving assets, several cost-cutting
measures and a special $10 dividend. The proposal still needs
regulatory approval.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said his company has no
plans to raise its tender offer.
   The company had proposed increasing the stock portion if Irving
agreed to hold friendly talks and dismantle its poison pill
defense. But Irving's board of directors unanimously rejected that
proposal last week.
   In a reconvened annual shareholders' meeting Tuesday, Irving
said its shareholders re-elected the incumbent board over Bank of
New York's slate of 16 nominees by 52 percent to 48 percent. The
count confirmed preliminary results that were released earlier this
month.
   Brady said it would file suit in New York State Supreme Court to
declare the results invalid. The company claimed that four Irving
shareholders with more than 950,000 shares of Irving stock
confirmed that their votes were improperly counted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880525-0340 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BlueMountain-Hallmark     05-25 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blue Mountain-Hallmark,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Ruling Against Hallmark Cards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has upheld a ruling
temporarily forbidding Hallmark Cards Inc. from making greeting
card designs resembling those of a small competitor, clearing the
way for a full trial of the company's $50 million damage suit
against Hallmark.
   ``Blue Mountain Arts has pushed the bullies back to the alley.
We've been waiting and waiting on the ruling and it's entirely in
our favor,'' said Bob Gall, general manager of the Boulder,
Colo.-based company, which won the injunction. ``We are absolutely
ecstatic.''
   Blue Mountain brought suit against Hallmark, based in Kansas
City, Mo., in July 1986, alleging that Hallmark's ``Personal
Touch'' line of greeting cards is deceptively similar to Blue
Mountain's ``AireBrush Feelings'' and ``WaterColor Feelings'' lines.
   Blue Mountain alleged that Hallmark was guilty of unfair
competition and copyright infringement.
   A federal court ruled in November 1986 that Blue Mountain's two
card lines have ``an inherently distinctive and highly uniform
overall appearance that is recognizable and attributable to Blue
Mountain.''
   It ordered Hallmark to stop producing and marketing 83 specific
greeting card designs.
   The Blue Mountain cards are characterized by backgrounds of soft
colors done with air brush blends or light watercolor strokes.
   In April, Hallmark appealed the injunction order, arguing that a
single greeting card company should not have ``perpetual rights to
a style of art, a style of text and a concept of their combined
use.''
   In Tuesday's decision, the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
affirmed the injunction, saying the lower court was correct in
determining that the combination of features comprising the trade
dress, or the overall appearance, of Blue Mountain's cards can be
protected.
   A date for a full trial is expected to be scheduled now that the
appeal has been decided. Blue Mountain is seeking $50 million in
damages from Hallmark and will fight what they consider Hallmarks's
other ``copycat'' card designs.
   ``It's not only a victory for Stephen and me and for Blue
Mountain, but it's also a victory for the arts and for all creative
people,'' said Susan Polis Schutz, a poet who co-founded Blue
Mountain with her husband Stephen Schutz.
   Polis Schutz said Blue Mountain's main complaint was the look of
the cards, which she said confused everyone, ``including myself.''
   ``This decision means you can create something and not have to
worry about it being stolen,'' she said. ``One of the things that
Stephen and I learned is that it is possible to stand up for your
rights no matter how small you are or how big your opponent is.''
   Charles W. Hucker, a spokesman for the greeting card giant, said
Tuesday night that Hallmark was disappointed but not surprised by
the decision.
   ``We will consider making a further appeal. It is important to
understand that this is a preliminary decision based on a limited
airing of the issues,'' Hucker said. ``We will have the opportunity
to present our case in full for the first time at the trial.''
   Hucker noted that the Blue Mountain suit contended Hallmark
copied the smaller company's look.
   ``It is absolutely not true, and they know it's not true, that
we copied specific designs,'' he said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
