<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened modestly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as fears of dry weather
continued to dominate the market.
   Little rain was forecast for the nation's midsection for the
rest of this week, and the newly planted corn and soybean crops
need rain to get off to a good start, analysts said.
   ``There's also some follow-through buying from yesterday's
sharply higher close and that's about it,'' said Victor Lespinasse,
a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``There's really nothing
else of any consequence.''
   Lespinasse said bullish traders hoped to bid the November
soybean contract above its lifetime high of $8.08 a bushel today. A
successful test of that barrier could prompt a new surge of buying,
he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.51 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1} cents higher with July at $2.20 a bushel; oats were { cent to 1
cent higher with July at $1.76 a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to
6 cents higher with July at $7.86 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .27 cent lower with June at 72.10
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .90 cent lower with
May at 80.85 cents a pound; hogs were .35 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with June at 53.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.10 cent to .13 cent lower with July at 53.57 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
