<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IroquoisChairman     05-25 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iroquois Chairman,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Executive Sells Stock, Leaves Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terence J. Fox, who served 23 years as
chief executive officer and largest shareholder of Iroquois Brands
Ltd., has sold all his Iroquois stock and left the company.
   Fox sold his stock, comprising 21.4 percent of the total
outstanding shares, to Malcolm H. Stockdale of Houston, the company
said Tuesday.
   Stockdale was named chief executive officer and elected chairman
of the Iroquois board. He is president and chairman of the board of
Bio International Inc., an engineering-equipment maker incorporated
in Utah.
   Fox declined to say why he decided to sell his shares and leave
the board, but said it was ``a mutual decision.''
   ``I'm quite pleased with the situation,'' he said.
   In November 1985, Fox was arrested at a Hartford hotel and
charged with possession of cocaine and possession of narcotics
paraphernalia after police said they found 17 grams of cocaine in
his room. In April 1986, he was granted accelerated rehabilitation,
a program allowing dismissal of charges if a probationary period is
successfully completed.
   During the last four years, Iroquois has sold its biggest and
best-known businesses _ including Champale _ reducing revenue in
1987 to less than half the level the company had reported four
years earlier.
   The remaining businesses _ Schiff health food vitamins and
Pharmacaps Inc., which makes gelatin capsules most commonly used
for Vitamin E _ have reported losses for the past five years.
   Last week, the company reported first quarter earnings of
$107,000, or 18 cents a share, compared to $187,000, or 26 cents a
share, for the same period a year ago.
   Revenue for the latest quarter was $19 million, down from $21.5
million.
</TEXT>
