<1ST_LINE>s f BC-GoingPublic Adv29   05-25 1038</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Going Public, Adv 29,1072</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday May 29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Some Small Firms Brave The Market; Others Seek Alternative
Financing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small companies still hunger to see their names
on a filigreed stock certificate, but it's a luxury few can afford
these days.
   The companies that can make a convincing sales pitch for their
stock to a jittery, post-crash Wall Street are those with
substantial track records and solid, innovative products.
   But other young companies are shrinking from the prospect of
selling stock at fire-sale prices and instead are knocking on the
doors of venture capitalists, who may ask for a few board seats in
return for capital.
   Industry insiders say the market crash and its aftershocks have
been devastating for less-developed companies by limiting the
financial tools they depend on.
   ``A lot of companies won't be financed, and it will lead to a
pruning out, a survival of the fittest,'' one expert said.
   Since last October's Black Monday, the number of initial public
offerings raising $25 million or less _ a size typical for small
companies _ has fallen off dramatically.
   In April 1987, 28 such offerings were recorded, raising a total
of $205.4 million, according to IDD Information Services Inc. Last
month, only 10 offerings were made for a mere $53.2 million. The
intervening months saw even fewer new issues.
   A pervasive lack of investor confidence is the main reason it
has become ``almost impossible for companies without a strong
record of earnings or strong evidence of exceptionally powerful
technology to go public,'' said Martin Orland, president of Amev
Venture Management Inc.
   Many companies simply scrapped their plans after the Oct. 19
market collapse. Orland had three companies that had registered
with the Securities and Exchange Commission to issue stock, but
they aborted their plans rather than slash the offering price.
   Pulse Engineering Inc., a San Diego maker of electronic
components that hoped to raise about $15 million by selling shares
for between $9 and $10, was one of those companies.
   Orland said the stock price would have been ``substantially
lower'' had the company decided to go ahead with the issue in the
wake of the crash. Instead, the group was able to secure additional
bank financing.
   Not all companies are that fortunate.
   ``A lot can't fill the gap, and we are seeing many situations of
aborted public offerings coming to us for financing,'' Orland said.
   But money from venture capitalists is exchanged for a piece of
ownership, forcing management to decide how much control they are
willing to give up.
   For young companies, the alternatives can be limited. Some have
opted to go public anyway at lower offering prices, while others
are bootstrapping their way along _ simply growing slower without
the funds. Still others are seeking mergers or equity links to
larger corporations.
   NeoRx Corp., a Seattle-based biotechnology firm, had registered
with the SEC in March to raise $30 million but has since witnessed
``a deterioration in the market, particularly in biotechnology and
pharmaceutical stocks,'' said Chief Financial Officer Robert
Littauer.
   In the meantime, Littauer said the company is looking for other
methods of financing until the market turns around. So far, the
company has held discussions with a Japanese company and a European
firm.
   ``We would be doing that anyway,'' Littauer said, ``but we might
make the terms more responsive to our current situation _ we might
ask for a larger up-front payment so we can use it as a tool to
help our current financial situation.''
   Companies that are braving the stock market's choppy waters are
established, often showing annual revenue in excess of $50 million.
   Clean Harbors Inc., a Boston-based hazardous waste firm with $50
million in annual revenue, raised $10 million last November. Shares
that initially sold for $9 each are now trading in the $14 range.
   Sandy Robertson, a partner in the San Francisco investment
banking firm Robertson, Colman & Stephens Inc., attributed the
issue's success to ``institutional investors who understood the
hazardous waste business,'' which he described as ``immune from the
economy as a whole.''
   Another market survivor is Tampa, Fla.-based Silk Greenhouse
Inc., a budding retail chain of artificial flowers whose stock
traded as high as $16 a share after intially selling at $11.
   ``The market saw it as a new, unique retailing concept,''
Robertson explained.
   In addition to providing companies with needed working capital,
going public has more subtle benefits. Entrepreneurs and small
business owners agree there is a certain ``status'' to being
publicly held.
   ``It makes a company seem much more substantial, and that's very
important to many of our customers,'' said Edward Wilner, president
of the 4-year-old Long Island software developer Software
Performance Group Inc.
   ``It conveys the impression we're here to stay, and it's
important to original investors to have a mechanism for cashing in
on their investment,'' said Wilner, who saw his own plans to issue
stock delayed by three months. Software Performance currently is
scheduled to go public in September rather than June.
   Wilner noted that the small size of the offering _ the company
is seeking to raise only between $2 million and $3 million _ helped
insulate it from post-crash queasiness.
   ``There are still underwriters and investment bankers that need
to make a living,'' Wilner noted. Ironically, he found the crash
``actually left us with an opportunity ... because there are not a
lot of companies left to do an offering, and a strong company that
is set up properly actually is more attractive now.''
   Indeed, for venture capitalists who often specialize in
early-stage financing, business is busy.
   ``We're looking at more, we're traveling more, but we're being
discriminatory,'' Orland said.
   While investors may not be attracted by the potential of
handsome returns that go hand-in-hand with speculative deals,
venture capitalists have before them some significantly undervalued
companies.
   ``People ask if the market window (for financing) is open or
shut, but the market really is like a filter,'' Robertson
explained. ``After the crash, the market is tougher and the filter
is finer, but `fine' companies, if you will, the really good
companies can get through. There's billions out there.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday May 29</NOTE>
