<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Banks 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0668</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with 12 grafs with testimony today, picking up 7th pvs,
Seidman in; trims for length.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators and senators today offered
a cautiously upbeat view of the prospects for a rebound this year
of the nation's banks, which in 1987 suffered their worst year
since the Depression.
   The regulators, testifying before the Senate Banking Committee,
noted two longstanding problems dragging down banking as a whole:
shaky loans to Third World countries and bank failures in
southwestern states whose economies are heavily dependent on oil.
   ``There are two areas of concern,'' said the comptroller of the
currency, Robert Clarke, whose office regulates nationally
chartered banks. ``But they should not overshadow the fact that the
national banking system remains sound.''
   In the troubled southwestern states of Texas, Oklahoma and
Louisiana, which accounted for more than half of the
post-Depression record of 184 bank failures last year, ``the worst
may be over,'' he said.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., agreed that ``the picture this
year is by no means gloomy.'' But he warned that the financial
devastation in Texas could be an indication of what lies ahead if
the national economy turns downward.
   ``What haunts me is that Texas today might be the United States
tomorrow if we have a national recession,'' he said.
   L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., which insures bank deposits up to $100,000, said many banks
are prepared to withstand a short recession with few ill effects.
   He added, ``The FDIC fund is adequate to deal with any problems
we can forsee in the banking system in 1988.''
   By any measure, 1987 was a disaster for the nation's 13,650
commercial banks. The industry as a whole recorded a profit of only
$3.7 billion on $3 trillion in assets, the worst performance since
1933.
   The nation's largest banks set aside reserves in anticipation of
losses on loans to Third World countries. Nine of the 10 largest
banks in the nation and 17 of the 25 largest recorded a loss for
the year.
   Federal Reserve Board Governor H. Robert Heller said
``meaningful progress'' has been achieved on the Third World debt
problem.
   ``Leaders in a number of borrowing countries have recognized the
need to restructure their economies,'' he said.
   Seidman, in a trip to San Antonio, Texas, last week said that
Texas banks would hit bottom in 1988 and improve next year. He has
been predicting that bank failures in Texas should climb from 50 in
1987 to 70 this year, but that improvements elsewhere should hold
bank failures nationally to about the same level as last year.
   One substantial, but known, cloud on the horizon is First
Republicbank Corp. of Dallas. In March, the FDIC infused $1 billion
into banks owned by the huge holding company with the idea of
coming up with a permanent rescue package within six months.
   The ailing giant likely will cause the insurance fund, which
stood at $18.3 billion at the end of 1987, to register its first
loss in its 55-year history.
   According to an audit of the FDIC released last month by the
General Accounting Office, an investigating arm of Congress, bank
profits probably will improve despite a continued high level of
bank failures and ``continuing and long-term'' problems presented
by Third World debt.
   Last month, 12 of the 15 largest bank holding companies reported
increased earnings for the first quarter of this year.
   The banking committee hearing today is the second session on the
condition of U.S. financial institutions. The first last week
reviewed the state of savings institutions, where much of Congress'
attention has been focused.
   Compared with banks, the 3,120 federally insured thrifts are in
much worse shape as a whole, posting a $6.8 billion loss last year.
The S&L insurance fund has been hard-pressed to cope with mounting
insolvencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
