   Stock prices continued to edge higher today, but
the market showed no signs of a broad-based rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.80 to 1,969.33 in
the first 2{ hours of trading as trading remained thin.
   Gainers outnumbered losers 9 to 5 in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 803 issues up, 446 down and
519 unchanged.
   Aside from trading related to dividend captures, the volume was
about even with Tuesday's light dealings.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 68.32 million shares as of noon
on Wall Street, compared to 81.21 million at the same time Tuesday,
when there was heavy dividend-related trading.
   Analysts say the stock market will not make a healthy advance
until volume increases. On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 21.05 points in thin trading.
   Investors have been preoccupied with high interest rates and the
possibility that they could go still higher.
   High interest rates hurt Wall Street by cutting into the
corporate profits that support stock prices, and by causing
investors to take money from stocks and put it into high-yielding
debt instruments.
   Interest rates may go higher in the short term, but they are
likely to decline in the longer term because it will become
apparent that the economy is not overheating, Neil Eigen, senior
vice president of Integrated Resources Management, said today.
   ``The economy is not booming and rates will not go a lot
higher,'' Eigen said. When rates fall, he said, ``I think stocks
can go a lot higher.''
   In economic news, the government said the merchandise trade
deficit on a balance of payments basis narrowed to $35.95 billion
in the first quarter from $41.19 billion in the fourth quarter.
   Utah Power & Light, which headed the list of most actively
traded issues, was up [ at 30} with more than 4 million shares
traded. Big traders, mainly Japanese, buy the stock to capture its
dividend and then quickly sell it back.
   West Point-Pepperell was up 4\ to 35|. The company said Farley
had filed for federal clearance to acquire between 15 percent and
25 percent of its common shares.
   Financial companies advanced across the board. Among actively
traded issues, Citicorp was up ] at 22~ and Federal National
Mortgage Association was up 1 at 38. Also advancing were Bank
America, up \ to 10], J.P. Morgan, up } to 35], and Chemical Bank,
up ] to 27{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.59 to 144.12. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.37 at 290.89.
