<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Embezzlement, 1st Ld-Writethru,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Says All Funds Returned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS grammar in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the First National Bank of Chicago
say the bank has recovered the last of the nearly $70 million
embezzled in a fund transfer scheme.
   The remaining funds, totaling $19.8 million, were returned by
the Chase Manhattan Bank in New York, along with $37,046 in
interest payments, officials said Tuesday.
   The money was transferred electronically May 13, by those
involved in the alleged embezzlement from First National Bank to
accounts of Austrian-based Focobank, at Chase in New York.
   As part of the scheme, an additonal $49 million allegedly was
wired to accounts of another Austrian bank, Creditanstalt, at
Citibank in New York.
   Government prosecutors said Creditanstalt, through Citibank,
previously returned the $49 million.
   Seven men, including two First Chicago employees, were charged
last week with attempting to defraud the bank.
   With the return of the money, First National said it hs dropped
a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in New York against Chase,
Focobank and the seven defendants accused of fraud.
</TEXT>
