<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Japanese     05-25 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Japanese,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fujitsu Earnings Up 94.9 Percent; Sony Up 46.8 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujitsu Ltd., Japan's biggest computer maker, said Wednesday its
consolidated earnings jumped 94.9 percent in its latest fiscal year
while Sony Corp. reported a 46.8 percent earnings gain.
   Fujitsu said it had a profit of 42.1 billion yen, or $336.9
million, in the fiscal year ended March 31, up from 21.6 billion
yen in the previous year.
   Revenue rose 14.4 percent to 2,047 billion yen, or $16.4
billion, from 1,789 billion yen a year earlier.
   Fujitsu's earnings are consolidated to include the results of
overseas subsidiaries and partly owned companies. Dollar totals
were based on an exchange rate of 125 yen to the dollar.
   In addition to making computers, Fujitsu is one of the world's
largest producers of telecommunications systems, semiconductors and
other electronic equipment.
   Sony said its consolidated profit was 36.7 billion yen, or
$293.9 million, in the fiscal year ended March 31, up from 25.0
billion yen in the previous fiscal year.
   Revenue rose 10.5 percent to 1,431 billion yen, or $11.4
billion, from 1,295 billion yen a year earlier.
   Sony said it achieved its stronger results, despite the adverse
effects of the strong yen, through aggressive marketing,
introduction of new products and improvements in its overseas
operations.
   Sony also reported dollar totals on the basis of 125 yen to the
dollar.
</TEXT>
