<DOCNO> AP880525-0352 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IBM-Chips     05-25 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IBM-Chips,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Slicing Chips From Biggest Wafers Yet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Wednesday it has begun making computer chips from the biggest
wafers in the industry _ platters that are 8 inches across, or
about the size of a flying disk.
   Most semiconductor manufacturers use wafers that are 4 to 6
inches across. IBM said the bigger wafers permit cost reduction and
higher productivity.
   A wafer is like a pancake that is sliced out of a log of
carefully grown silicon. After being imprinted with circuit
designs, the wafer is diced into individual chips.
   IBM said the 8-inch wafers, now used in volume production in
Essex Junction, Vt., can yield up to 450 chips vs. 150 chips for
the old 5-inch wafers. It is being used on the company's
state-of-the-art million-bit memory chips.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
