<DOCNO> AP880525-0353 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Soviet-Computers     05-25 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Computers,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silicon Valley Firm Says Pact Not Reached In Soviet Computer Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Silicon Valley company Wednesday
toned down an earlier announcement that it had reached an agreement
with the Soviet Union to assemble and sell thousands of
American-designed personal computers in the Soviet Union.
   Televideo Systems Inc., parent company of Advanced Transducer
Devices, said that a final agreement has not been reached on all
important points of the deal, which it had announced Monday.
   In addition, Televideo said California Microelectronics Inc.
would have a minority interest in the American half of the
partnership, with Advanced Transducer Devices owning a majority
interest in the firm.
   Televideo Systems had not previously mentioned California
Microelectronics' involvement.
   The Soviets would be represented by V-O Electronorgtechnica, an
electronics trading company.
   Televideo also backed down from a conjecture in a previous press
release that the joint venture, with proper nourishing, could grow
into ``a PC giant, on a par with IBM and Apple.''
   Advanced Transducer Devices, which makes components for personal
computers, had said the joint venture expected to sell at least
4,000 personal computers in the first year. The computers would be
for use in schools, factories and offices, but not the military.
   Televideo said it was optimistic a final agreement would be
reached within the next few months, but it also emphasized that the
transaction remains subject to approval by Advanced Transducer
Devices and Elorg. Actual sales of the computer components are also
subject to U.S. government approval.
   The company, in a news release, said that ATD's sales have
increased from $300,000 in 1985 to $8.6 million through the six
months ended April 30, 1988.
   Advanced Transducer Devices would need an export license from
the Department of Commerce before shipping any computers,
components or technical data.
   In addition, the Department of Defense reviews export
applications for most communist countries to determine if the
product will significantly contribute to the military potential of
the importer. The State Department also makes recommendations to
the Department of Commerce when foreign policy is concerned.
</TEXT>
