<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Canada-Chinese Bjt   05-25 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Chinese, Bjt,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Chinese Fleeing to Canada and Investing Heavily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S. unless specified as Canadian. This
moved in advance. Also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese first came to Canada as cooks and
launderers in the gold rush 130 years ago. Today they're flying in
from Hong Kong with millions of dollars to invest in businesses and
real estate.
   For the large majority, Canada is a hedge against Hong Kong's
reversion to Chinese Communist sovereignty in 1997.
   While Hong Kong entrepreneurs find easy entry under Canada's
``investor immigrant'' program, hospitals in Toronto and Vancouver
in British Columbia report an increase in the number of Hong Kong
women who come to have babies because the infants automatically
become Canadian citizens.
   Other Chinese come as students and professionals.
   But the entrepreneurs and investors often get a special welcome.
   ``They have no problem flipping down 5 million dollars ($4
million) for a house because in Hong Kong it would be 20 million
($16 million),'' said Premier David Peterson of Ontario.
   One recent buyer was Stanley Ho, whose casino and ferry empire
in Hong Kong and Macao makes him one of Asia's richest men. He paid
5.5 million Canadian dollars ($4.4 million) for a 25-room mansion
on Bridle Path, Toronto's millionaire's row.
   Across the country in Vancouver, Li Ka-shing, whose companies
represent 20 percent of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, won the
bidding in April for the right to develop the choice 210-acre site
of Expo '86.
   Through his 25-year-old son, Victor, a Canadian citizen, Li
plans to spend $1.6 billion to turn the choice downtown strip into
``Pacific Place,'' a high-rise complex that will consist of a
24-hour global financial center, a 400-room hotel, manmade islands
with 10,000 housing units and a 630-berth marina.
   Li and his son also control 52 percent of Husky Oil Ltd.,
Canada's 12th largest oil company, and his Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corp. bought the ailing Bank of British Columbia this past
November.
   Officials estimate the current flow of Chinese investment at
$1.6 billion a year, half of it in real estate. Hong Kong Chinese
own one-third of the shopping malls in the Toronto suburb of
Scarborough, one of three metropolitan Chinatowns.
   Edward Hou, a Canadian-Chinese community leader, said his real
estate company deals with 100 Hong Kong investors a month.
   After the first Chinese came for the gold rush and later to work
on the construction of the Canadian Pacific Railway, Canada
discouraged further immigration by imposing a tax of $50 a head on
new arrivals. Those who stayed were denied citizenship until 1947.
   Today, 600,000 Canadians are of Chinese descent, including more
than 200,000 in Toronto and 175,000 in Vancouver.
   At any one time, 18,000 Hong Kong students are enrolled at
Canadian universities.
   Hong Kong has become the leading source of immigrants to Canada,
with 22,100 visas issued last year.
   ``I came in 1967,'' said David Lam, a 65-year-old Vancouver real
estate magnate who has donated more than $5 million to British
Columbia universities and the Sun Yat-sen Classical Chinese Garden
in Vancouver, a replica of the ancient gardens of Suzhou.
   Lam pulled off the biggest real estate deal in Vancouver's
history in 1972 and has since built a fortune as a conduit for
other Hong Kong investors.
   ``Now we're seeing more than just flight capital,'' Lam said in
an interview. ``There's a second strata of people, young
professionals who see the writing on the wall for Hong Kong and are
afraid.''
   The Chinese Communists have agreed to allow Hong Kong to
maintain its capitalist system for 50 years after the reversion of
sovereignty, but many Hong Kong Chinese are hedging against that.
   ``Canada is seen as desirable because of its political stability
and large Chinese population.'' said Andrea Eng, a Vancouver
realtor.
   Canada's ``investor immigrant'' program offers a visa in
exchange for investment of 150,000 Canadian dollars ($121,500) to
500,000 dollars ($405,000) in approved businesses.
   Government figures show Hong Kong investment under the program
totaled 776 million Canadian dollars ($628 million) last year and
created 4,500 jobs.
   Premier Peterson of Ontario said he welcomes the well-heeled
arrivals.
   ``Canada has been built by foreign capital _ over 50 percent of
our manufacturing industry is foreign-owned,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
