<HEAD>Leading Entrepreneurs Like Bush, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush swamped Michael Dukakis
for president in a straw poll of leading entrepreneurs conducted by
Inc. magazine.
   In the survey, conducted Tuesday, Bush captured 77 percent of
the votes, compared with 11 percent favoring the Massachussetts
Democrat, a statement by the magazine said Wednesday.
   Among Republican vice-presidential choices, Howard Baker
captured 23.5 percent of the vote, followed by Bob Dole, at 19.1
percent; Elizabeth Dole, at 15.7 percent; Jack Kemp, at 9.6
percent; and California Governor George Deukmejian, at 8.7 percent.
   Sen. Sam Nunn of Georga led the list of Democratic vice
presidential favorites, with 32.2 percent of the vote, followed by
former presidential candidate Al Gore, at 20 percent, and Jesse
Jackson, at 10.4 percent, Inc. said.
   The magazine polled about 600 attendees at a conference of past
and present Inc. 500 companies _ those cited as being among the
fastest-growing companies in the nation.
   Valerie Silverman, an Inc. spokeswoman, said 115 of those
attendees responded to the poll.
