<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-25 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plummet At Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed sharply lower Wednesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade after some meteorologists increased the
amount of rain in their forecasts for early next week. Grain
futures prices also fell.
   Technical factors also entered into the fray Wednesday, analysts
said. Attitudes turned bearish after an effort to push the price
for November delivery of soybeans beyond $8.08 a bushel, the
contract's lifetime high, stalled at $8.07.
   A sharp drop in cash prices for Argentine soybean meal also
weighed on the soybean complex, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``But overpowering everything else is the weather,'' he said.
``They are saying there will be more rain early next week than
previously anticipated.''
   Weather has been the dominant factor in the grain and soybean
markets since April, when government reports indicated a large 1988
soybean crop would be needed to prevent a substantial tightening of
supplies.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 8} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.41 a bushel; corn was 2 cents
to 4{ cents lower with July at $2.14} a bushel; oats were 2{ cents
to 3 cents lower with July at $1.72 a bushel; soybeans were 20{
cents to 30 cents lower with July at $7.58 a bushel.
</TEXT>
