<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KidderWorkWeek     05-25 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidder Work Week,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidder Denies Report of Four-Day Week for Traders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidder, Peabody & Co. denied a published report
Wednesday that it is considering putting some traders on a four-day
work week because of slackened activity on Wall Street.
   The Wall Street Journal quoted unidentified Kidder officials as
saying the investment firm might shift some securities traders and
some institutional sales personnel to a shorter work week during
the summer.
   A memo distributed Wednesday to all Kidder employees nationwide
said the Journal's story ``is not true.''
   Kidder Chairman Silas Cathcart and President Max Chapman Jr.
said in the memo that ``at no time has Kidder, Peabody considered
placing professional traders or sales personnel on a four-day work
week.''
   Steve Swartz, the Journal reporter who wrote the story, said he
stood by his story.
   The Journal said the move would save Kidder money by cutting
stock and bond traders' compensation in exchange for the extra day
off.
   The paper said Kidder was considering a plan to operate with at
least some traders on hand at all times while securities markets
are open.
   The Journal said such a move would be highly unusual but
reflected lethargic times on Wall Street since October's stock
market crash.
   Trading volume has been unusually low. On Monday, for example,
only 102.6 million shares traded hands on the New York Stock
Exchange, the lightest level since Thanksgiving. Bond trading also
has tapered off.
   Kidder is a unit of General Electric Corp.
</TEXT>
