<HEAD>Sales of Existing Homes Rose 4.5 Percent in April</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 4, The April increase, to CORRECT percentage
increase in price from 19.8 percent to 2 percent.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes rose 4.5 percent in
April, the biggest advance since November 1986, a real estate trade
group reported today.
   The National Association of Realtors said that existing
single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.48 million units last month, following increases of 2.5
percent in both February and March.
   Economists said increases in mortgage rates late in the month
spurred sales as potential home buyers jumped into the market out
of concern that rates would go higher.
   The April increase in sales was accompanied by a slight drop in
prices, which fell by $200 to $87,700 compared to March. However,
the resale price of a home was still 2 percent higher than a year
ago, when the median price of a home was $86,000.
   In the Northeast, sales rose 6.2 percent from March to April to
an annual rate of 690,000 units. Sales were up 5.7 percent in the
South to an annual rate of 1.3 million units while the Midwest had
a 2.3 percent increase in sales to an annual rate of 900,000.
   The West was the only region of the country to have a decline in
sales, a drop of 1.8 percent to an annual rate of 560,000 units.
</TEXT>
