<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AT&T-Olivetti     05-25 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Olivetti,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Confirms It Is Reevaluating Relationship With Olivetti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. confirmed
Wednesday it is reevaluating aspects of its relationship with Ing.
C. Olivetti & Co. SpA, the Italian partner that builds its personal
computer line.
   AT&T Chairman Robert E. Allen said Tuesday in Madrid that the
company may curtail purchases of Olivetti personal computers and
may seek another supplier.
   Allen, speaking at a news luncheon, also said the company plans
to take ``direct'' management control of its foreign operations.
   The remarks were reported Wednesday by the Wall Street Journal
and confirmed by AT&T.
   But AT&T spokeswoman Marj McKean said AT&T expects to
strengthen, not weaken, its ties with Olivetti. ``Both sides are
looking at the arrangement with a hard business eye, but a
reassessment does not automatically mean a change,'' she added.
   Olivetti currently sells AT&T minicomputers and phone switches
in Europe. Ms. McKean said she could not confirm whether Allen's
mention about taking direct management control referred to the
Olivetti relationship.
   Allen said the Olivetti review was prompted in part by changes
in currency-exchange rates and the two companies' product
portfolios, according to the Journal.
   AT&T owns 22.3 percent of Olivetti's stock. There were reports
of discord between the companies earlier this year after they
reportedly could not agree on terms for AT&T to boost its stake in
the Italian company.
   Vittorio Cassoni, hired away from Olivetti to head AT&T's
computer operations, recently returned to Olivetti as managing
director. Robert M. Kavner, the new head of AT&T's Data Systems
Group, was elected last week as an Olivetti director.
   Ms. McKean said Cassoni's return to Olivetti could help the
relationship. ``Cassoni has a clear vision of what we're doing here
and he understands our needs, and he takes that with him to
Olivetti,'' she said.
</TEXT>
