<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-25 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Futures Sink As Inflation Signals Weaken</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures prices fell broadly Wednesday on
profit-taking as fears of inflation eased and the dollar gained
strength against other currencies.
   On other markets, soybean futures plummeted and prices retreated
for an array of commodities, including grains, cotton, livestock
and meat, oils and stock-index futures.
   Prices for future delivery of platinum, which has led the
precious-metals complex in posting impressive gains this month,
dropped $11.20 per troy ounce across the board on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   The platinum contract for delivery in July settled at $579.40 a
troy ounce. July platinum rose from $515 a troy ounce at the
beginning of this month to a high of $597.50 at one point during
Tuesday's session.
   Analysts said the dollar's gains, declining commodity prices and
nervousness about Thursday's government report on the gross
national product all contributed to the fall in precious metals
prices.
   ``Mainly, there's some uncertainty as to what the GNP number is
going to be,'' said Andrea Gould, director of investments for the
Platinum Guild International in New York. ``Whenever there is
uncertainty and there are profits to be taken, they'll take their
profits.''
   The Commodity Research Bureau's index of 21 commodities, a rough
indicator of inflation, fell sharply Wednesday, which spurred
further selling of precious metals futures, analysts said.
   Nevertheless, many technical and fundamental factors suggest
platinum, gold and silver will continue to rally, analysts said.
   ``I would categorize this as a normal correction following a
meteoric advance in platinum since the beginning of the month,''
said Bernard Savakl, an analyst in New York with PaineWebber Inc.
``Nothing goes straight up like a rocket.''
   Savakl noted that warehouse stocks of gold at the Commodity
Exchange in New York fell about 185,000 troy ounces Wednesday to a
10{-year low of about 1.224 million ounces. The physical tightness
is supportive for the gold market and ``could be a prelude to an
explosive upside move this summer,'' he said.
   On the Commodity Exchange, gold settled $6.20 to $7.50 lower
with June at $454.80 a troy ounce; silver was 16.2 cents to 18.2
cents lower with May at $6.592 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply on the Chicago Board of
Trade after some meteorologists increased the amount of rain in
their forecasts for early next week.
   Technical factors also entered into the fray, analysts said.
Attitudes turned bearish after an effort to push the price for
November delivery of soybeans beyond $8.08 a bushel, the contract's
lifetime high, stalled at $8.07.
   A sharp drop in cash prices for Argentine soybean meal also
weighed on the soybean complex, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``But overpowering everything else is the weather,'' he said.
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a
six-to-10-day forecast calling for normal to above-normal rainfall
in the Midwest during the second half of next week.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 8{ cents lower with July at $3.41\ a
bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4{ cents lower with July at $2.14} a
bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 3 cents lower with July at $1.72 a
bushel; soybeans were 21{ cents to 30 cents lower with July at
$7.59 a bushel.
   Cotton futures, which are also weather-sensitive, posted steep
losses on the New York Cotton Exchange. The July contract settled
1.10 cents lower at 65.07 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange on expectations of a temporary slowdown in wholesale meat
demand.
   ``People are a little worried that the bulk of buying for the
holiday weekend is pretty much done,'' said Tom O'Hare, an analyst
in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent to .65 cent lower with June at
71.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .75 cent lower
with May at 80.95 cents a pound; hogs were .60 cent lower to .02
cent higher with June at 52.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .25 cent to 1.05 cents lower with July at 53.22 cents a pound.
   Oil futures finished nearly unchanged in dull trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents lower to 1
cent higher with July at $17.37 a barrel; heating oil was .17 cent
lower to .06 cent higher with June at 47.31 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .13 cent to .25 cent lower with June at 51.72
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled .25 point lower at 255.80.
</TEXT>
