<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Boeing-Order Bjt   05-25 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-Order, Bjt,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines Orders Up To 100 Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines announced Wednesday it
would buy up to 100 Boeing 757-200s to replace aging aircraft in
its fleet, giving the Seattle aerospace company its second
multibillion-dollar order in as many weeks.
   American officials said they were ordering 50 757s for delivery
between July 1989 and November 1991, with an option to purchase 50
more. The deal could be worth more than $4 billion to Boeing.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton said the
order substantiates Boeing's belief in a plane that had been a slow
seller since its launch a decade ago.
   ``I think most of you know that we've been probably a little
disappointed with the 757 over the years,'' Thornton said.
   ``The purchase and thereby the endorsement of the product by an
airline like American is going to be a real boost to Boeing and a
real boost to what we think is going to be a mainstay ... in the
domestic and international markets,'' he said.
   American executives said exact cost figures were proprietary,
but Robert W. Baker, American's vice president for operations, said
the order was on ``very favorable terms for American,'' with the
first 50 jets costing just over $2 billion, and the second 50 about
the same.
   Analyst Wolfgang Demisch at Union Bank of Switzerland in New
York said ``American got a very good deal'' at a price of roughly
$40 million a plane. Depending on configuration, 757s normally sell
for $41 million to $47 million each.
   Industry analysts say Boeing could be headed for its fourth
straight year of record orders, topping 1987's $20.2 billion.
Boeing has had orders for 326 aircraft so far this year, compared
with 366 ordered for all of 1987.
   Wednesday's announcement follows a May 16 firm order by
International Lease Finance Corp. of Beverly Hills, Calif., for 100
Boeing aircraft with options for 24 more. At $4.6 billion for the
124 planes, the ILFC deal was a record for Boeing.
   Several newspapers have reported that Allegis Corp., parent of
United Airlines, is considering ordering up to 60 757s worth an
estimated $2.5 billion to $2.9 billion, possibly this week. Both
Allegis and Boeing officials have declined to comment on the
reports.
   American canceled an order to buy 15 757s in 1982 because of
poor economic conditions, and Thornton said Boeing has been talking
with American about buying the new jet since.
   Baker said American's new jets will primarily replace aging
Boeing 737s and 727s in its fleet. The 194-passenger 757 jetliner,
with a range of about 3,300 miles, burns 25 percent less fuel than
comparable aircraft and will be powered by two Rolls Royce engines.
   The 50 additional planes, if ordered, would be delivered through
December 1993. In an interview with The Seattle Times last week,
American Chairman Robert Crandall said it was possible American
could order yet another 100 757s by the end of the century.
   Boeing introduced the 757 in 1978 as a high-tech, fuel-stingy
replacement for its 727 tri-jet, which went into service in 1964.
But a drop in fuel prices and airline deregulation stalled sales.
Just 239 of the jets were ordered through the end of 1987.
   So far this year, however, 90 757s have been ordered. Analysts
say higher maintenance costs for older planes, tougher airport
noise restrictions and airport congestion have brought the plane
new popularity.
   ``It was just a matter of time before the 757 would grow into
its time,'' analyst David Smith of Robert Elsworth and Co. in
Washington, D.C., said Tuesday.
   Thornton said Boeing planned to increase 757 production at its
Renton plant from four a month at present to five a month sometime
next year. However, he said, Boeing did not expect to need to hire
many new workers.
   Crandall said American chose Rolls-Royce engines for the 757
because of what he called its superior reliability over comparable
Pratt & Whitney models available. He said Pratt & Whitney undertook
a vigorous competition to gain the order but ``Rolls simply
prevailed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
