<DOCNO> AP880525-0370 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MediaGeneral     05-25 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarman Reportedly Loses Bid For Media General Board Slate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Sugarman, who earlier this year
launched a $1.8 billion takeover bid for Media General Inc.,
appears to have lost his attempt to capture three of its board
seats, the company said Wednesday.
   Preliminary results from Friday's shareholders vote show the
incumbent management nominees received more than 56 percent of the
vote, compared to 42.6 percent for Sugarman's proposed slate, Media
General President James S. Evans said in a statement.
   Evans said Media General got the early results by telephone
Wednesday afternoon from Corporation Trust Co. He said the election
inspection company told him 86 percent of Media General's total
outstanding 28 million Class A shares voted, with the incumbents
receiving 13.5 million votes and Sugarman's ticket of himself,
Harold Simmons and David Gotterer getting just under 10.3 million
votes.
   Sugarman, in responding to the Media General announcement, noted
his slate's vote total and said, ``We fully expect that Media
General's management and their board of directors will respect the
opinion of this large group of shareholders and initiate action
that will maximize shareholder value.''
   Sugarman was referring to his battle for management acceptance
for his $70-a-share bid for Media General.
   Evans said a final report on the vote would not be made until
both sides have had an opportunity to inspect shareholder proxies
and to raise any questions with Corporation Trust.
   The family of Media General Chairman D. Tennant Bryan owns 71
percent of the company's controlling Class B shares, which
represent seven of the 10 board seats.
   Sugarman, a California-based investor with 10 percent of Media
General's Class A holdings, launched the takeover bid in February
with a $61.50-per-share offer that he later boosted to $70.
Subsequently, he and two associates challenged three
Bryan-supported directors seeking re-election to the board's three
Class A seats.
   In the weeks leading up to Friday's shareholders meeting,
lawyers for both sides went to court seeking injunctions to stop
the opposition from delivering what they characterized as false and
misleading information to shareholders about the proxy battle.
   U.S. District Judge Richard L. Williams denied both parties'
motions, saying the proper time to file them would be after the
annual meeting.
   Media General owns several daily newspapers, including the
Richmond Times-Dispatch and Richmond News Leader, as well as
several weekly papers, television stations and cable operations.
   Sugarman is the chairman and chief executive officer of Barris
Industries Inc., a producer of television programs, and Giant Group
Ltd., whose holdings including cement businesses.
</TEXT>
