<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RailPurchase     05-25 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Purchase,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX, P&LE Agree On $59 Million Rail Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An understanding has been reached in a
$59 million deal that would create an independent railroad owned by
former employees of the Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad,
officials said Wednesday.
   Under the deal, CSX Transportation and the Railway Labor
Executive's Association would buy P&LE's business and some of its
assets, said John W. Snow, president and chief operating officer of
CSX Transportation, one of the nation's largest freight railroads.
   CSX Transportation is a subsidiary of CSX Corp., which is also
involved in energy, technology and real estate. CSX Transportation,
based in Jacksonville, operates 21,000 route miles of railroad in
the eastern half of the United States and the province of Ontario,
Canada.
   ``While we have reached this understanding, there are
significant issues yet to be resolved,'' Snow said. He did not
specify what the issues are.
   The plan calls for the business to be operated by a new company
that will buy nearly all of P&LE's right-of-way and about 1,700
freight cars for $59 million. The purchase will be financed by CSX
Transportation.
   Completion of the deal depends on approval by local labor
groups, the CSX board of directors and the Interstate Commerce
Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
