<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Minstar-Jacobs     05-25 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minstar-Jacobs,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jacobs Group Sweetens Offer To Take Minstar Private</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group led by takeover
specialist Irwin Jacobs on Wednesday sweetened its offer to take
Minstar Inc. private.
   Jacobs' group, I.J. Holdings Corp., said it is offering $26.50
in cash and a $5 note for each of Minstar's 11.4 million
outstanding common shares, giving the deal a value of about $400
million if all shares are tendered.
   The group, which owns 56 percent of Minstar's stock, would leave
about 1.3 million shares in the company as equity, said Ken
Severinson, Minstar president. The tender offer is expected to
begin June 2.
   Minstar is a diversified company that consists of several boat
manufacturers, other sporting goods businesses and Bekins Co.
   The deal has the backing of an independent committee of
Minstar's board of directors, which negotiated an increase in the
$29-a-share leveraged buyout which Jacobs proposed last month,
according to Robin Young, director of research at the Minneapolis
investment firm John G. Kinnard & Co.
   In a leveraged buyout, the acquirer finances the purchase of the
target company with sales of the target's assets or from its cash
flow.
   Jacobs, the chairman of Minstar, owns about a third of the
company's shares, which are worth more than $122 million under the
terms of the offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
